<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from editorials in newspapers in the United  
States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 1  
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times, on Million Youth March:  
</P>
<P>
	The Federal District Court in New York ruled properly yesterday  
that the city's attempt to prevent the so-called Million Youth 
March violated the constitutional right to free speech. Instead of 
appealing to a higher court, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani needs to issue 
the necessary permits and concentrate on making this a safe and 
orderly gathering. To escalate the public statements and the legal 
battle would only inflame racial tensions -- and provide the 
archbigot Khallid Abdul Muhammad with free publicity and a wider 
audience. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 25  
</P>
<P>
	South County Journal, Kent, Wash., on Ken Starr:  
</P>
<P>
	Ken Starr wants to leave the independent counsel's post and has  
told a three-judge panel that he plans to leave before the end of 
the year. Given the thankless nature of the job, who can blame him? 
</P>
<P>
	However, Starr ... should stay on to see his work through to  
completion. After all, this investigation is hardly ordinary. It 
resulted in the impeachment of the president and his near-removal 
from office. 
</P>
<P>
	We could understand Starr's point if there were only loose ends  
left and subordinates could wrap up the loose ends and edit the 
final report. But Starr won't say if that's the case and has 
declined to tell the three-judge panel what, if any, significant 
prosecutions remain. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr has said that he expected the investigation and the final  
report to be done by November 2000. We would hope it is a lot 
sooner than that. It would be better if it ended before the end of 
this year. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 30  
</P>
<P>
	Press-Journal, Vero Beach, Fla., on Warren Beatty's presidential  
quest: 
</P>
<P>
	Warren Beatty, best known to date for his moviemaking, is  
hinting that he may become a presidential candidate, and without 
having first obtained the sort of credential that Hollywood's 
Ronald Reagan took time to garner: an eight-year stint as 
California governor. 
</P>
<P>
	This is an era when anybody runs for president, sometimes just  
to espouse some ideal or policy while also hoping, no doubt, that 
lightning will strike. So, despite many, many jokes, why not 
Beatty? ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 31  
</P>
<P>
	Las Cruces (N.M.) Sun-News, on offering clemency to terrorists:  
</P>
<P>
	Why would anyone be given clemency after being convicted of  
terrorism, especially a group of terrorists? 
</P>
<P>
	The one sure message that should be sent in this country is that  
the penalties for those found guilty of terrorism will be harsh and 
that the full term of their sentences should be carried out. 
Otherwise, the wrong message is being sent. 
</P>
<P>
	That, unfortunately, is what President Clinton is doing by  
offering conditional clemency to 16 members of a Puerto Rican 
terrorist group known as the Armed Forces for National Liberation 
(FALN), an organization behind 130 bomb attacks on civilian and 
military targets from 1974 to 1983. Those attacks, according to an 
Associated Press report, killed six people and wounded dozens. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The widely talked about suspicion is that Clinton is taking this  
questionable action because Puerto Rican leaders in New York want 
it, and as a result it might help his wife Hillary with Puerto 
Rican voters in her planned run for the U.S. Senate from New York. 
The timing of all this certainly leads to that perception. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The terrorists should serve out their full sentences as a  
message to others of their ilk. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 30  
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Globe, on demise of Mir:  
</P>
<P>
	For a space station plagued with problems, Russia's Mir has run  
up a respectable record that ended Saturday with the return of its 
last regular crew to earth. Mir's fate, to be settled next year 
when it is incinerated while plunging into the atmosphere above the 
Pacific Ocean, will be merely the mechanical aftermath of a major 
human achievement. 
</P>
<P>
	Mir, launched more than 13 years ago, was expected to serve for  
five years. Its impressive longevity had its counterparts in the 
prolonged space duty of some of its crew members, including one who 
all told spent more than a year on Mir. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Mir added enormously to the store of knowledge about prolonged  
space flight, which will be critical to the next big undertaking -- 
the international space station in which Russian, American, and 
other participants will work closely together. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 1  
</P>
<P>
	The State, Columbia, S.C., on protecting state's habitat:  
</P>
<P>
	Looking forward to the new millennium, the board of the state  
Natural Resources Department took a welcome step ... by voting 
unanimously to make habitat protection its top priority. This means 
that DNR, which owns and manages 159,262 acres of unspoiled, 
natural areas at about 140 sites around the state, will be focusing 
on protecting that and other land from development. ... 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, DNR's focus has been mainly on making sure its land  
is managed properly for hunters and people who fish. The agency 
does this with a $65 million budget and 1,000 employees. ... 
</P>
<P>
	DNR's new priority is a sign of commitment to the environment by  
Gov. Jim Hodges, who appointed a new board earlier this year. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution is only a first step. DNR says it will be  
developing an inventory of its sensitive lands, making plans to 
acquire more lands and creating public-private partnerships to 
preserve land. Right now, however, those plans are only 
well-meaning wishes. Unless DNR devotes staff power, time, energy 
and money to this priority, the resolution won't be worth the paper 
it is written on. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 29  
</P>
<P>
	Akron (Ohio) Beacon Journal, on Attorney General Janet Reno:  
</P>
<P>
	There's more that should concern Janet Reno than her own  
credibility. The attorney general should be worried about public 
confidence in the country's top investigative agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of the fire at the Branch Davidian compound in Waco,  
Texas, on April 19, 1993, officials of the Justice Department and 
the Federal Bureau of Investigation denied any role in the fire 
that killed 80 members of the cult. They insisted that no 
pyrotechnic tear-gas canisters had been used during the FBI assault 
that aimed to end the 51-day standoff at the compound. 
</P>
<P>
	Disclosures last week from an FBI inventory of weapons used that  
day indicate, however, that agents, in fact, had used pyrotechnic 
tear-gas canisters at the compound. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's explanation of the contradiction is that the  
canisters had been used six hours before at a bunker 100 yards away 
from the main building where the fire started. That may, indeed, be 
the truth, but what reason would anyone have now, after six years 
of denials, to trust the word of the bureau or the Justice 
Department? 
</P>
<P>
	Reno announced in 1993 that the buck stopped with her. If there  
is a time to order a truly thorough and independent investigation, 
this is it. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 27  
</P>
<P>
	The Intelligencer, Wheeling, W.Va., on the Superfund:  
</P>
<P>
	Talk about toxic waste: How about hundreds of millions of  
dollars a year fed into a cesspool of attorneys and bureaucrats 
rather than into the environmental clean-up work for which the 
money was intended? That's the federal government's ``Superfund'' 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of ``Superfund,'' noting that it has been in existence  
for nearly a generation but has managed to clean up fewer than 200 
sites where toxic waste was discovered, say it's time to tear the 
program apart and start all over. 
</P>
<P>
	According to estimates by the General Accounting Office, less  
than half of the $1.5 billion a year spent by ``Superfund'' 
actually goes to clean up toxic waste sites. Most of the money goes 
for ``support'' functions such as lawyers and other administrative 
functions. Meanwhile, more than 1,200 waste sites throughout the 
country remain to be cleaned up. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``Superfund'' can't even do a quick, inexpensive, effective  
cleanup job on a toxic waste site, much less on itself. Congress 
should step in and chuck ``Superfund'' into a garbage can, then 
draft a new law that may give Americans some reason to have 
confidence that their government isn't wasting their money. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 31  
</P>
<P>
	The Sun, London, on anniversary of death of Princess Diana:  
</P>
<P>
	It is two years to the day since Diana died. Yet flowers and  
tributes laid outside the gates of her London home show the people 
still mourn the People's Princess. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of us will take time out today to remember a remarkable  
woman, and how she touched so many lives for the better. 
</P>
<P>
	Then we wish for three things:  
</P>
<P>
	That the official report into her death dispels forever wild  
conspiracy theories. 
</P>
<P>
	That the Diana fund starts to pay out for good causes some of  
the millions collected. 
</P>
<P>
	And that rats like James Hewitt put the welfare of her sons  
before their money-grubbing. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, finally, Diana may be able to truly rest in peace.  

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 1  
</P>
<P>
	Daily Telegraph, London, on anniversary of death of Princess  
Diana: 
</P>
<P>
	Two years on from the sudden death of Diana, the Princess of  
Wales, there is plainly a public feeling that somewhere soon there 
should be a permanent memorial to her. ... It might help to get 
things moving in accordance with public wishes if certain 
misconceptions were removed. The royal family does not erect 
statues to themselves or anyone else. To lay blame in that quarter 
for failure to get anything moving, as certain protagonists for a 
memorial have been doing, is there wholly to misrepresent the 
position. Nor is it right to assert that the absence of a memorial 
means that Diana has been ``shamefully forgotten.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course the mourning of two years ago has diminished;  
mercifully, the passage of time does relieve nearly all 
bereavements. It does not follow that people have been forgotten. 
There will, furthermore, always be people who are critical of the 
princess and regard tributes to her as tantamount to disloyalty to 
the monarchy. That certainly should not stand in the way of 
devising the sort of permanent memorial that most of the public 
would like to see. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 31  
</P>
<P>
	Corriere della Sera, Rome, on English reaction to anniversary of  
death of Princess Diana: 
</P>
<P>
	Few flowers, a half-empty museum, unsold souvenirs. No flag at  
half mast, no commemoration. Listless recollections in the 
newspapers. The anniversary of the disappearance of the Princess of 
Wales is a weary one. 
</P>
<P>
	When she left two years ago, we all thought she was only moving  
from a tunnel in Paris to the heavens of the great myths, where 
Marilyn Monroe, James Dean, and John Lennon were waiting for her. 
That wasn't the case: In a short time, the myth of Diana seems to 
have evaporated. ... 
</P>
<P>
	What happened? Two things, probably.  
</P>
<P>
	The first is obvious. She wasn't a diva of cinema or a rock  
star. She was Queen of the news, and the news is a furnace that 
burns and leaves nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	However, something else happened. Remember the day of Diana's  
funeral. There was nothing English about it. There were tears and 
wailing, gifts and flowers, regrets and promises. ... 
</P>
<P>
	There is a melancholy consistency in the way the English are  
forgetting Diana. They were a race of cold blood and long memories. 
They are becoming a people of warm blood and short-lived memories. 
Welcome to Europe, we might say. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 31  
</P>
<P>
	The Australian, Sydney, on East Timor's independence ballot:  
</P>
<P>
	The relief that yesterday's poll passed relatively peacefully  
does not mean an end to anxiety in East Timor. The votes have yet 
to be counted. Presumably, the general population will have some 
idea, before the official result is announced, of the result. The 
high turnout of voters and relative calm of the poll suggest that 
the result may well be rejection of the proposal for autonomy 
within Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the result, there has always been a possibility of  
post-poll violence, fueled by the anger of the disappointed 
factions and the possibility of victors' retribution. Before the 
poll, the performance of the Indonesian military and police in 
meeting their responsibility for maintaining law and order was 
seriously deficient, and improved only after severe international 
criticism. After the poll, Indonesia's responsibility for keeping 
the peace remains. If, as seems likely, the vote is for 
independence, the responsibility on Indonesia will be even greater. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 1  
</P>
<P>
	Yediot Ahronot daily, Tel Aviv, Israel, on efforts to stop  
terrorism: 
</P>
<P>
	Yesterday, all kinds of strange leaks attributed to the prime  
minister's office surfaced, saying that if it became clear that the 
murder (of an Israeli couple on the border of Israel and the West 
Bank over the weekend) was politically motivated, the signing 
ceremony for the Israeli-Palestinian agreement, if an agreement is 
reached, would be postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it becomes clear that the killing was a terrorist act  
committed by opponents of the peace process, we cannot allow an act 
like this to obstruct the negotiations for peace and reconciliation 
between the two nations. 
</P>
<P>
	We need to remember that it is particularly now that ... we are  
witnessing a three-way effort among Israel, the Palestinian 
Authority and Jordan to destroy Islamic terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	The major development of the last few days is Jordan actively  
signing on (to efforts to stop militants). 
</P>
<P>
	King Abdullah demonstrated this week even stronger determination  
than his father ... and the steps he took are more forceful and 
effective than in the past. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 30  
</P>
<P>
	The Jordan Times, Amman, on U.S. and pope's visit to Mideast:  
</P>
<P>
	Washington is voicing opposition even to the thought of Pope  
John Paul II visiting Iraq as part of his tour to biblical sites in 
the Middle East region on the occasion of the advent of the third 
Millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the U.S. looks dimly at the prospect of the visit ... for  
fear that the Iraqi regime would exploit such a high-profile visit 
by the leader of the Roman Catholic Church. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the U.S. doesn't want the truth about the dire effects  
of sanctions on the Iraqi people, especially on their children, to 
be further documented for the whole international community to hear 
and see. How else can one explain the opposition to the visit of 
the Pope, the assistants of members of the U.S. Congress and other 
groups of people whose only agenda is to get at the truth behind 
the sanctions against Iraq and its people? 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 1  
</P>
<P>
	South China Morning Post, Hong Kong, on East Timor:  
</P>
<P>
	Yesterday morning, when reports came in of a 98.6 percent  
turnout in the East Timor election, and -- one tragic stabbing of a 
UN official aside -- none of the violence that has permeated life 
there for more than two decades, it seemed possible to hope that 
the calm on the streets set the standard for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	But, perhaps to no one's surprise, Monday proved a false dawn.  
...
</P>
<P>
	The atmosphere of order that prevailed on polling day suggested  
that the authorities are capable of maintaining the peace when the 
eyes of the world are on them; and while they are mindful of U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's hint that international loans might dry up 
if there was bloodshed on polling day. That pressure must be 
maintained for the foreseeable future. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 1  
</P>
<P>
	Neue Zuercher Zeitung, Zurich, Switzerland, on the Congo crisis:  
</P>
<P>
	If it takes a long time, it will end up being good -- or not. We  
are only too happy to believe that the rebel Congolese Rally for 
Democracy's belated formal yes to the Lusaka cease-fire agreement 
is an important step on the road to a lasting peace in Congo; that 
it will see an end to the civil war there which threatens to burn 
the whole of central Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	A glance at the reality and at events in Congo will serve to  
subdue the high expectations. Signatures alone do not create peace, 
as has been proved by the latest fighting between troops from 
Uganda and Rwanda -- both signatories to the Lusaka agreement in 
July. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 31  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun, Tokyo, on North Korea:  
</P>
<P>
	We should not lose sight of the fact that North Korea's  
continued missile development increases tension in relations 
between North Korea and the United States as well as the situation 
in the Korean Peninsula, and increases the possibility of an 
escalated arms race in East Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea is trying to earn hard currency by exporting its  
missiles to get over its economic crisis and its food shortages, 
and hopes to extract aid from the United States using the missile 
development and suspected nuclear development as leverage. North 
Korea's approach is a form of brinkmanship with the goal of 
preserving the present political regime. 
</P>
<P>
	Without some change in North Korea's posture, there can be no  
hope of a genuine solution to the missile problem. We must consider 
how to encourage and hasten, in cooperation with the international 
community, needed changes in North Korea's policy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
