<DOCNO> APW19990902.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 07:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Service Settles Tree Paint Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A worker advocacy group says it has settled a  
suit against the U.S. Forest Service over the past use of oil-based 
paint that workers had blamed for giving them flu-like symptoms and 
placing them at greater risk of miscarriages. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service has agreed to use water-based paint for tree  
marking -- not oil-based paint -- for the next three years under the 
settlement, according to the Forest Service Employees for 
Environmental Ethics, which had sued the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also agreed to give the Eugene, Ore.-based group  
specifications of the water-based paint when they become available 
and promised to advise the group in advance of any change in paint 
specifications in the next three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service also agreed to pay $5,000 for covering legal  
costs to the group, which includes 500 Forest Service employees and 
13,000 other members. 
</P>
<P>
	Forest Service officials did not return telephone calls  
requesting a comment on the settlement announced by the advocacy 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal health study completed last year concluded that  
hundreds of female employees at the Forest Service who worked with 
herbicides or special paint used to mark trees for logging were at 
an increased risk of miscarriage. 
</P>
<P>
	But the National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health  
study stopped short of blaming the paint for miscarriages or other 
health problems. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 09:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANDOVER, Md. (AP) -- The crowd is on its feet, stage lights  
swirl overhead and the young singer leaps across the stage 
chanting, ``Have the people had enough?'' 
</P>
<P>
	They haven't; the audience screams its approval.  
</P>
<P>
	If this sounds like a rock concert, it's actually a special  
service at the 10,000-seat Jericho City of Praise church in this 
Washington, D.C. suburb, one of several mammoth churches throughout 
the country to embrace professional musicians and artists as one 
way to lure people wary of the traditional tones of organized 
religion. 
</P>
<P>
	On a recent Saturday night at Jericho, more than 10,000 people  
waited nearly three hours in the summer heat for a gospel concert. 
Thousands more were turned away. 
</P>
<P>
	Once inside, the crowd seldom sat down as artists performed with  
a backdrop of stage smoke, bright lights and choirs. 
</P>
<P>
	More and more churches are sponsoring concerts, hiring musicians  
for Sunday services and even placing some artists on staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``They recognize this is one of the ways they not only minister  
to their flock spiritually but also to their entertainment needs,'' 
said Frank Breedon, president of the Nashville-based Gospel Music 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	With the swelling popularity of gospel and Christian music,  
dozens of congregations have evolved into ``megachurches'' with 
thousands of members. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a lifestyle marketing approach that these churches  
have gone to,'' Breedon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Anderson, program director at the Washington gospel music  
radio station WPGC-AM, has also seen a trend of churches ``having 
recording artists as ministers of music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You know the person is committed to the church, but they are  
also committed to their music ministry,'' Anderson said. ``You're 
getting top quality, and that in itself tends to generate 
excitement amongst parishioners ... .'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Washington area, award-winning Gospocentric artist Byron  
Cage heads the music ministry at Ebenezer AME Church in Fort 
Washington, Md. Verity Records' Richard Smallwood, a Grammy award 
winner and composer, is at Metropolitan Baptist Church in downtown 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	At West Angeles Church of God in Christ in Los Angeles, artist  
Kurt Carr is the creative director. 
</P>
<P>
	Before climbing the charts to musical stardom, Grammy winner  
Kirk Franklin, who is credited with taking gospel music from its 
traditional tones to a more hip-hop sound, was the music minister 
at a Texas church. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Recording Industry Association of America,  
gospel music sales grew 40 percent last year. ``Gospel is now 
larger than jazz, classical and New Age combined,'' Breedon said. 
</P>
<P>
	But gospel is not the only hot music in churches.  
</P>
<P>
	In Houston, the 25,000-member Second Baptist Church serves as  
home to Caedmon's Call, a seven-member Christian rock band. 
Parishioners are treated to the group's sounds every Sunday night 
as the band leads the services. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think us being there has definitely helped with the  
growth,'' said vocalist and guitarist Cliff Young, whose father, 
the Rev. Ed Young, is pastor of Second Baptist. 
</P>
<P>
	Several years ago the elder Young began an artist-in-residence  
program at the church for professional touring musicians. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'd say, 'Play in service whenever you're in town and we'll  
help you,' '' Cliff Young recalled. ``My dad has always been 
supportive of musicians. A lot of churches were not into that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cage, one of the artists performing at the recent Jericho  
service and the minister for church worship and music 
administration at the 12,000-member Ebenezer AME Church, said 
having professional artists in service can contribute something 
special. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Earth belongs to the Lord,'' he said, ``why can't we  
use strobe lights?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Having professional performers ``creates an excitement. They  
(parishioners) don't know what to expect,'' said Cage, whose staff 
at Ebenezer includes two other recorded gospel artists, Patrick 
Lundy and Stephen Hurd. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent Ebenezer services have featured such performers as Bebe  
Winans, Yolanda Adams, Karen Clark-Sheard and Dottie Peoples. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll travel all over the country the other six days of the  
week, but on Sunday morning they're at their church in place and 
ready to minister,'' Anderson said of such artists. 
</P>
<P>
	And parishioners seem to appreciate their efforts. Said Cage:  
``Those people who never came to church before are flocking now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Maryland Teen Admits To Strangling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Unflinching and stone-faced, a Maryland  
teen-ager told an Israeli court today that he strangled an 
acquaintance with a rope in the United States in 1997, then 
dismembered and burned the body. 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel Sheinbein's confession came as part of a plea bargain  
under which he will serve 24 years in an Israeli prison. The deal 
was leaked last month by angry U.S. prosecutors who felt the 
sentence was too lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein, 19, fled to Israel shortly after the killing of  
Alfredo Tello Jr. in September 1997 and successfully fought 
extradition. The case strained relations between Israel and the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Sheinbein stared ahead as Tel Aviv District Court Judge  
Uri Oren read from the indictment, which said Tello was killed by 
Sheinbein and an accomplice, Aaron Needle, who hanged himself in a 
U.S. jail while awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The accused and Needle brutally attacked Tello by strangling  
him with a rope around his neck and hitting him with a blunt 
instrument to the head several times,'' the judge read from the 
indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Turning to the defendant, Oren asked whether this was true.  
Sheinbein, showing no emotion, stood up and answered ``ken,'' using 
the Hebrew word for yes. The proceedings were in Hebrew, but were 
translated into English for Sheinbein. 
</P>
<P>
	Oren then convicted Sheinbein of premeditated murder.  
</P>
<P>
	Under the plea bargain, which must be formally approved in an  
Oct. 11 court session, Sheinbein would be eligible for parole after 
16 years, likely including the two years he has already spent in 
custody in Israel. He would also be eligible for weekend furloughs 
after six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein fled to Israel shortly after Tello's body was found in  
an empty garage near Sheinbein's home in Aspen Hill, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Claiming Israeli citizenship through his father, the U.S.-born  
Sheinbein successfully blocked his return to the United States, 
seeking refuge under a law that bars the extradition of Israeli 
citizens for trial abroad. Sheinbein had little connection to 
Israel, except for a few visits as a child. 
</P>
<P>
	The killing and Sheinbein's flight raised a furor among  
Maryland's Hispanic organizations and Latino community. U.S. 
authorities expressed anger at Sheinbein's manipulation of the 
system, and some U.S. lawmakers threatened to cut aid to Israel if 
Sheinbein was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's Justice Ministry fought all the way to the Supreme  
Court to get Sheinbein extradited, but the court upheld Sheinbein's 
citizenship and set the stage for the trial to take place in 
Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein initially entered a not guilty plea, and the attorney  
general's staff -- seeking to avoid a lengthy, costly trial -- began 
negotiating a plea bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli prosecutors initially defended the deal by saying a  
24-year sentence is the longest that can be imposed in Israel on a 
minor. At the time of the killing, Sheinbein was 17. 
</P>
<P>
	However, lawyers in the case said today that Sheinbein was  
already an adult when he was indicted and could have faced life in 
prison, though such a sentence is rarely imposed in criminal murder 
cases in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	In Maryland, the prosecutor who would have had jurisdiction over  
the case called it ``a miscarriage of justice'' that Sheinbein was 
punished in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery County state's attorney Doug Gansler said he had  
spoken with the Tello family last week. He described the family as 
``resigned, frustrated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long legal process that they do not understand and  
are not going to understand -- because there is no understanding 
it,'' Gansler said. ``If you look at it from a global view, what 
seems right, what seems wrong, it's wrong. It's a miscarriage of 
justice. He should have been tried here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
