<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Bush Says Don't Aid Bad Schools  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate George W.  
Bush said today that federal funds should be confiscated from the 
worst-performing schools and made available to parents for private 
education, tutoring or ``whatever offers hope.'' Under the Texas 
governor's plan, every school getting the Title I money would be 
required to test its impoverished students on basic academics each 
year. After three years of no progress, the Title I money would be 
matched with other federal education money and given to the state, 
which would set up an education account -- about $1,500 a year -- for 
each affected student. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., China Set Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and Chinese officials will hold trade  
talks next week for the first time since the accidental NATO 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. The move clears the way 
for a meeting between President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin. Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher said today 
the technical-level meeting will be a ``stocktaking'' of where the 
two countries stand on negotiations to bring China into the World 
Trade Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	Clintons Sign N.Y. House Deal  
</P>
<P>
	CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton and his wife signed a  
contract today to buy a $1.7 million house in this New York City 
suburb, providing her the residency she needs to run for a U.S. 
Senate seat next year. The white, three-story wood frame home in 
the Westchester County town of Chappaqua was built in 1889 and 
features a swimming pool, five bedrooms, four bathrooms and two 
fireplaces. The top floor contains an exercise room. The lot, just 
over an acre, is screened by evergreens at the end of a cul-de-sac. 

</P>
<P>
	Celebration for Internet's 30th  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The computer scientists who pioneered the  
Internet today celebrated the 30th anniversary of the global 
network's first primitive connection. On Sept. 2, 1969, a small 
crowd gathered inside a lab at the University of California, Los 
Angeles to watch a test of the technology that remains the 
foundation of the Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Detroit Teachers Continue Strike  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Detroit's public teachers remained on strike for  
a fourth day today as the school district refused to back down from 
a plan to give merit bonuses to every employee of an improved 
school. But at least one concession was made when the district 
agreed to withdraw a proposal to extend the school day by 2 hours, 
to 8 1/2 hours. In return, teachers would not oppose having aides and 
other non-teaching personnel work longer days so the district could 
offer after-school programs. 

</P>
<P>
	Minor Quake Rattles N. Illinois  
</P>
<P>
	DIXON, Ill. (AP) -- An earthquake rippled through northern  
Illinois today, shaking pictures off walls and causing some 
buildings to wobble. Authorities said there were no immediate 
reports of damage or injuries from the quake, which occurred at 
11:17 a.m. and had a preliminary magnitude of 3.5, according to the 
U.S. Geological Survey. The epicenter was 10 miles south-southeast 
of Dixon, about 90 miles west of Chicago. 

</P>
<P>
	Big Board Won't Go Public This Year  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Stock Exchange is delaying plans to  
sell stock in itself until at least next year while it studies 
issues ranging from regulation to the taxation of the deal. Richard 
Grasso, the chairman of the NYSE, said earlier this summer that he 
had hoped the exchange could complete an initial public offering, 
or IPO, this fall so he could read the stock price of the Big Board 
in the newspaper on Thanksgiving morning. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks opened mixed Friday as the Nikkei  
Stock Average gained 12.42 points to 17,643.67 in the first 30 
minutes of trading. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones 
industrial average closed down 94.67 at 10,843.21, having worked 
its way back from a loss of 205 points earlier in the session. 

</P>
<P>
	First Day for New Umps Goes Smoothly  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There were no problems involving the 25 new  
umpires during this afternoon's four games. They replaced 22 
veteran umpires whose firings resulted from the union's failed 
strategy of mass resignations, designed to force an early start to 
negotiations for a contract to replace the labor deal that expires 
Dec. 31. Instead of negotiating, baseball accepted the 22 
resignations and hired 25 replacements from the minors. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
