<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Rise by 4,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits inched up last week. The Labor Department 
reported today that 289,000 Americans filed new claims for jobless 
benefits for the week ending Aug. 28, up by 4,000 from the previous 
week. That was the highest since Aug. 14, when claims matched last 
week's level. The four-week moving average for claims, which 
smoothes out week-to-week volatility, was up to 286,500 last week. 
That was the highest level since Aug. 7, when claims were at 
288,250. 

</P>
<P>
	Productivity Report Due Today  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Labor Department issues its final report  
on second-quarter productivity at 10 a.m. EDT. A report issued in 
early August showed second-quarter productivity growing at an 
annual rate of 1.3 percent, as compared to the 3.6 percent growth 
rate in the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Report Due Today  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department reports on factory  
orders for July at 10 a.m. EDT today. Orders to factories rose 0.7 
percent in June, the 10th increase in the last 13 months. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing Machinists Approve Contract  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Machinists went to work today with a  
freshly approved contract that union members say signals a new era 
of mutual respect between company management and hourly workers. 
The pact won 86 percent approval last night, the highest ever for a 
Boeing contract, union negotiator Dick Schneider told a cheering 
crowd after the votes were tallied. The vote was 26,842 to 4,328, 
with a 71 percent turnout from the 44,000 members of the 
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers in 
Washington, Oregon and Kansas. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Prices May Drop After Holiday  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As the Labor Day weekend approaches, a series  
of sharp gasoline price spikes that have pinched motorists' 
pocketbooks since March appear to be nearing an end. That's because 
crude oil prices appear to be stable and other pressures that 
helped push gas prices upward, such as refinery breakdowns and 
higher summertime demand, are waning. After the holiday weekend, 
prices will begin to drop, said Bill Berman, a petroleum industry 
analyst and publisher of the Price Pump Report. 

</P>
<P>
	Most Asian Markets Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets closed lower today on  
various local news, with the large Tokyo market dipping slightly on 
the yen's recent strength. Tokyo's 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average 
dropped 171.23 points, or 0.96 percent, to 17,631.25. Hong Kong's 
Hang Seng Index fell 176.63 points, or 1.3 percent, to 13,367.56. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Breaks Four-Session Losing Streak  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology issues lent some strength to Wall  
Street Wednesday, driving most stocks higher and helping the Dow 
Jones industrials to their first advance in a week. The Dow rose 
108.60 to 10,937.88 after having lost 496.76 over the previous four 
sessions. The index had not closed higher since last Wednesday, 
when it rose 42.74 to an all-time high of 11,326.04. Broader stock 
indicators also gained yesterday. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 
10.66 to 1,331.07, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 11.45 to 
2,750.80. 

</P>
<P>
	Intel, IBM Move Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Intel was among the high-tech issues to revive a  
market that has sagged under interest rate concerns. The chip 
maker, up 1 1/4 yesterday to 83 7/16, led the Nasdaq and was among the 
strongest components of the S&AMP;P 500 as it unveiled a new 
microprocessor intended for use in devices that route information 
across the Internet. In a similar vein, IBM was one of the 
strongest Dow stocks, rising 2 7/16 to 127. IBM and Cisco said 
Tuesday they will jointly provide networking equipment and services 
to companies looking to do business online. 

</P>
