<DOCNO> APW19990902.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russian Rebels Driven From Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Federal forces today took control of  
a village that had been occupied by Islamic militants in southern 
Russia, and military officials said the fight against the gunmen 
would be over before the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The militants forced police and local administrators out of  
several villages in the southern republic of Dagestan last year and 
imposed a strict version of Islamic law. Russian forces began an 
offensive Sunday to drive them out. 
</P>
<P>
	The militants were driven from the village of Chabanmakhi today,  
a day after losing control of the nearby stronghold of Karamakhi, 
said Deputy Interior Minister Col Gen. Vladimir Kolesnikov. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the exact position of the militants was not known, it  
appeared that they had been expelled from all the villages they 
once occupied. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Kolesnikov said, the militants were putting up a fierce  
fight in mountains surrounding the villages. Russia continued with 
attacks from helicopter gunships as ground troops swept the areas 
they had seized. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Vyacheslav Ovchinnikov, who is commanding the Russian  
troops, said the operation against the rebels would be finished by 
Friday. He claimed that the estimated 120 remaining militants were 
surrounded and would either have to surrender or be killed. 
</P>
<P>
	NTV television news today showed Russian troops going from house  
to house in Karamakhi searching for militants. It also showed 
Russian forces firing rockets on rebel positions outside the 
village. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 25 Russians have died since the offensive began  
Sunday, Kolesnikov said. Another 143 Russians were injured, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebel losses were estimated by Russian forces at more than 100  
fighters, but that number couldn't be independently confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting is 50 miles east of where Russian troops battled  
Islamic insurgents from breakaway Chechnya in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The Karamakhi region was not involved in that round of fighting,  
which lasted for two weeks. The region is a stronghold of Islamic 
fundamentalists who have close links with their brethren in 
Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	The villages in the district -- 25 miles south of Dagestan's  
capital, Makhachkala -- have a total population of 10,000 people, 
but most civilians fled Saturday after the gunmen refused 
government demands to hand over their weapons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
