<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Surreal Comedy Gets Buzz at Venice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VENICE, Italy (AP) -- You could hear a buzz in the air on Day 2  
of the Venice Film Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie generating the stir was a quirky, surreal comedy  
called ``Being John Malkovich,'' starring -- who else? -- John 
Malkovich, directed by Spike Jonze. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, which premiered Thursday, is Jonze's first feature  
film. But he already had a cult following thanks to a string of 
award-winning music videos for the Beastie Boys, Puff Daddy, Bjork 
and REM; commercials for Coca-Cola, Nike and Nissan; and short 
films featured at several festivals, including Sundance. 
</P>
<P>
	At first blush, Jonze seems an unlikely character to generate  
excitement. Despite the hip moniker, he's a short guy with a high, 
nasal voice who wears his fair hair brushed forward a la Bill 
Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	His real name isn't even Spike Jonze; it's Adam Spiegel. And his  
movie is, at heart, about wanting to be somebody else. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being John Malkovich,'' which also stars John Cusack, Cameron  
Diaz and Catherine Keener, is funny, original and almost impossible 
to explain. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the action takes place in the offices of the fictional  
Lester Corp. on the 7 1/2th floor of a New York office building with 
ceilings so low everyone walks around hunched over. To get there, 
you have to stop the elevator between two floors and use a crowbar 
to pry open the doors. 
</P>
<P>
	The office turns out to have a secret door, a portal into John  
Malkovich's head. Go through the door and -- presto! -- you're John 
Malkovich for 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The real John Malkovich says the story has very little to do  
with him. In fact, he joked at a standing-room-only news conference 
Thursday that being John Malkovich ``is less fun than you might 
imagine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the characters in the movie, however, being John Malkovich  
is a chance to realize their desires. These characters include a 
puppeteer played by Cusack, his wife, played by Diaz, and Cusack's 
vampish co-worker, played by Keener. There is also a chimpanzee 
with an ulcer and a 105-year-old man. 
</P>
<P>
	Malkovich first read the script, written four years ago by  
Charles Kaufmann, who had never even met Malkovich. 
</P>
<P>
	``I probably thought the title was a sort of one-line joke,''  
Malkovich said. ``Then I realized it was a 110-page joke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The movie pokes fun at a lot of things, including the sort of  
celebrity enjoyed by someone like Malkovich, whose credits include 
``Dangerous Liaisons,'' ``Of Mice and Men'' and ``Places in the 
Heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The movie also gets in licks on love, jealousy, gender, growing  
old and the effects of childhood trauma on chimps. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being John Malkovich'' is being screened at Venice in the  
``Dreams and Visions'' section of the festival, one of several 
showcases for fresh talent. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's festival, which ends Sept. 11, also features a new  
award: $100,000 and 20,000 yards of film to a first-time filmmaker. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Surreal Comedy Gets Buzz at Venice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VENICE, Italy (AP) -- You could hear a buzz in the air on Day 2  
of the Venice Film Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie generating the stir was a quirky, surreal comedy  
called ``Being John Malkovich,'' starring -- who else? -- John 
Malkovich, directed by Spike Jonze. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, which premiered Thursday, is Jonze's first feature  
film. But he already had a cult following thanks to a string of 
award-winning music videos for the Beastie Boys, Puff Daddy, Bjork 
and REM; commercials for Coca-Cola, Nike and Nissan; and short 
