<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burton Likes To Race Clean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DARLINGTON, S.C. (AP) -- Jeff Burton feels good about the way he  
lost the Southern 500 two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He had the fastest car and the will to tame Darlington Raceway  
in 1997. Only Jeff Gordon stood in his way. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton moved low, and Gordon blocked him. Burton moved low  
again, Gordon blocked again, the cars touching hard on the final 
lap. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton was fighting mad and thought about spinning Gordon into  
the Darlington stands. But he didn't, and Gordon won the third of 
his four straight Southern 500s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was frustrated because he had blocked me real, real badly on  
the straightaway. I was frustrated because we didn't win a race we 
should have won,'' Burton said Thursday. ``Looking back on it, I 
still think I did the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burton has finished second in the Southern 500 the past two  
years. But he's proud he held the line on clean racing. As he 
prepared for today's qualifying for the event's historic 50th 
running, Burton was angry NASCAR let Dale Earnhardt keep his 
Bristol win last week after the Intimidator caused leader Terry 
Labonte to spin out near the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened last week, I totally disagree with. I don't  
think that's what racing is,'' said Burton, runner-up here to 
Gordon in 1997 and 1998. ``It would have been wrong for me to wreck 
the 24 (Gordon). That's not the way I race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Darlington, Burton normally races hard. Besides his two  
straight seconds, he won the rain-shortened TranSouth 400 here in 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	But Burton worries that without punishment, other drivers, young  
and old, will follow Earnhardt's lead that it's OK to wreck 
competitors to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be leading a race and get knocked out of the  
way to win it,'' he said. ``And I don't want to run second and have 
my car owner tell me, `Why didn't you knock him out of the way to 
win?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt has swapped body paint with racers almost from the  
start of his Winston Cup career. Fans have cherished his aggressive 
style, but even the crowd at Bristol disagreed with Earnhardt's 
latest move, booing him noisily in Victory Lane. 
</P>
<P>
	Darlington Raceway, a ridiculously tricky 1.366-mile oval, is  
not the place to carry a grudge. Its corners get tighter and more 
unpredictable with each layer of rubber chewed out of a racer's 
tires. If you're not focused on the track, Burton says, you're 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Winston Cup points leader Dale Jarrett earned a TranSouth 400  
win here in 1997 despite Ted Musgrave nipping at his rear bumper. 
Afterward, Jarrett thanked Musgrave for not spinning him out. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the way you'd like to think, that people are going to  
race you the way you race them,'' Jarrett said. ``That's not always 
the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why shouldn't Earnhardt plaster rivals, Jarrett said, since  
NASCAR has let him bump and grind for 20 years. Jarrett says he has 
never wrecked anyone to win a race. ``Maybe one day I'll experience 
that and I'll find it was worth it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not likely, Burton said. He thought NASCAR should have given the  
Bristol race to runner-up Jimmy Spencer. ``If we don't prevent 
people from doing what happened Saturday night,'' he said, ``then 
it will happen a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can pass a guy fair and square,'' Burton says, ``that's  
the way I want to win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
