Gold(final) -    $255.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   $5.220  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Workers' Productivity Slows  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The growth of American workers' productivity  
slowed considerably in the spring while labor costs jumped sharply, 
the Labor Department said today. The twin doses of bad news helped 
shake up investors about the August unemployment figures due out 
tomorrow. Productivity, defined as the amount of output for each 
hour of work, increased at an annual rate of 0.6 percent in the 
April-June quarter, far below the 3.6 percent rate in the first 
three months of the year. Meanwhile, unit labor costs, considered a 
key measure of wage pressures, rose at an annual rate of 4.5 
percent in the second quarter, the largest increase since the first 
quarter of 1994 when they also rose 4.5 percent. In another 
economic report, the Commerce Department said orders to U.S. 
factories for manufactured goods posted a bigger-than-expected gain 
of 2.1 percent in July. 

</P>
<P>
	August Retail Sales Mostly Strong  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Retailers enjoyed another strong month in  
August, as customers shrugged off rising interest rates and 
turbulence on Wall Street and kept buying at the nation's stores 
and malls. But a few hints of weakness among the sales reports 
issued today raised some concerns over the outlook for consumer 
spending in the coming months. Moderately priced department store 
chains such as J.C. Penney and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. continued to 
lose sales to the discounters and department store chains. Sears 
also warned today that its third-quarter earnings would be lower 
than Wall Street analysts' estimates. 

</P>
<P>
	Sears Makes Changes; Stock Falls  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Still unable to boost its sagging sales and  
profits, Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. today warned that its third-quarter 
earnings would fall well below expectations and announced a shakeup 
in its executive ranks. Arthur C. Martinez, Sears' chairman and 
chief executive, will now share all corporate decision-making with 
two executives who will work with him in the newly created Office 
of the Chief Executive. Alan J. Lacy, president of Sears Credit, 
will assume additional responsibilities as president of services. 
Julian C. Day, chief financial officer since March, was named to 
the new position of executive vice president and chief operating 
officer responsible for finance, logistics and information 
technology. Sears spokeswoman Peggy Palter said the ``entire 
reason'' for the reorganization was to allow Martinez to ``focus 
more closely on the retail business.'' Sears stock sank 3 11/16 or 
almost 10 percent, at 33 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Party Spray String Recalled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three California companies are recalling more  
than 900,000 cans of extremely flammable party spray string after 
one child was seriously burned. When sprayed near an open flame the 
string catches fire, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said 
today. The sprays, ``Crazy Ribbon'' and ``Crazy String,'' are 
manufactured by Stelex Enterprises Inc., Major Import and LeSa Yang 
Family Ltd. The commission said customers should take the sprays 
away from children, stop using them immediately and return them to 
the store where they were purchased for a refund. 

</P>
<P>
	Belluzzo To Run Microsoft Web Unit  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. named Richard Belluzzo, the  
former head of Silicon Graphics Inc., to lead its Internet business 
in a battle against rival behemoths such as America Online Inc. and 
Yahoo! Belluzzo has been enlisted ``to help step our online 
business up to the next level,'' Microsoft President Steve Ballmer 
said in a telephone interview from the company's Redmond 
headquarters. Microsoft has had mixed success competing on the 
Internet. Its Web investments include sites devoted to travel and 
personal finance, but the company has backed off from some 
ventures. 

</P>
<P>
	Pan American Airways Gets an OK  
</P>
<P>
	PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) -- Pan American Airways, at one point one  
of the world's largest air carriers before falling upon hard times, 
has received final federal approval to resume regular passenger 
service. The new service will be based at Pease International 
Tradeport, site of the old Pease Air Force Base, the first of 
several military bases to close in the early 1990s to save money. 
Pan Am President Dave Fink said details of the new service are 
being worked out and will be announced soon. Initially, Pan Am will 
fly from Pease to Orlando, Fla. 

</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia To Cut 13,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italian phone giant Telecom Italia SpA today  
announced plans to eliminate 13,000 jobs and reduce overall costs 
by $2.5 billion. Roberto Colaninno, who was named Telecom's 
chairman and chief executive officer following the company's 
hostile takeover by Olivetti SpA in May, said the cuts were part of 
long-term restructuring plans. Colaninno is also head of Olivetti, 
which controls 52.1 percent of Telecom. A former monopoly, Telecom 
has struggled since its privatization in October 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Smithfield To Buy Murphy  
</P>
<P>
	ROSE HILL, N.C. (AP) -- Smithfield Foods Inc., the world's  
largest hog producer and processor, has agreed to buy No. 2 hog 
producer Murphy Family Farms for about $290 million in stock. 
Founder and chief executive officer Wendell H. Murphy signed a 
letter of intent yesterday to sell his family-owned company to the 
Smithfield, Va., pork giant effective Jan. 1. The purchase involves 
about 10 million shares of Smithfield Foods plus the assumption of 
about $170 million in Murphy Farms debt and other liabilities. 

</P>
