<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Court Backs Environment Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court has rejected a claim  
from a Florida developer for government compensation because of 
environmental restrictions on use of his land, handing property 
rights advocates a major defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge panel said that the developer, who had wanted to  
fill in wetlands to build a housing complex in the Florida Keys, 
was not entitled to compensation even though the restrictions 
substantially reduced the value of his property. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision, handed down earlier this week by the U.S. Court of  
Appeals for the Federal Circuit, was announced Thursday by the 
Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Lois Schiffer, assistant attorney general for environment,  
called the decision ``a significant victory for environmental 
protection'' and said it sets an important precedent for so-called 
property ``takings'' cases brought before the federal court of 
claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ruling ensures that courts considering takings claims in  
the future will take a hard look at the reasonableness of a 
developers' plans in light of federal state and local environmental 
protection standards,'' said Schiffer. 
</P>
<P>
	The developer, Lloyd A. Good Jr., had sought for 13 years to  
develop a 40-acre tract of land on Sugarloaf Key in the Florida 
Keys into a 54-lot subdivision. However, 32 of the acres were 
wetlands and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers would not approve 
dredging and filling the land without certain restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Good first sought state permits to build in 1981 on the land he  
bought in 1973. Initially he obtained local and conditional state 
permits, but later was blocked from proceeding because of the 
presence of two endangered species -- the Lower Keys marsh rabbit 
and the silver rice rat. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, the Army Corps said Good would get a permit to fill in  
some of the wetland as long as he tailored the project to protect 
the two endangered species. He refused to accept those conditions 
and filed suit with the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, seeking 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	In an opinion on Tuesday, the three-judge panel upheld the  
claims court's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Judge Edward S. Smith, who wrote the opinion, said that  
Good had been told in 1973 and again when he sought to develop the 
property that there were ``significant restrictions'' on his 
ability to develop it. 
</P>
<P>
	Good ``lacked a reasonable, investment-backed expectation that  
he would obtain the regulatory approval needed to develop the 
property,'' wrote Smith. This ``defeats his takings claim as a 
matter of law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Court of Federal Claims had made a similar finding in  
rejecting the compensation claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard R. Nageotte of Stafford, Va., who argued Good's case,  
said Thursday that the decision ``wipes out the property rights 
guaranteed by the Constitution of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless you got the property from the King of England you  
probably can never prove a reasonable investment'' because of some 
restrictive law or regulation, said Nageotte in a telephone 
interview. ``It's a devastating ruling for private property 
owners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Good had made no decision on an appeal to the U.S.  
Supreme Court, but indicated such an appeal is unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Smith, the two appeals court members were Circuit  
Judges Pauline Newman and Arthur J. Gajarsa. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
