<DOCNO> APW19990902.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 15:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Says Don't Aid Bad Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate George W.  
Bush said Thursday that federal funds should be confiscated from 
the worst-performing schools and made available to parents for 
private education, tutoring or ``whatever offers hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In my administration, federal money will no longer follow  
failure,'' the Texas governor told the Latin Business Association, 
a Hispanic group. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Bush's plan, every school getting the Title I money would  
be required to test its impoverished students on basic academics 
each year. A warning would be issued to schools that fail to make 
progress toward state standards. After three years of no progress, 
the Title I money would be matched with other federal education 
money and given to the state, which would set up an education 
account -- about $1,500 a year -- for each affected student. 
</P>
<P>
	The parents could choose how to spend the money. They could keep  
the money and their child in the original school or opt for an 
alternative, including private school and tutoring -- ``for whatever 
offers hope,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government currently spends $7.7 billion on Title I to help  
educate poor children. 
</P>
<P>
	A Bush aide said the plan would require states to create  
mechanisms for ensuring parents spend the money on education. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said federal programs affecting teacher training,  
curriculum research and school safety would have to prove results. 
Those that didn't would be stripped of their funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also proposed shifting the $4.4 billion Head Start program  
from the Department of Health and Human Services to the Education 
Department, a step he said would return the program's focus to 
preparing disadvantaged preschoolers for the classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Invoking the buzzwords often heard in school-reform efforts in  
California, Texas and many other states, Bush said schools must 
establish clear goals that help measure students' basic skills. 
Testing helps ensure they achieve them, he said. And someone must 
take responsibility when they fail, he said, singling out 
principals. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he said, local control of schools is essential  
to meeting the goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Secretary Richard Riley said he saw similarities  
between Bush's Title I proposal and those of his brother Jeb, who 
as Florida's governor pushed through the nation's first statewide 
voucher plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how you dress it up, how long you delay it, or what  
you call it, a voucher is a voucher,'' Riley said. ``Gov. George W. 
Bush would have us start down the road of accountability, then take 
a dangerous detour into vouchers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We would be against a plan like this,'' said Reginald Felton,  
director of federal relations for the National School Boards 
Association. ``The objective is to raise the academic achievement 
of all students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But at a Title I elementary school Bush visited Thursday, the  
idea of vouchers won cautious support from two teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is a good idea, because sometimes private schools  
have a lot more to offer -- more personal, smaller classes,'' said 
teacher Joann Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	She and fellow teacher Janet Leinin didn't believe that such  
programs would rob Bennett-Kew Elementary School of students and 
the public money that follows them, because, they said, it is 
academically one of the strongest in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his GOP presidential opponents, Ken Blackwell, national  
chairman of Steve Forbes' campaign, said Bush didn't go far enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think his program is a bit weak in one particular area -- he  
tells parents to wait three years for real school reform,'' said 
Blackwell, who is also secretary of state in Ohio, a state that is 
experimenting with vouchers. ``I don't believe and neither does 
Steve Forbes that we can wait three years for real school reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole's spokesman, Ari Fleischer, said, ``I thought it  
was more notable for what was not in it than for what was in it.'' 
He cited the discipline issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole favors school vouchers, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley, campaigning in  
Ohio said vouchers are not the answer to the problems of public 
education. ``I think that there are problems -- not the least of 
which are issues of church and state -- and ultimately they will 
have to be resolved,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As a senator from New Jersey, Bradley said he voted twice for  
federally funded voucher experiments. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush delivered his remarks in a state where voters have soundly  
rejected proposals to allow public money for private schools, an 
arrangement often referred to as school vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, Bush has backed a proposed pilot program for  
taxpayer-funded vouchers for private school tuition. State 
lawmakers have declined to pass the proposal ever since Bush became 
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month a federal judge halted a voucher program in Ohio,  
saying it appeared to have the ``primary effect of advancing 
religion'' because it allowed public money to be used for religious 
and other private schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge later said the program can remain in place for  
students who participated in the program last year, but said that 
would last only one semester or until a final judgment is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush offered a forceful defense of such programs.  
</P>
<P>
	``All monopolies are slow to reform when consumers have no power  
to express their frustration,'' he said. ``In education, parents 
who have options have influence.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
