<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track Evens CART Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Every track that Juan Montoya  
has raced on this season has been a new experience. 
</P>
<P>
	The sensational CART FedEx Series rookie has adjusted to the  
newness very well, winning six of the first 15 races this season 
and carrying a four-point lead over Dario Franchitti into this 
week's Vancouver Molson Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	To make matters worse for the rest of the CART competitors, the  
newly reconfigured 1.802-mile temporary street circuit at the edge 
of downtown Vancouver evens things out because it's new for 
everyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vancouver is a challenge because it's another of the courses  
I've never seen before,'' Montoya said. ``But I think because the 
track has been reconfigured since last year, the other rookies and 
I will have an advantage since we're not used to the old layout.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the final quarter of the 20-race season about to begin,  
Montoya could be excused if he felt a little pressure from the 
championship battle with Franchitti. But last year's European 
Formula 3000 champion is just fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having too much fun to feel nervous,'' Montoya said. ``Not  
one expected me to be doing so well so soon, so I don't feel any 
pressure. Besides, I'm a rookie. I have nothing to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya is riding a two-race winning string. Moreover, he has  
won races on each type of track where CART races, including the 
temporary street circuit in Long Beach, Calif., permanent road 
courses and ovals. 
</P>
<P>
	But Franchitti and teammate Paul Tracy have finished 1-2 in the  
last two CART street races, in Toronto and Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only that, but Franchitti won last year's race in Vancouver  
from the pole. That victory -- only his second in CART -- established 
the Scotsman as a legitimate title contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``That victory proved that winning the previous race at Road  
America was no fluke,'' Franchitti said. ``Above all else, I think 
it signaled to everyone in CART that our team had arrived. We 
became the team to beat as the season ended.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy and Michael Andretti are the only other drivers with a  
legitimate shot at winning this year's PPG Cup championship. But 
both need to begin making a move in Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into the opening of practice today, Andretti trails  
Montoya by 48 points and Tracy is two more back. 
</P>
<P>
	But Andretti, the only one of the top four in the points race  
who has won a championship, isn't ready to concede just yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Realistically, getting back into it, the way those two are  
going, isn't going to be easy,'' the second-generation Champ Car 
star said. ``But a couple of wins, a couple of weeks with max 
points and ... who knows? 
</P>
<P>
	``There are still 110 points out there. But we can't keep  
letting things get away from us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti and Tracy lost considerable ground two weeks ago when  
they tangled in a controversial wreck. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were battling side-by-side for third place early in the  
Target Grand Prix on the new Chicago Motor Speedway oval when they 
collided, sending both hard into the wall. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't the first time the two antagonists have tangled. In  
fact, Tracy was held out of the first race this season as a penalty 
for an on-track incident with Andretti last fall in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to get somebody hurt one of these days,'' Andretti  
said of Tracy. ``He doesn't use his head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy called the latest incident a racing accident, saying  
Andretti should accept at least part of the blame. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing is ever his fault,'' Tracy said. ``We were racing to  
the corner and I had the position, as far as I'm concerned. He 
didn't back off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But both said all that matter now is the 22 points -- one for the  
pole, 20 for winning the race and one for leading the most laps -- 
that are out there for the taking this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``This time, I'd like to reverse roles with Dario and get the  
victory for myself,'' Tracy said. ``I definitely need to win some 
races to get back into the championship race with Juan and Dario.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
