<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Night of Tears for MLB Umpires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- For umpires, there is crying in baseball.  
</P>
<P>
	Eyes accustomed to calling balls and strikes were filled with  
tears Wednesday night after 22 umps lost their jobs, part of a 
complex deal between their union and baseball that was brokered by 
a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``It not only has broken my heart, but it has devastated me as  
an individual,'' said Tom Hallion, one of 13 NL umps let go. 
``Right now, I'm sitting here, I just did my last game. This is 
what I want to do, this is what I love to do. I love baseball. 
Right now, I hate baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the four umps on Hallion's crew were sent home for the  
season, their only hope an arbitration hearing months from now. 
Between the eighth and ninth innings, Dodger Stadium organist Nancy 
Bea Hefley paid tribute to the departing umpires with a few 
choruses of ``I'll Be Seeing You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Baltimore, Greg Kosc had tears in his eyes as Orioles manager  
Ray Miller handed him his lineup card before the game. Mark McGwire 
held open his glove after the final out in St. Louis, giving the 
ball to Frank Pulli, a 28-year veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's one of the 22 worst umpires in this league, I'm a  
kamikaze pilot,'' Cardinals third-base coach Rene Lachemann said. 
``It's a big mistake that they fired him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly one-third of the sport's 68 permanent umpires are out of  
work, although the agreement provides for them to be paid for the 
rest of the year. On July 14, more than 50 umpires announced a mass 
resignation effective Sept. 2, an attempt to force an early start 
to talks for a new labor agreement to replace the deal expiring 
Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Their strategy backfired when owners accepted the resignations,  
and 27 umps, mostly in the American League, broke ranks with union 
leader Richie Phillips, either by refusing to quit and quickly 
taking back their resignations. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Wednesday's agreement, umpires have the right to take the  
dispute to arbitration and argue baseball should have accepted the 
resignation rescissions of all umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	Their salary and benefits for the rest of the year would be  
deducted from their termination pay if they lose the grievance. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside court room 8-B, AL ump Mark Johnson couldn't focus on  
that, and tears filled his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea what I'm going to do now,'' he said. ``There  
aren't a lot of opportunities out there for a 48-year old ex-major 
league umpire that I know of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires filed suit to block baseball from letting the 22 go, but  
owners had an overwhelming legal advantage because it was the 
umpires themselves who voluntarily submitted the resignations, 
which they now say was only a symbolic protest. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point, people have to take responsibility for their  
decisions and the decisions made on their behalf,'' said Sandy 
Alderson, baseball's executive vice president of operations. ``It's 
unfortunate 22 umpires will no longer be working. We hope the 
payments each will receive will soften the transition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal mediated by U.S. District Judge J. Curtis Joyner  
during 16 hours of bargaining over two days, the union agreed the 
22 ``will provide no further services'' after 6 a.m. EDT today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think that it's a shame for baseball,'' umpires union head  
Richie Phillips said. ``Baseball will suffer from the loss of these 
enormously talented people that the commissioner's office has 
arbitrarily determined to hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, owners agreed that all umpires on staff as of  
Friday -- there will be 71 of them -- are entitled to the $20,000 
postseason bonus, an amount that totals $1.42 million. The deal 
also gives umpires the right to forgo the bonus and have it go 
directly to the union. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, the umpires withdrew their lawsuit and the unfair  
labor practice charges against baseball they filed with the 
National Labor Relations Board. They also agreed not to strike this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five umpires hired by baseball in July became permanent  
employees today. Many are vacation fill-ins from the minor leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``The resignations will stand and the new umpires are permanent  
employees,'' commissioner Bud Selig said. ``We are proud to have 
them on board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As several umpires left the court in the twilight of the  
evening, and perhaps their careers, they were bitter at Selig. They 
claimed that when talks recessed Tuesday night, the sides had 
agreed that any of the 22 umps could work the rest of the season at 
Selig's discretion. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took that off the table this morning,'' umpires lawyer  
Susan Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig acknowledged making the change, but said it wasn't  
significant. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no reason to put it in because they weren't going to  
work anymore,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Phillips proclaimed the deal a victory for his side,  
umpires' eyes told a different story. They couldn't believe they 
were jobless. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't these baseball people have hearts?'' NL ump Bill Hohn  
said. ``I mean, we have families. They're ruining families, and 
that's what hurts. It was a mistake, but my God, we're good people. 
We're the integrity of the game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 07:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
