<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Immigrants Are Staying Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of immigrants living in poverty  
across the country has grown and they are remaining poor longer 
than in the past, according to a study released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The portion of immigrants living in poverty grew from about one  
in six in 1979 to more than one in five in 1997, according to the 
study from the Center for Immigration Studies. The total number in 
poverty tripled from 2.2 million to 7.7 million during that period, 
with the highest rates in California, Texas and South Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth of immigrant poverty, which occurred during a period  
when poverty in native households remained steady, meant that 
immigrants now account for more than one in five of all poor 
families nationwide, compared to less than one in 10 two decades 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigrants are also climbing out of poverty more slowly, the  
report found. For example, more than one in four immigrants who 
arrived during the 1980s remained impoverished in 1997, which was 
twice the rate for natives. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans may disagree over the best way to address poverty,''  
said Mark Krikorian, the center's executive director. ``But there 
can be no doubt that ongoing immigration is diverting scarce public 
and private resources that are needed to help the poor already 
here, native-born and immigrants, improve their circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Poverty was defined as the federal threshold of $16,400 for a  
family of four. 
</P>
<P>
	The report blamed the higher poverty rates on the lower levels  
of education, higher unemployment and larger family sizes of 
immigrants. But the report said that welfare reform and illegal 
immigrants weren't responsible for the broadening poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, nearly one in four of the 11.3 million immigrants  
were living in poverty in 1997. That was nearly twice the poverty 
rate for 21.6 million natives. Half the immigrants came from Mexico 
and Central America, with about one in six from Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, 28.7 percent of immigrants live in poverty. In  
Arizona, 36.4 percent. In Florida, the figure was 22.3 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Rebounding After Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- When angry pilots went on strike against  
Northwest Airlines last year, equally angry travelers revived a 
nickname that has plagued the airline from time to time: 
``Northworst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strike shut down the nation's fourth-largest carrier for 15  
days and contributed to more than $1 billion in losses from labor 
problems. One year later, Northwest is back on top in the on-time 
rankings, the airline is back in the black, workers are mostly 
happy and the scornful nickname is on ice. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, things are looking up for Northwest.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Northwest is definitely an airline on their way back.  
To a great degree, they are back,'' said Terry Trippler, an airline 
expert with 1travel.com. ``I think they're doing it faster than any 
of us thought they would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Northwest's regular passengers have returned, said  
George Wozniak of Hobbit Travel in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously during the strike it was, 'I'll never fly those  
bozos again.' The majority have returned because of the frequent 
flier program,'' Wozniak said. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline is buying new planes and refurbishing others, buying  
equipment to keep passenger-filled planes cool on the ground and 
improving the food for business and first-class passengers. 
Northwest has improved to No. 2 in baggage handling, hired 
additional staff and increased training for ground operations 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	After three money-losing quarters, the carrier returned to  
profitability in the quarter ended June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been working very hard and our people have been  
working very hard to provide consistent, reliable service to our 
passengers,'' said Richard Anderson, who was named to the new 
position of chief operating officer in mid-December. 
</P>
<P>
	During the strike, Northwest was buffeted by ill winds from more  
than one direction -- pilots seeking higher pay and better job 
security, customers angry about disrupted business and vacation 
plans and politicians demanding more airline competition to bring 
down fares at Northwest's hubs in Minneapolis-St. Paul, Detroit and 
Memphis, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots got much of what they wanted, gaining $156 million in the  
four-year contract that ended the strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the Air Line Pilots Association credited Anderson  
for many positive changes at Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's an operations guy. He says, 'What's the problem?' and  
he's willing to get it fixed,'' said ALPA spokesman Paul Omodt. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, considered a likely candidate to succeed John Dasburg  
as chief executive down the road, has instituted monthly meetings 
with both pilots and ground workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants an ongoing labor relations thing. You're starting to  
see the change,'' Omodt said. ``Employees are back into being No. 
1. It feels good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there still could be turbulence ahead.  
</P>
<P>
	Flight attendants will be going back to the negotiating table  
after rejecting a contract proposal last week that would have 
raised pay an average of 14 percent, boosted pensions and increased 
job security. Mechanics, who split off from the International 
Association of Machinists to join the Aircraft Mechanics Fraternal 
Association, are preparing to begin contract negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Reaching agreement with the remaining employees is ``very  
important'' to Northwest's recovery, Anderson said. Dasburg has 
said that Northwest can't claim it is a top-quality airline until 
its labor problems are settled. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the looming fare dispute.  
</P>
<P>
	Northwest still dominates its hubs. As a result, air traffic was  
cut to a trickle during the strike, and many smaller cities lost 
all air service because Northwest's regional Airlink partners also 
shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Transportation and Congress are looking  
at ways to increase airline competition, improve service to small 
and medium-size communities and reduce fares throughout the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest is starting to see some competition. Sun Country  
Airlines now operates regularly scheduled service out of 
Minneapolis-St. Paul to more than a dozen cities. Icelandair has 
beefed up its service to northern Europe and Vanguard Airlines has 
added flights, said Wendy Burt, a spokeswoman for the Metropolitan 
Airports Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	American, America West, Continental, Delta, Frontier, TWA,  
United and USAirways also offer scheduled service and there are 
several charter operations serving the Twin Cities. Detroit, in 
addition to the major carriers, is served by Southwest, Ryan, 
Spirit and TransAir. 
</P>
<P>
	But Northwest remains the giant. The airline says it flies 53  
percent of passengers whose trips originate or end in 
Minneapolis-St. Paul. For Detroit, the figure is 40 percent. Those 
figures do not include passengers connecting with Northwest at the 
hubs via Northwest's regional Airlink partners. When passengers 
making connections are counted, the Northwest percentage rises to 
about 80 at the three hub airports. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
