<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was steady against the yen early Friday  
ahead of the release of key U.S. economic data. Japanese stocks 
opened mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 109.42 yen in early trading, unchanged from  
late Thursday in Tokyo but higher than its late New York level of 
109.11 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 12.42  
points, or 0.07 percent, to 17,643.67 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. On Thursday, the average closed down 171.23 points, or 
0.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, players were awaiting the release of U.S.  
employment figures for August, due out in Washington later Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's relative strength from its New York level came  
after some investors bought the dollar to cover short, or oversold, 
positions in early Asian trading, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also got support from comments by Eisuke Sakakibara,  
Japan's former vice finance minister for international affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a U.S. television interview broadcast Friday on CNBC,  
Sakakibara, now an advisor to the Finance Ministry, said currency 
``intervention is always a strategic decision,'' which depends on 
market conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Sakakibara's remarks, there have been no recent signs of  
dollar-buying intervention by the Bank of Japan, the country's 
central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials have repeatedly said a premature  
strengthening of the yen is undesirable amid sporadic signs that 
Japan is recovering from its worst recession in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 117.26 yen, up from  
115.86 late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices were suppressed by the strong yen  
and a 94.67-point fall in the Dow Jones industrial average. The Dow 
closed at 10,843.23 points on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The yen remains strong, and that is hurting stock market  
sentiment,'' said Yasushi Hoshi, a market analyst at Daiwa 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive and thus less  
competitive abroad, reducing foreign revenues when translated into 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 1.04 points, or 0.07 percent, to 1,495.95. 
The TOPIX closed up 0.75 points, or 0.05 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was  
unquoted in early trading. On Thursday it settled at 1.8850 percent 
and its price stood at 100.12 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
