<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Carlos Moya pulled out of the U.S. Open  
because of a bad back Thursday, he was the third player who had 
been ranked No. 1 to withdraw this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Moya was trailing Nicolas Escude of France 1-6, 4-6, 1-0 when he  
called it quits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had this pain for 10 days already,'' he said. ``It got  
really worse and really bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moya became No. 1 on March 15, becoming the first Spanish man  
and the 15th player to hold the top ranking. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, top-ranked Pete Sampras withdrew with an injured  
back and Patrick Rafter, who held the No. 1 spot earlier this year, 
pulled out with a tear in the right rotator cuff. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CLOSE TO PERFECT:* Conchita Martinez was nearly perfect in the  
second set of her 6-0, 6-0 victory over Alexia Dechaume-Balleret of 
France. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second set, Dechaume-Balleret won just five points. She  
won 16 points in the match. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LIGHTS, CAMERA, ACTION:* Mark Keil of Kauai, Hawaii, is a busy  
man at the U.S. Open this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides competing in men's doubles, Keil is filming a  
documentary, ``Beyond the Baseline.'' in which the former 
University of South Florida student interviews fellow ATP Tour 
players behind the scenes at tournaments around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a one-year odyssey with me, a player, as I film the  
top-ranked players around the world on the tour from hotels to 
locker rooms to player parties,'' said Keil, who beat Pete Sampras 
on a grass court at Queens Club in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Keil said he was inspired to pursue the film project when  
reading Andy Warhol's autobiography last Christmas. In the 
autobiography, Warhol spoke of documenting as much of his life as 
possible with a personal camera. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TELLING IT LIKE IT IS:* Two-time U.S. Open winner Tracy Austin,  
now a television commentator on the USA Network, said the WTA Tour 
is able to get along very well even though Steffi Graf has retired. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time someone like Steffi leaves, with 22 Grand Slams in  
her resume, it's a huge loss,'' Austin told viewers. ``But luckily, 
I think, women's tennis has so many stars right now, it's not going 
to be a big gap. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lindsay Davenport and (Martina) Hingis going for that No. 1  
ranking back-and-forth. The Williams sisters starting to come on 
and really do some big things. Venus (Williams) with her highest 
ranking ever at No. 3 and Serena (Williams) with her highest 
ranking at No. 6. I don't think they've come close to fulfilling 
their potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``And you've got Anna Kournikova, who's not even here this year  
with a stress fracture in her foot. She's got a ton of potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TURNING IT AROUND:* Since his surprising run to the French  
Open, where he lost to Andre Agassi, Andre Medvedev has won only 
three matches in six tournaments before the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything was so unexpected at Roland Garros and I came so  
close to winning it that after that the smaller tournaments, you 
just struggle for motivation,'' said Medvedev, who gained a berth 
in the third round Thursday by beating Canada's Sebastian Lareau 
6-4, 6-1, 6-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just surprised to get through the first two rounds here  
because frankly I don't feel I was playing well,'' Medvedev said. 
``But I must be doing something right. I came here with the goal to 
get to the second week, so I'm on my way.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
