<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford faces $1.5M Fine in Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A state agency said today it is fining Ford Motor  
Co. $1.5 million for at least a dozen workplace violations stemming 
from the February explosion in the Rouge complex that killed six 
workers 
</P>
<P>
	The Michigan Occupational and Safety Administration outlined  
fines, safety violations and specific safety changes that Ford has 
agreed to make. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the $1.5 million fine, Ford will spend $5 million on  
burn care at area hospitals, occupational health and safety 
measures and a union scholarship fund in memory of those who died 
in the explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	``This historic agreement cannot reclaim lost lives, it cannot  
restore broken bodies. But it can ease the suffering of the victims 
and their families by assuring a safer and healthier work 
environment for all Ford employees in the future,'' said Kathy 
Wilbur, director of Michigan Consumer and Industry Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said it has agreed to specific safety changes, including  
inspection and upgrading of all boilers if necessary. It will not 
contest the fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot change the terrible events of the past, but we can  
work hard to make our workplaces safer in the future,'' James 
Padilla, Ford manufacturing group vice president, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Feb. 1 explosion in the powerhouse at the Dearborn complex  
also injured 14 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	MIOSHA investigators collected more than 30,000 pages of  
documents during the seven-month investigation. The agency also 
reviewed more than 100,000 documents from Ford and Dearborn fire 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the explosion was an inadvertent buildup of natural  
gas in Boiler No. 6, which was being shut down for a planned 
inspection and overhaul, according to a joint report released today 
by Ford and the United Auto Workers. However, the report didn't 
determine a source of the gas ignition. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the state, the primary factor in the accident was  
that Ford did not adequately train its boiler operators. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the automaker announced it had hired CEC Consultants, a  
Cleveland firm, to help it examine safety procedures at power 
plants across North America. 
</P>
<P>
	The families of three workers have sued Rouge Steel, which  
co-owns the Rouge complex. Those claims are expected to be dropped 
after the families of the workers sign settlements with Ford, which 
has offered more than $30 million to settle claims. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
