<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Outlaws Textbook Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis has signed into law a  
measure barring references to consumer products in school books 
purchased with state money. 
</P>
<P>
	The law, which Davis approved Wednesday, requires all books  
submitted to the state Board of Education to meet the bill's 
standards after Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Math problems involving products like Nike sneakers, M&AMP;M candies  
and Oreo cookies appear in a 6th-grade textbook, ``Mathematics 
Applications and Connections,'' developed by Glencoe, a division of 
McGraw-Hill. Other books contain similar uses of brand-name 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's inappropriate, in that it's pushing products. We're  
trying to get away from this very quiet level of advertising,'' 
said Erika Hoffman, legislative representative for the state 
Department of Education. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not advertising, said Bill Jordan, McGraw-Hill's  
director of media relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we develop textbooks, we get a lot of feedback from a lot  
of users of our books, and one thing that kept coming through loud 
and clear was, use real-world examples,'' he said. ``Make it 
relevant to the kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said McGraw-Hill was not paid to use any of the brand  
names. The company simply selected names they felt would be 
recognized by the children using the books. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Hagelshaw of the Center for Commercial-Free Public  
Education in Oakland said the product placements were unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We oppose any advertising in public schools that turn students  
into a captive audience,'' he said. ``You can make a textbook more 
relevant by saying bike without saying it's a Schwinn. You can say 
cookie without mentioning Oreos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	California's legislature is the first to complain about  
``Mathematics Applications and Connections,'' which has been the 
best seller in its category since it was introduced about six years 
ago, said Steve Weiss, a McGraw-Hill spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to California's reaction, new books minus the brand  
names already are being published, Weiss said. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
