<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sears Makes Changes; Stock Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s stock plummeted 11  
percent today after the nation's second-largest retailer warned 
Wall Street that its third-quarter earnings would fall below 
expectations and announced a management shakeup. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears, still mired in a slump despite a series of changes aimed  
at reviving its business, disclosed the news as it reported 
disappointing sales for the month of August. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said today's announcement clearly signaled that the  
marketing and merchandising campaign Sears embarked on this year 
isn't yet paying off. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've clearly got to do something,'' said Jeffrey Edelman,  
an analyst for Paine Webber. ``It would appear the department 
stores need a lot of work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors apparently agreed. Sears stock was down $4.12 1/2 to  
$33.06 1/4 today on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur C. Martinez, chairman and chief executive officer,  
acknowledged the changes aren't working but said the latest moves 
show the company's ``commitment to re-energizing our sales.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shakeup came barely two weeks after the Hoffman Estates,  
Ill.-based company unveiled a more value-focused advertising 
campaign aimed at regaining some of the ground it has lost to 
discount and specialty retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears is also trying to offer more trendy clothing, is  
remodeling its stores and selling merchandise on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the company announced today that sales at stores  
open at least a year -- an industry gauge of performance -- rose a 
mere 0.1 percent in August. Sales were particularly weak in lawn 
and garden products, men's clothing and footwear. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears also said third-quarter earnings would be in the range of  
63 cents to 67 cents per share, less than the 82 cents that 
analysts were expecting. The retailer also said it is revising its 
full-year earnings outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez's role in an overhauled Sears management was not fully  
defined, but analysts suggested it would give him more of a 
hands-on role in strategy, especially at the department stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, however, will begin to share all corporate  
decision-making with two executives that will work with him in the 
newly created Office of the Chief Executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan J. Lacy, president of Sears Credit, will assume additional  
responsibilities as president of services. Julian C. Day, chief 
financial officer since March, was named to the new position of 
executive vice president and chief operating officer responsible 
for finance, logistics and information technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced the departure of the chief of  
merchandising for its full-line department stores, Robert Mettler. 
</P>
<P>
	With Mettler's departure, two presidents have been appointed to  
cover his responsibilities. Lyle Heidemann will be president of 
hardlines, which includes appliances, hardware and consumer 
electronics. Mark Cohen will be president of softlines, which 
includes all clothing and accessories. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
