<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Envoy to IMF Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's special envoy to the International  
Monetary Fund and other foreign lenders resigned suddenly Thursday, 
saying he had ``fulfilled'' his mission and wanted to run for 
parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhail Zadornov gave no indication that his resignation was  
connected to concerns that the IMF may delay new loans to Russia 
because of reports that previous IMF aid to Russia may have been 
illegally diverted through U.S. banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Zadornov insisted that all IMF aid had been used properly, and  
predicted the next loan would come as scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was resigning to run for parliament in December's  
legislative elections as a candidate of the liberal Yabloko party. 
</P>
<P>
	A long-time member of the Russian Cabinet, Zadornov said his  
departure should not harm Russia's relations with the IMF, its 
biggest lender. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the last three months, we have succeeded in fully  
renewing our relations with international financial institutions,'' 
Zadornov told a news conference. ``I consider my mission 
fulfilled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zadornov, a former finance minister, helped negotiate the  
resumption of IMF aid to Russia after it was frozen in the wake of 
Russia's financial meltdown last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF renewed lending in July, and was expected to release  
$640 million of a $4.5 billion loan package this month. But the 
U.S. government -- the IMF's largest member -- said Wednesday it 
won't decide whether to approve new loans until a full accounting 
is made of the IMF money Russia has already received. 
</P>
<P>
	The hesitation comes amid reports that U.S. investigators  
believe Russian organized crime laundered billions of dollars 
through Western banks. Some reports have suggested that IMF money 
may have also been used in the transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Russian ruble fell against the U.S. dollar for a  
third day Thursday amid concerns that the IMF loan would be 
delayed. One dollar bought 25.79 rubles on the Moscow Interbank 
Currency Exchange, up from 25.4 rubles the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is the IMF's biggest borrower, with about $20 billion in  
lending since 1992. Moscow is seeking new loans to help pay off 
previous debts to the fund. 
</P>
<P>
	In other economic news Thursday, the Russian Statistics Agency  
said Russia's gross domestic product shrank by 1 percent in the 
first half of this year from the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's GDP totaled $72 billion in the first six months of  
the year, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's economy has shrunk every year since the collapse of the  
Soviet Union except for 1997, when it grew by less than one 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
