<DOCNO> APW19990902.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:26:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Serbs Block Road in Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRACANICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Angry Serbs blocked the main road  
in Gracanica today, protesting the disappearance of a Serb man two 
days ago and demanding that NATO troops protect them from their 
revenge-minded Albanian neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO troops said Serbs roughed up six people when they tried to  
drive through the village Wednesday afternoon. About 20 Serbs and a 
few Gyspies today stood beside vehicles preventing all but NATO 
vehicles from passing. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in London, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said today  
that British police in Kosovo have uncovered 50 bodies buried in a 
garbage dump. The latest discovery brings the number of bodies 
found by British forces and police in Kosovo to more than 200 in 
the last two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are currently carrying out the work of exhuming and  
documenting those bodies,'' Cook said. Evidence from the mass grave 
will be sent to the International War Crimes Tribunal, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Local Serbs said they erected the barricade in Gracanica on  
Wednesday after Milorad Popovic, 41, disappeared the day before 
while driving a truckload of lumber to a nearby village. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not only because of my husband,'' said Popovic's wife,  
Vesna. ``It's because of the way we have to live here now that we 
put up the barricades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Popovic said she, her husband and two children came to  
Gracanica (pronounced GRA-cha-neet-zah) two months ago after ethnic 
Albanians drove them from their apartment in Pristina, four miles 
to the north. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the blockade would last ``until they find my husband.''  
</P>
<P>
	In Pristina, an Albanian doctor, Mehmet Maxhuni, said five  
Albanians and one Bulgarian woman, married to an Albanian, were 
pummeled at the barricade. NATO spokesman Maj. Roland Lavoie said 
six people were roughed up but none was seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Gracanica, in the British sector, is the site of a Serbian  
Orthodox monastery -- one of several religious shrines threatened by 
ethnic Albanians, the majority of whom are Muslim. A detachment of 
Irish Guards is stationed in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The blockade is a further sign of ethnic divisions that have  
impeded efforts by the NATO-led peacekeeping force to bring peace 
to this province. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, NATO said a Gypsy family of four, was found dead of  
gunshot wounds Wednesday in Gornji Dragolevci, one mile southeast 
of Istok. 
</P>
<P>
	A Serb man was killed and another injured in an ambush Wednesday  
near Kosovska Mitrovica, NATO said. Late Wednesday, three Serbs 
were injured in a grenade attack on their house in the British 
sector, NATO added. 
</P>
<P>
	In Orahovac, where local Albanians have been blocking roads  
since Aug. 23, Kosovo's Albanian rebel leader endorsed efforts to 
prevent Russian peacekeepers from taking up positions there. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hasim Thaci, head of Kosovo's unofficial government, said  
during a visit there Wednesday that Russian troops might be allowed 
to deploy in the larger region. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians are part of the NATO-led international peacekeeping  
force, or KFOR, that entered Kosovo following NATO's bombing 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The Albanians claim Russian paramilitaries committed atrocities  
while stationed in Orahovac, 30 miles southwest of the provincial 
capital, Pristina, during the Serb-led crackdown on ethnic Albanian 
rebels in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant 
republic. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, no official decisions have been made on whether the  
Russians will replace Dutch peacekeepers in the region, as 
previously planned. Ethnic Albanians along the barricades, however, 
have been pitching tents, setting up makeshift shops and other 
measures to prepare for an indefinite standoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, Bernard Kouchner, the top U.N. official in  
Kosovo, announced international police officers would be sent to 
Orahovac until the standoff is resolved. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
