<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Regulation Part of NYSE Public Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Stock Exchange board members are  
considering creation of a new regulatory structure that would 
separate the exchange's marketplace from its enforcement arm under 
plans to take the exchange public. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators at the Securities and Exchange Commission, which  
enforces federal securities laws at the United States stock 
exchanges, have raised concerns over how the Big Board will police 
itself as a publicly traded organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE board was set to meet today to discuss a possible  
initial public offering of stock, or IPO. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange currently is a self-regulating organization,  
imposing fines and suspensions on members who break its rules and 
cheat investors. The main concern, according to officials at the 
Securities and Exchange Commission, is that such regulation could 
slip as a priority if the NYSE becomes more focused on turning a 
profit and improving share price than in policing its members. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE announced in July it was considering going public to  
raise money to better compete with upstart electronic trading 
networks. The Nasdaq Stock Market, the second largest after the 
NYSE, also is considering an IPO. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE has yet to submit a proposal to the SEC on how it might  
restructure its regulatory arm. But the plan is expected to closely 
mirror the structure now used by the National Association of 
Securities Dealers, which acts as the parent company for two 
independent but affiliated units -- the Nasdaq Stock Market and NASD 
Regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Talks between the New York Stock Exchange and the SEC have  
been very productive to this point and we believe they embrace our 
notion that some separation of the market and the self-regulatory 
function is appropriate,'' Annette Nazareth, director of the SEC's 
market regulation division, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The Big Board, like other stock exchanges, currently polices its  
members itself through its status as a self-regulating 
organization, or SRO. Under the SRO structure, the NYSE creates its 
own regulation policies and enforces them through an in-house 
regulatory unit. 
</P>
<P>
	The job of the SEC, which enforces federal securities laws at  
all U.S. stock exchanges, is to make sure the NYSE's regulations 
conform with federal standards. In addition, the SEC must approve 
any regulatory changes proposed by the exchange, and is authorized 
to inspect the NYSE's operations to ensure compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	None of that would change if the Big Board goes forward with an  
IPO. What would change is that the NYSE would suddenly be 
accountable to profit-seeking shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rap on SROs in general is that they are owned by their  
members and there's an inherent tension between the members and the 
regulatory arm. The members want the regulatory people to take it 
easy on them,'' said Bruce Baird, a Washington, D.C., securities 
lawyer and former head of the securities fraud unit for the U.S. 
Attorney's Office in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that conflict would even be greater if the exchange was  
accountable to shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt raised the issue publicly in a letter  
shortly after the NYSE announced in July it is considering shifting 
from a private, member-owned entity to a publicly owned company. 
</P>
<P>
	Another concern is whether an exchange can be trusted to monitor  
trading in its own shares. ``Can they police the trading of their 
own stock?'' asked James Angel, an associate professor of finance 
at Georgetown University. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE and Nasdaq believe going public will give them the  
flexibility to compete with low-cost electronic trading networks, 
known as ECNs. 
</P>
<P>
	Both markets have said the stock created in an IPO could be used  
to buy or team-up with an ECN. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE board members are also expected today to discuss the  
exchange's membership structure in the event of an IPO. One idea 
floated has members receiving stock in exchange for their seats on 
the exchange. But that plan could be scuttled by members who don't 
want to pay the capital gains taxes that would be assessed on that 
type of stock transaction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Possible Sister Act Looms at Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When the U.S. Tennis Association held its draw  
for the U.S. Open, No. 3 Venus Williams wound up in the top half 
and No. 7 Serena Williams landed in the bottom half. 
</P>
<P>
	Some tournaments have all the luck.  
</P>
<P>
	The blind draw created the possibility of an all-Williams final,  
something their father, Richard, predicted was going to happen all 
along. Right now, papa's prediction is right on target. 
</P>
<P>
	The Williams siblings have been down this road before. In March,  
Venus beat Serena in three sets at the finals of the Lipton, the 
first time sisters have met in a WTA Tour final. This, though, is 
the Open, a much larger stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Serena reached the third round Thursday, stopping Jelena  
Kostanic 6-4, 6-2. Venus got a third-round walkover when Henrieta 
Nagyova withdrew because of an injured right wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Serena Williams did not like the way she played against  
Kostanic, 
</P>
<P>
	``I really made way too many errors,'' she said. ``I was pretty  
erratic and not playing that great. But I came out with the big 
`W''' 
</P>
<P>
	Three more wins for Venus and four more for Serena and their  
father will face the toughest of circumstances -- picking between 
his daughters in the finals of the year's last Grand Slam. 
</P>
<P>
	This, of course, assumes considerable cooperation from  
top-seeded Martina Hingis, defending champion Lindsay Davenport and 
nine-time Grand Slam champion Monica Seles, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	Details, details, details.  
</P>
<P>
	Hingis got a little indignant over the ambitious prediction and  
popped off about it the other day, saying something about the 
Williams clan having big mouths. Serena, armed with a disarming 
smile, seemed at first uninterested in getting into a battle of 
words with the No. 1 player in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	And then she did anyway.  
</P>
<P>
	``She's always the type of person who says things, just speaks  
her mind,'' Williams said. ``I guess it has a little bit to do with 
not having a formal education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ouch!  
</P>
<P>
	``But you just have to somehow think more,'' Williams continued.  
``You have to use your brain more in the tennis world. She does 
that well on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's her opinion and she's entitled to her own opinion. She  
can say whatever she would like. I personally don't think my mouth 
is big if you're looking at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams then poked away at Hingis some more, talking about  
personal priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was No. 1 when she was 16,'' Serena said. ``That's  
something I've never done. I still haven't won a Grand Slam and 
she's won five. She's pursued other things. I'm pursuing education. 
I'm catching up in tennis, though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is studying Portuguese and wants to learn Spanish next.  
``I always try to keep my brain focused on something.,'' she said. 
``I don't like to get too much involved with a lot of nonsense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She will be attending an art school for fashion design in Fort  
Lauderdale, Fla., this fall, taking psychology courses as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I can help some of you guys,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	At 17, Serena sees tennis as a temporary stopover.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't see myself 10 years from now, in here,'' she said.  
``But I know Steffi Graf, when she was younger, said the same 
thing, and she was here 10 years later. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I really don't know. I mean right now I can't see it, but  
I'm not going to have a myopic view and say I'm not going to be 
here because you never know in the future.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 15:20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Second Russian Bank Employee Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Bank of New York on Thursday dismissed a  
second employee amid a probe into whether the bank's accounts were 
used by Russian mobsters and others to launder billions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Svetlana Kudryavtsev, an associate in the bank's Eastern  
European division, was fired for failing to cooperate with an 
internal investigation, a source familiar with the matter said. 
</P>
<P>
	A bank spokesman would only confirm that Ms. Kudryavtsev had  
been fired, and did not provide a reason. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, the bank fired Lucy Edwards, a London-based vice  
president, for gross misconduct, violation of the bank's internal 
policies, falsification of bank records and failure to cooperate 
with the bank's investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement authorities are looking into allegations that up  
to $10 billion was laundered through the bank's accounts by Russian 
organized crime and other figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank had earlier suspended Ms. Edwards along with another  
executive, Natasha Kagalovsky, who supervised the bank's business 
in Eastern Europe from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kagalovsky has denied any wrongdoing. So far no one has been  
charged with any crime in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank clearly is troubled that its name has been associated  
with the scandal. On Monday, bank chairman Thomas A. Renyi sent a 
memo to employees defending the institution's reputation and 
promising ``prompt action'' if any inappropriate action by bank 
staff was discovered. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scripps Howard Funding Fellowships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Scripps Howard Foundation will provide  
funding to the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism to 
give scholarships to four international students a year beginning 
this fall, the foundation announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The fellowships will be named for the late Jack R. Howard, a  
founding trustee and past president of the Scripps Howard 
Foundation. He was also president and general editorial manager of 
The E.W. Scripps Co., parent company of the Scripps Howard 
newspapers and television station group. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati-based foundation supports journalism education  
and internships, literacy programs, First Amendment causes and 
minority recruitment and development. 
</P>
<P>
	The journalism school's international program admits about 40  
students each year from more than 20 countries. Many qualified 
candidates are unable to attend because of limited financial aid, 
school officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jack R. Howard Fellowships will provide more than $40,000  
per student for full tuition and living expenses, foundation 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	To qualify for the fellowship, candidates must live outside the  
United States. Recipients will be selected on the basis of 
financial need and academic promise. 
</P>
<P>
	Foundation officials said they hope the students will return  
home and contribute to the development of journalism in their 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The students selected to receive scholarships for the 1999-2000  
academic year are Nguyen My Ha, Vietnam; Yiva Norberg, Sweden; 
Alfredo Sepulveda, Chile; and Alieu Sheriff, Sierra Leone. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biggest Insurer Covers New Pap Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A reversal by the nation's largest health  
insurer will give millions of women access to new types of Pap 
tests believed to be better, albeit more expensive, screening 
methods for cervical cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna Inc. on Thursday agreed to cover the ThinPrep Pap Test,  
which federal officials in 1996 said was more effective in 
detecting early signs of cervical cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, a top Aetna official said ThinPrep was not worth the  
extra cost, usually an additional $15 per test. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna now says new, as yet unpublished studies show ThinPrep  
increases the detection of abnormal or precancerous cells. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ThinPrep, Aetna said it will cover a similar  
test, PREP, made by AutoCyte, and an automated Pap test in which a 
computer, rather than a laboratory technician, scans Pap smear 
slides. 
</P>
<P>
	The coverage begins immediately.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time,'' said Dr. Peter Grossman, an  
obstetrician/gynecologist in Augusta, Ga. ``Aetna held out as long 
as they could, but as more studies show this is a more accurate 
test and more insurers come on board, there's a lot of peer 
pressure in the industry to cover the test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For patients, it will significantly reduce the chances that  
their Pap test will miss an abnormality,'' he said. Further, the 
ThinPrep lets doctors use the same sample to test for the presence 
of the HPV virus, which is known to cause cervical cancer, Grossman 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna's U.S. Healthcare unit, based in Blue Bell, Pa., provides  
health insurance to 21 million Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that it is best to have the treating physician make  
the decision'' about which type of Pap test to use, said Dr. Arnold 
Cohen, an obstetrician-gynecologist in charge of Aetna's women's 
health programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance coverage is crucial because ThinPrep typically costs  
$25 to $30 per test compared to $7 to $10 for the conventional Pap 
test. Aetna said its costs would increase as a result of the new 
coverage, but said it was too early to estimate the amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna joins most of the major health insurers to cover ThinPrep,  
which was approved in 1996 but has struggled until recently to 
build demand. The only major insurer not to cover the test is 
Kaiser Permanente, the nation's second-largest health maintenance 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	A Kaiser official said last month that the company is looking  
into covering the newer test. 
</P>
<P>
	About 13 percent of the 50 million Pap smears performed in the  
United States are now done with ThinPrep, which is made by Cytyc 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	ThinPrep makes it easier for lab technicians to interpret Pap  
smears and as a result find more abnormal or precancerous cells. 
</P>
<P>
	ThinPrep treats the cells with a liquid to remove blood and  
mucus that can hide cancerous changes. In November 1996, the 
federal government agreed that the Thin Prep system is more than 65 
percent more effective in diagnosing precancerous cells, which can 
lead to cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Named for Dr. George Papanicolaou, the pathologist who developed  
it in 1948, the Pap smear involves a doctor scraping cells from the 
cervix, at the neck of the uterus. 
</P>
<P>
	The cells are smeared onto a glass slide and sent to a lab,  
where a technician reads the slide under a microscope. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pap smear is far from infallible. It misses problems  
about 20 percent of the time, according to the National Institutes 
of Health, usually because of poor cervical samples or difficulty 
reading the slides at the lab. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a big deal,'' said Tom Gunderson, an analyst at Piper  
Jaffray, said of Aetna's decision. ``It is not only nice for Aetna 
and its customers, but is a tremendous boon for Cytyc's 
psychology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many doctors and health insurers initially were hesitant to  
replace the conventional diagnostic test that led to a big drop in 
cervical cancer deaths with a pricier version. Critics claimed that 
the new test was no better than the conventional one at identifying 
cancer, and argued ThinPrep would result in too many false 
warnings, thus unnecessarily alarming patients. 
</P>
<P>
	ThinPrep's increasing market share comes as Cytyc, based in  
Boxborough, Mass., has convinced more big health insurers -- 
including several Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans -- that the new 
test is worth the extra expense. Other major insurers that cover 
ThinPrep include United HealthCare, Cigna and Foundation Health. 
Another major insurer, Humana, provides partial coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna's Cohen said the new studies show ThinPrep helps detect  
more serious abnormal cells, which have a strong likelihood of 
becoming cancerous. He said older studies involved too few women, 
and showed the test only detected the type of abnormal cells that 
most likely would not become cancerous. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gander Scores in Saratoga Feature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Gander won his second straight  
race on Thursday, surging to a 5 1/4-length victory in the $125,000 
Albany Handicap at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner dueled head to head with Corroborator for the first  
seven furlongs. But Corroborator, the favorite, weakened and 
finished last in the field of five 3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Go Union Go was second, a half length behind, and Hearts at Risk  
was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Gander, a gelding ridden by Pat Day and carrying 117 pounds,  
covered nine furlongs in 1:48:4 on a fast track. He earned $75,000 
for Gatsas Stables. 
</P>
<P>
	He was winless with two seconds and two thirds in seven previous  
starts this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gander returned $6.60, $4.20 and $4.70. Go Union Go paid $6.90  
and $7.20 and Hearts At Risk showed at $5.40. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
