<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 14:50:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Demotes Ret. Maj. Gen. Hale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army took the highly unusual action  
Thursday of demoting a retired general who admitted during his 
court-martial last spring that he had adulterous affairs with the 
wives of four subordinates. 
</P>
<P>
	The officer, David Hale, vowed to challenge the decision in  
federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Secretary Louis Caldera reduced Hale's rank from a two-star  
major general to a one-star brigadier general. Hale, 53, was once a 
top commander of NATO forces in southern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale's attorney, Frank Spinner, issued a statement on Hale's  
behalf calling Caldera's action an ``unprecedented abuse of 
power.'' Spinner also said Caldera had acted in response to a 
``media campaign built on outrageous lies and outright deception.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Secretary Caldera is literally making up the rules as he goes  
along,'' Spinner said, adding that he knows of no other case in 
which the Army has demoted an officer after retirement. ``It is my 
belief that Congress never authorized the secretaries of the Army, 
Air Force and Navy to take this kind of action against a retired 
officer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By Caldera's action, Hale's current retirement pay of $6,250 a  
month will be reduced by about $750 a month. That cut is 
retroactive to Hale's retirement date of March 1, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Army lawyers said it will be up to the Defense Department's  
Finance and Accounting Service to decide whether to seek 
reimbursement from Hale for a portion of the pay he has collected 
since retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army said Hale's only option for appealing the decision  
would be to petition the Army Board for Correction of Military 
Records. 
</P>
<P>
	Donnamaria Carpino, one of the women Hale had sex with, issued a  
statement endorsing the Army's action. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am pleased that the Army has come to the stunning revelation  
that a court-martialed general should not retain all of his 
stars,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine, who wrote to Caldera in July  
urging that Hale's rank be reduced, said she was pleased the Army 
secretary ``closed the Hale case on a high note of justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This proportionate punishment sends a clear signal that the  
enforcement of regulations against sexual harassment must remain 
blind to rank or privilege,'' the senator said. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera acted on the unanimous recommendation of a panel of  
three active-duty generals convened in August to determine whether 
Hale should be allowed to keep his two-star rank. 
</P>
<P>
	When allegations of sexual misconduct surfaced in 1998, Hale  
denied them and even sued one of his accusers. At his court-martial 
last March he admitted to the charges and tearfully apologized for 
his actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was reprimanded and fined after the court-martial, but he  
was allowed to retire with honor and escape a possible 11-year term 
in a military prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was the highest-ranking Army officer to face court-martial  
since 1952. His sexual misconduct occurred while he worked in the 
NATO command in southern Europe. The resulting furor led the 
Pentagon to change its rules to bar top officers from retiring 
while facing allegations of wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army also decided to take the highly unusual step of  
court-martialing Hale even though he had retired a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other case in which an Army general faced court-martial  
since Congress enacted the Uniform Code of Military Justice in 1951 
was in 1952, when Maj. Gen. Robert Grow, military attache in 
Moscow, was tried on charges of dereliction of duty. Grow was 
reprimanded and suspended from command for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale pled guilty to seven counts of conduct unbecoming an  
officer and one count of lying to investigators. He was ordered to 
pay a $10,000 fine and forfeit $12,000 of his $75,744 annual 
pension for one year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Carpino said she is awaiting an Army decision about whether  
to reimburse her for the $26,000 she spent defending herself 
against a defamation suit filed by Hale last year in which he 
denied he had an adulterous relationship with her. Hale later 
withdrew the lawsuit and admitted to the relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	An Army official said discussions were underway on possible  
forms of financial compensation to Ms. Carpino. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
