<HEADLINE> Former Fed Judge Dies At 79 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- Almeric L.  
Christian, the first native of the U.S. Virgin Islands to be named 
a judge in the territory's District Court, has died at age 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian died Wednesday at a hospital in nearby Puerto Rico of  
an undisclosed illness, a written statement from the territory's 
governor, Charles Turnbull, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian was appointed by President Richard Nixon in 1969 and  
retired in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	His most controversial decisions were in two 1970s cases, in  
which he ruled that immigrants' children had a right to public 
education. 
</P>
<P>
	``Judge Christian made a profound impact on the judicial, social  
and political history of the Virgin Islands,'' Turnbull's statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian died one day after his 36th wedding anniversary to his  
wife, Shirley, who survives him. 
</P>
<P>
	He is also survived by a son, Adam, and daughters Rebecca  
Christian and Donna Christian-Christensen, who is the Virgin 
Islands' nonvoting delegate to the U.S. Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	His mother, Elena L. Christian, also survives him and is 103.  
</P>
<P>
	His funeral will be next Wednesday on the Caribbean island of  
St. Croix, the government said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
