<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Automakers Report Higher Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- With low prices and buyers flush with cash, the  
U.S. auto industry seems poised to blaze past its previous record 
for yearly sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Another piece of evidence arrived Thursday, when Ford Motor Co.  
said its U.S. sales had gone up 5 percent last month over August 
1998. Car sales jumped 11.5 percent, an increase Ford said was due 
in part to better fleet sales. Light truck sales were up 0.5 
percent compared to last year, when the automaker took advantage of 
a strike that wiped out much of General Motors Corp.'s truck 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the Ford Explorer and Expedition and Mercury  
Mountaineer sport utility vehicles set sales records for the month. 
That offset lower sales of the popular Ford Ranger and F-Series 
pickups, a problem Ford said was due to production line changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``August was another sensational month for Ford and the  
industry,'' said Bob Rewey, Ford's group vice president of 
marketing, sales and service. ``The conventional wisdom seems to be 
this is as good as it gets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall U.S. sales were up 20 percent. August's sales were at a  
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 17.8 million light vehicles, 
compared to a 14.8 million rate last year, according to Michigan 
research firm Morgan &AMP; Co. For the year through August, sales were 
at an annual rate of 16.9 million vehicles -- far more than the 
record of about 16.1 million in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Several economic conditions -- low unemployment, low inflation,  
low interest rates -- have combined to keep vehicles affordable. One 
analyst said the only surprise in August's reports was the strength 
in passenger cars, partly due to incentives and a lack of the most 
popular truck models. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be that consumers would prefer to buy light trucks if  
they could get them, but they can't get the one they want,'' said 
David Garrity, an analyst with Dresdner Kleinwort Benson in New 
York. ``So passenger cars become an acceptable substitute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, GM and DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler division as a group sold  
978,333 cars and light trucks last month -- a 26 percent increase 
over the strike-torn August of a year ago. The American nameplates 
captured about 66 percent of the market, with GM just below its 
goal of having 30 percent of the market by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say the standout performer of the Big Three was GM,  
who also had an incentive level that I would estimate is the 
highest in the industry,'' Garrity said. 
</P>
<P>
	European companies saw sales increase about 29 percent. Sales  
were up sharply at the two Ford-owned European nameplates, with 
Volvo up 11 percent and Jaguar up 87 percent behind the S-Type 
sedan. Another European automaker, BMW, saw sales zoom 31.5 percent 
on sales of the 2000 3-series. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian automakers gained about 7 percent as a group. Hyundai, Kia  
and Suzuki all posted gains. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
