<HEADLINE> Wildcats QB Loses Eligibility Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A Chicago judge on Thursday upheld an NCAA rule  
that bars Northwestern quarterback Zachary Kustok from playing in 
Saturday's opening game against Miami of Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge Michael Getty refused to immediately overturn the  
rule, which would keep Kustok from playing for the Wildcats in 
their first seven games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Getty did offer to hold a hearing later that might get  
Kustok onto the field by the season's third or fourth game, 
attorneys said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kustok played one season at Notre Dame but never got into a game  
and decided to attend school elsewhere. He claims the NCAA 
compliance officer at Kansas told him last fall that he would still 
have three seasons of football eligibility at another Division IA 
school if he successfully completed one year at a junior college. 
</P>
<P>
	Kustok completed a year at Moraine Valley Community College in  
Palos Hills and accepted a scholarship to Northwestern in February. 
He expected to be eligible, starting with the opening game. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA, however, ruled that Kustok must sit out the first  
seven games. Northwestern appealed the NCAA ruling but lost. 
</P>
<P>
	Kustok attorney Peter Rush told the court that his client  
shouldn't be penalized merely because the Kansas compliance officer 
gave him bad information about his eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20-year-old Kustok has been practicing as a backup to  
starter Nick Kreinbrink. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
