<HEADLINE> Injured Marion Jones Ends Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- It's wait until next year for sprinter  
Marion Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	Back spasms will prevent Jones from competing again this year,  
but she still plans to seek an unprecedented five gold medals in at 
the Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	She still hopes to win gold in the 100 and 200 meters, long jump  
and 400- and 1,600-meter relays next year, her agent, Charlie 
Wells, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But for now, while she is improving, ``she is not well enough to  
compete,'' Wells said in a telephone interview from Brussels, 
Belgium, where Jones had hoped to resume her season at a Golden 
League meet Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones collapsed on the track in the semifinals of the women's  
200 meters at the world championships last week in Seville, Spain, 
suffering from cramps and back spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	She returned to the United States over the weekend for further  
evaluation. Her doctors recommended she not compete again this 
season, Wells said. The former North Carolina basketball and track 
star trains at North Carolina State. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate, and we know her many fans will be  
disappointed, but it was not worth the risk,'' Wells told The News 
&AMP; Observer of Raleigh. He said Jones would continue to be evaluated 
in the United States, but declined to elaborate on the extent of 
her injury. 
  	   	
</P>
