<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 07:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea To Meet on Seoulbank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The government's financial watchdog  
agency will meet Friday to decide whether to declare Seoulbank 
insolvent and inject additional government funds into the ailing 
bank, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting by the Financial Supervisory Commission comes the  
same week that talks broke down between the government and HSBC 
Holdings PLC over the British bank's acquisition of a controlling 
stake in Seoulbank. The two sides could not reach agreement over 
the terms. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides signed a memorandum of understanding in February  
calling for HSBC to buy a 70-percent stake in Seoulbank for $700 
million, with the Seoul government keeping the remaining 30 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides differed on the amount of bad loans that the  
government would have covered after selling the majority interest 
in Seoulbank. 
</P>
<P>
	The government invested $1.34 billion in Seoulbank and Korea  
First Bank last year, effectively nationalizing them. 
</P>
<P>
	Sale of the two troubled banks was one of the conditions laid  
down by the International Monetary Fund in exchange for its $58 
billion bailout of South Korea's sinking economy in late 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	President Kim Dae-jung's government insisted on selling the  
banks to foreigners to demonstrate its willingness to open the 
cloistered domestic financial sector. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
