<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burned Firefighter Recovers in DC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- District of Columbia firefighters who greeted  
their colleague, Joseph Morgan Jr., with hugs Wednesday said there 
were times during the past three months when they didn't think he 
would make it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was bandaged from head to toe. He looked like a mummy,''  
said Assistant Fire Chief William Mould. 
</P>
<P>
	But Morgan, of Brentwood, Md., was determined to recover from  
the severe burns that covered 60 percent of his body. He sustained 
them while fighting a blaze in a townhouse on May 30. Two other 
firefighters, Anthony Phillips and Louis Matthews, were killed. 
Smoke detectors allowed the residents to escape without injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan, 37, left Washington Hospital Center a week ago. Doctors  
said he would be off the job at least a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I plan on cutting that time in half,'' he said, during a news  
conference at his Northeast fire station Wednesday. ``Doctors say 
my wounds are healing at a miraculous rate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan said he will continue to have physical therapy three  
times a week. 
</P>
<P>
	He credited the support he received from people in the  
Washington area and around the world with helping him to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	The May fire in the basement of a townhouse at 3146 Cherry Lane,  
N.E., was electrical, said Fire Chief Donald Edwards. Firefighters 
are still investigating what went so wrong, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
