<DOCNO> APW19990902.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belluzzo To Run Microsoft Web Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. today named Richard Belluzzo, a  
computer industry veteran who most recently headed California-based 
Silicon Graphics Inc., to run its Internet operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Belluzzo, 45, will oversee Microsoft's Consumer and Commerce  
Group as the company seeks to expand its online commerce services. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tremendous opportunity given the fundamental change the  
Internet brings to the world,'' Belluzzo said in a telephone 
interview from Microsoft headquarters in suburban Redmond. ``Having 
a chance to be part of a team that has the resources, the vision 
and the technical strength that Microsoft has is a tremendous 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Chase and Jon DeVaan, who had jointly headed the Consumer  
and Commerce Group since its formation in March, were named to 
positions directly under Belluzzo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's announcements underscore our commitment to executing  
decisively and rapidly in the online services space by forming a 
seasoned management team that is dedicated to improving and 
facilitating commerce for consumers,'' said Microsoft President 
Steve Ballmer, to whom Belluzzo will report. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballmer called Belluzzo ``a very focused businessman, a great  
leader and a great lover of the consumer'' who will ``help 
complement our online business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belluzzo resigned last week as chairman and chief executive  
officer of Silicon Graphics, a position he held for less than two 
years. Before he moved to Silicon Graphics, Belluzzo had a 22-year 
career at Hewlett-Packard, where he became the No. 2 executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's recent Web investments have focused mainly on  
communications, shopping, travel, scheduling and personal finance. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the company has pulled back from some of its media  
ventures. It recently sold off its collection of city arts and 
entertainment guides, MSN Sidewalk, for about $240 million to 
Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's Consumer and Commerce Group's was formed as part of  
a reorganization announced in March and is designed to link 
consumers and businesses online. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
