<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Indicted in Olympic Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Olympic bribery investigation produced  
its second federal criminal case with the indictment of the son of 
a powerful International Olympic Committee official. 
</P>
<P>
	John Kim, whose father is IOC executive board member Un-yong  
Kim, was indicted in Utah on Wednesday on a charge that he lied to 
the FBI about the work he did for Keystone Communications of Salt 
Lake City. The charge stems from statements the younger Kim made to 
the FBI on Feb. 23 in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Wednesday, a federal judge in Brooklyn, N.Y., unsealed a  
16-count indictment alleging Kim used a fraudulently obtained green 
card to enter the United States 16 times from 1995 to 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brooklyn indictment says Kim was put on the Keystone payroll  
by the Salt Lake Bid Committee as part of a scheme to help him 
obtain his green card and to influence his father to vote for Salt 
Lake City's Olympic bid. 
</P>
<P>
	John Kim was notified in Korea of the charges by his wife, who  
was confronted Wednesday at their home on Long Island by five armed 
Justice Department agents, Kim family spokesman Bill Schechter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agents came to the home, ``flashing their badges and weapons  
without a warrant, to the dismay of his wife, 6-year-old daughter 
and 3-year-old son,'' Schechter said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They pushed past (Kim's wife) to the room where the children  
were. They were frightened by the procedure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said last week that he returned to South Korea and forfeited  
his green card at the U.S. embassy there. 
</P>
<P>
	Schechter also said the Justice Department has a copy of a  
letter on Salt Lake Organizing Committee stationery written by bid 
committee head Tom Welch saying Utah Republican Sen. Orrin Hatch 
``is prepared to provide special legislation if necessary to 
overcome any problems that John may have on his green card.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schechter said Hatch staffers made follow-up calls to Kim  
restating the offer of help. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said he only advised the committee on immigration  
procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	``My office furnished the information as we routinely do with  
all constituent requests for assistance with immigration problems. 
To my recollection, no other action was taken,'' said Hatch, who is 
seeking the Republican nomination for the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim is alleged to have received $104,000 through phony contracts  
and invoices until Keystone President David E. Simmons finally 
fired him in October 1992 for ``nonperformance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim then arranged to reimburse Simmons $40,000 to partly cover  
the expense of his own employment, and the bid committee added 
$78,000 in disguised payments to Keystone Communications, according 
to the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, meanwhile, claimed his employment was permanent and  
full-time when he applied for permanent U.S. residency. Prosecutors 
maintain Kim's employment was temporary and depended on Keystone's 
being reimbursed by the bid committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Kim told the FBI agents in February that he did  
not know the bid committee reimbursed Simmons for his salary. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also accused of lying about consulting payments for  
services he never performed. The charges also say he denied a 
relationship with a company named Kobee, which prosecutors say 
funneled some money for Kim's salary through the bid committee to 
Simmons. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors contend Kim introduced one of Kobee's officers  
to Welch and arranged a bogus consulting contract and a $20,000 
payment from the bid committee to Kobee and then to Keystone. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 3, Simmons pleaded guilty to a federal misdemeanor tax  
charge. He said he helped create a sham job for Kim and 
manufactured a paper trail to cover up the arrangement and was 
reimbursed for Kim's salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons was charged with illegally deducting Kim's salary as a  
business expense on his tax forms. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons told SLOC investigators that the deal was approved by  
Un-yong Kim and masterminded by Welch. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Kim sued Simmons in Seoul District Civil Court,  
claiming Simmons' testimony was false and had hurt Kim's integrity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
