<DOCNO> APW19990902.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 10:32:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Delays on New Loans to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration has delayed  
deciding whether it should approve new loans to Russia from the 
International Monetary Fund until a full accounting is made of the 
money already lent. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, which has been put on the defensive by  
suspicions that IMF loans to Russia were illegally diverted through 
U.S. banks, wants to make sure the money ``is going to 
reform-oriented projects,'' said John Podesta, the White House 
chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	A report released today by the assistant inspector general at  
the Agriculture Department, based on a prior review of U.S. food 
aid to the Russian government, concluded there are adequate 
controls to prevent siphoning off of the surplus grain, corn and 
other farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also noted, however, that ships carrying grain cargo  
had been spotted leaving a port on Russia's Black Sea early this 
year. The food aid agreements with the United States prohibit 
Russia ``from re-exporting any of the commodities ... and restrain 
the export of similar commodities'' unless they were sold before 
the accords were signed in December, the report says. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no evidence the ships' cargo was stolen U.S. grain,  
according to Agriculture Department officials. The ship sightings 
raised concern, however, because Russian organized crime groups are 
believed to have infiltrated ports where the U.S. food shipments 
are delivered. 
</P>
<P>
	Podesta defended the administration's record in dealing with  
Russia, citing successes in getting the Russians to withdraw from 
the Baltics and persuading former Soviet republics Ukraine and 
Kazakstan to give up nuclear weapons placed in their territory by 
the old Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some progress. We've had some problems. And we're  
aware of the allegations of (Russian) corruption. I think ... we've 
tried to deal with them,'' Podesta said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators are looking into allegations that Russian  
gangsters have laundered some $10 billion, possibly including IMF 
funds, through the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, as a presidential candidate, already has  
come under fire from some Republican rivals for his close 
relationship with Russian leaders and his hands-on role in 
U.S.-Russian diplomacy, particularly as chairman of a joint 
commission on bilateral ties with former Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian government says the case has been overblown by  
Western media and politicians. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov called 
it part of a deliberate policy by ``certain circles who don't want 
Russia to reassert its role as a great power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's special envoy to the IMF and to other foreign lenders  
resigned suddenly today, saying he had fulfilled his mission and 
wanted to run for parliament. Mikhail Zadornov gave no indication 
that his resignation was connected to concerns that the IMF may 
delay new loans to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	He insisted that all IMF aid to Russia had been used properly,  
and predicted the next loan installment would come as scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF spokesman Thomas Dawson today reiterated statements made  
earlier this week that the organization has seen no evidence that 
IMF loan money to Russia was diverted. The IMF has ``absolutely no 
evidence of any diversion or misuse of IMF funds,'' Dawson told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF head Michel Camdessus said this week that adequate controls  
are in place and he sees no reason to block new aid to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We take the allegations extremely seriously. We will continue  
to look at any new reports or old reports,'' Dawson said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted recent statements by Clinton administration  
officials that so far U.S. investigators have found no evidence of 
any misuse of IMF money. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson said Russia now owes $16 billion of the $22 billion that  
the 182-nation IMF has lent it since 1992, ``so they are paying us 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF board is expected to soon consider approving a second,  
$640 million installment under a $4.5 billion loan package for 
Russia that was previously authorized. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, in an interview in  
Wednesday's USA Today, said the administration will not support 
approval of the next installment ``without adequate safeguards to 
assure that any funds disbursed are used properly (and) without 
adequate accounting for the previous use of funds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As these investigations continue ... we'll have to make  
judgments about what constitutes a satisfactory accounting,'' 
Summers told the newspaper. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
