<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y., Fla., Texas Hold Tax Holidays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Clothes strewn all over the place, lines for the  
fitting rooms, long waits at the cash register. 
</P>
<P>
	A scene from last year's Christmas rush? Nope -- just a glimpse  
of what happens when the sales tax on clothing is suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of our retailers told us, `If we run a 10 percent-off  
sale, shoppers just walk by and yawn.' But when they're getting an 
8 1/4 percent price reduction as a result of the tax holiday, they 
come in droves,'' said Mickey Moore of the Texas Retailers 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas, Florida and New York all dropped their sales tax on  
clothing for several days before the start of school. Instead of 
simply causing a shift in spending -- with shoppers buying less 
before and after the tax holiday -- the event has led to actual net 
increases in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a real increase,'' said Duncan Muir, a spokesman for  
J.C. Penney. ``Sales pretty much maintain what they have been 
before and after. Our experience is, it does get into a 
double-digit increase in sales during the tax-free period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But why would shoppers end up spending so much more than they  
are saving? 
</P>
<P>
	``The psychology of it is, you're not paying a tax,'' said Ted  
Potrikus, vice president of the Retail Council, which represents 
5,000 stores in New York State. ``It's a tax cut, and you don't 
have to file for it or wait until April 15 for it. It's immediate 
gratification. It's like sanctioned tax evasion. For a week, you 
don't have to give your money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Golder, a professor at New York University's Stern School  
of Business, said publicity -- essentially free advertising from the 
media -- and a desire among shoppers to do what everyone else is 
doing also play a role. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the idea that shopping becomes a social thing and  
community activity -- something to talk about at work, with friends 
and family,'' Golder said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York has been suspending the state's 4 percent clothing tax  
for two weeks a year -- before school and again in mid-January -- 
since 1997. Most counties and cities also suspend local taxes 
during the period, so in places like New York City, shoppers save 
8.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The discount increased sales as much as 300 percent for some  
retailers the first time the holiday took place, according to the 
Retail Council. Increases in the years since remain in the 20 
percent to 30 percent range. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's tax-free week in New York began Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I overbought,'' said Nancy Petrone, clutching  
one of a half-dozen shopping bags filled with clothes for her two 
kids just before they tumbled to the ground at the Staten Island 
Mall. ``This is just the right time of year to buy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You bet I was waiting for this week,'' said another shopper,  
Ann Farrell, also weighed down with packages. ``With three kids all 
wanting new school stuff, you've got to do it now. Between the 
sales, no tax, no New Jersey tolls, I really save a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tolls are an issue for New Yorkers because many of them  
travel to New Jersey -- where there is no clothing tax -- to do their 
shopping. Other parts of New York state near Pennsylvania and 
Massachusetts, which also charge no clothing tax, have the same 
problem. In March, New York will permanently abolish the clothing 
tax on items under $110, partly to remain competitive with these 
other states. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have thousands of commuters who come into the city every  
day who ordinarily would not make a purchase in New York City, but 
now they will,'' said Macy's vice president Edward Goldberg. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar phenomenon occurred in Florida during its tax holiday,  
July 31 to Aug. 8. The tax on clothing under $100 was suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of our retailers in Tallahassee said he looked in his  
parking lot and a number of the cars were all from Georgia,'' said 
Lori Elliott of the Florida Retail Federation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
