<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Said To Offer To Buy House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) -- The vacationing President Clinton and his  
wife have made a bid on a Georgian colonial house they toured last 
weekend in a New York City suburb, according to sources familiar 
with the Clintons' hunt for a post-White House residence. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're involved in trying to secure that house, in trying to  
buy it,'' a source familiar with the negotiations said Wednesday. 
``They've made some progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons offered less than the nearly $1.7 million asking  
price, but sources would not detail the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple spent two hours touring the 110-year-old Westchester  
County house on a little more than an acre of parklike grounds. The 
house is near golf courses and boasts a swimming pool, lush 
landscaping and an exercise room on the top floor. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials demurred when pressed for details, saying  
they didn't want to complicate negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any mystery here,'' said White House  
spokesman Jake Siewert. ``The president and first lady said they 
liked the House that they saw in Chappaqua.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The house apparently passed security muster this week. The  
Secret Service checked out the house with an eye to protecting 
Clinton when he is a private citizen. Former presidents have a 
small security detail. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Clintons toured historic sites in upstate New  
York while taking time out for plenty of glad-handing with locals 
who might one day help elect Mrs. Clinton their senator. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum tour was heavy on sites honoring 19th century women  
who fought to free slaves and to gain voting rights. The Clintons 
drew crowds at every stop on a five-hour sightseeing trip of the 
Finger Lakes region, where the family is spending the final week of 
their summer vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're off on an excursion,'' Clinton said as the couple set  
out after coffee at a cafe in the village of Skaneateles. They are 
staying at a borrowed estate just outside the village of restored 
Victorian houses and shops that cater to summer crowds of boaters 
and sightseers. 
</P>
<P>
	Their stay is part relaxation and part political maneuvering, as  
Mrs. Clinton calculates whether to mount a formal campaign for a 
Senate seat in New York next year. She scheduled two fund-raising 
parties later today for her exploratory campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The family's 16-day vacation in Massachusetts and New York was  
punctuated by political fund raising that will yield an estimated 
$800,000 for her campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Clintons held hands while a guide at the  
Harriet Tubman Home museum in Auburn described how the escaped 
slave made 19 trips back to the South to lead 300 others to 
freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was given a T-shirt with a quotation from Tubman,  
whose bravery and clever use of the ``Underground Railroad'' 
network of safehouses and escape routes earned her the nickname 
``Moses of her people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you are tired, keep going. If you are scared, keep going.  
If you are hungry, keep going. If you want to taste freedom, keep 
going,'' the quotation read. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Mrs. Clinton collected an unofficial endorsement from the  
mayor of Seneca Falls, considered the birthplace of the women's 
rights movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Corrado, a self-described Republican, was among the crowd of  
well-wishers in Seneca Falls. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beautiful. I like it,'' Corrado, said of the idea of a Clinton  
Senate run. 
</P>
<P>
	The rangers at the Women's Rights National Historical Park were  
impressed with the president's knowledge of the suffragette 
movement, and jokingly offered him a job when he leaves the White 
House after the 2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I can work for cheap,'' Clinton said with a smile.  
``I've got a good pension.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
