<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montreal's Molson Centre Up for Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Saying it is tired of paying high property  
taxes, beer giant Molson Inc. wants to sell the Molson Centre, a 
21,273-seat arena built for its Montreal Canadiens franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive James Arnett made the announcement late Thursday  
at a news conference where businessman Pierre Boivin was named the 
new president of the NHL team. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnett also confirmed that Molson will keep the Canadiens, and  
gave Boivin a mandate to improve its financial and on-ice 
performance. The landmark arena in downtown Montreal was completed 
in 1996 at a cost to the beer company of $235 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related move, Molson is also seeking buyers for its 50 per  
cent interest in Universal Concerts Canada and Molstar TV 
Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnett said selling the large arena is one option; the company  
could also seek a financial partner or refinance it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not strategically important for us to own it,'' said  
Arnett, noting that Molson did not own the Canadiens' previous 
legendary home, the Montreal Forum. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnett claimed that the Molson Centre pays the highest city  
taxes of any similar arena in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Molson's sports and entertainment division lost $3.7 million in  
the first quarter ended June 30, compared with a profit of $3.4 
million in the same period in 1998. This can be attributed mainly 
to five home playoff games the Canadiens played in 1998, while in 
1999 the team did not make the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Molson has sold off its non-brewing assets, and  
bought back the 50 per cent of the brewery it didn't own. However, 
Arnett said the company has decided that the hockey club ``is a 
criticial strategic asset to our core business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bovin, whose career was in the sporting goods industry, has been  
ordered ``to enhance the relationship between the Molson and 
Canadiens brands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also becomes executive vice-president at Molson Inc.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
