<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Panel Recommends Bid Visit Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Headlines Headlines Headlines .....    	
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- International Olympic Committee members might be  
given the chance to visit bidding cities, but only under strict 
conditions, a reform panel recommended Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A working group of the IOC 2000 reform commission decided that  
members on some occasions might feel the need for viewing bidding 
cities, and there should not be an absolute ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Visits were banned after disclosures of vote-buying in the  
selection of Salt Lake City for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things we discussed was if, for example, there was  
a bid from a city that has never hosted the games, and that city 
may have a very low profile but in actuality is a very strong 
candidate,'' Anita DeFrantz, the IOC vice president who heads the 
working group, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Visits would go ahead only ``if the IOC deems it necessary,''  
and under very strong conditions designed to prevent members 
accepting lavish hospitality. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the members themselves would be allowed to go -- in  
organized groups, not individually -- and not their spouses or other 
members of their family, said DeFrantz. 
</P>
<P>
	They would be allowed to go only once, and the trips would take  
place within a specific time frame, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said it was not yet clear whether, in such  
circumstances, members also would be allowed to visit all the 
bidding cities or only the ones where it was ``deemed necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members resigned or were expelled because of the Salt  
Lake City scandal after they or members of their family were found 
to have accepted hospitality, gifts, medical care and job offers, 
apparently as a bribe to obtain their votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve cities have expressed interest in bidding for the 2008  
Olympics. The decision will be made at an IOC meeting in Moscow in 
September 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The working party will formally present its recommendations at a  
meeting of the IOC 2000 commission Sept. 25, and the report from 
that session will be taken to an IOC meeting in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
