<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, S. Korea Discuss N. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi on Thursday  
held out the prospect of multilateral cooperation with North Korea 
if it forgoes testing a long-range missile. 
</P>
<P>
	``If North Korea freezes the launch of another missile it is  
possible Japan, South Korea and the United States can promote 
relations with it in a forward-looking manner,'' Obuchi said at a 
joint news conference with visiting South Korean Prime Minister Kim 
Jong-pil. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi did not elaborate, but said such a development would be  
``beneficial'' to North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, who arrived Wednesday on a five-day official visit, said he  
hopes that a ``good outcome'' will emerge from a new round of talks 
between U.S. and North Korean officials scheduled for Sept. 7-11 in 
Berlin, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim also reiterated that Tokyo and Seoul will work closely with  
Washington to persuade the North not to carry out a missile test. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and his  
South Korean counterpart, Cho Sung-tae, agreed to work closely to 
stop North Korea from launching a new ballistic missile. 
</P>
<P>
	``Confirming that another North Korean missile launch poses a  
threat to peace and stability on the Korean peninsula and in 
Northeast Asia, the ministers agreed to closely cooperate to curb 
it,'' the two said in a joint news release after their meeting in 
Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no explanations about how the two countries would  
cooperate. But Sergeyev said recently that Moscow was trying to 
convince North Korea through political and diplomatic channels to 
give up the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Reclusive North Korea shocked Japan, South Korea and other  
countries in the region last August, when it test-fired a missile 
that sailed over Japan and into the Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials have said the launch was a test of a Taepodong  
missile that is capable of reaching any part of the Japanese 
archipelago. North Korea has claimed it launched a satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts believe the North may try to test fire another more  
advanced missile capable of reaching as far as Alaska or Hawaii, 
though recently the nation has hinted a launch may not be imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	In nearly 90 minutes of talks, Kim and Obuchi also agreed to  
soon begin full-fledged negotiations to hammer out a bilateral 
treaty aimed at bolstering investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi said that the two leaders also agreed to further promote  
cultural, academic and youth exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that officials will consider ways to strengthen air  
transportation links between the Japan and South Korea during the 
World Cup soccer tournament in 2002. The two nations will co-host 
the event. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim is scheduled to meet with Emperor Akihito on Friday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
