<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Fined in Power Plant Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will pay $7 million but not be  
held criminally responsible for a boiler explosion in which six 
workers died and 14 were injured, the state's top workplace safety 
regulator said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement includes a $1.5 million fine -- the largest ever  
levied by the Michigan Occupational Health and Safety 
Administration, said Kathy Wilbur, director of the state Department 
of Consumer and Industry Services. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 2 automaker also will finance new safety programs,  
medical research into burn treatment and set up a scholarship fund 
in memory of the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``This historic agreement cannot reclaim lost lives. It cannot  
restore broken bodies,'' Ms. Wilbur said. ``But it can ease the 
suffering of the victims and their families by assuring a safer and 
healthier work environment for all Ford employees in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A seven-month investigation of the Feb. 1 explosion at Ford's  
Rouge complex in Dearborn revealed 15 workplace safety violations. 
The blast was caused by a buildup of natural gas in the boiler, 
which lacked adequate controls for shutting it down safely, 
investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old boiler was being shut down for routine monthly  
inspection, but one of two crews inadvertently left open a gas main 
leading into the furnace. 
</P>
<P>
	Human error -- beginning with inadequate training and culminating  
with maintenance crews' failure to communicate during the shutdown 
-- was the overriding cause, Ms. Wilbur said. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement, reached Monday night among representatives of  
Ford, the state and the United Auto Workers union, focuses on 
prevention as well as punishment, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This settlement agreement allows the company to focus its  
efforts on accident prevention,'' James Padilla, Ford group vice 
president for manufacturing, said in a statement. ``We cannot 
change the terrible events of the past, but we can work hard to 
make our workplaces safer in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the fine, the settlement calls for Ford to pay $5.5  
million for boiler safety, burn research and treatment, a 
scholarship fund for UAW members and their families, and state 
costs. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
