<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Outlines Issues on N.H. tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW LONDON, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate John  
McCain said Thursday the government should consider creating a 
guest-worker program for would-be illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as Mexican, El Salvadoran and Guatemalan young men  
can't feed themselves and their families where they live, they're 
going to come to America,'' the Arizona senator said. ``And there 
are many jobs American citizens won't do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giving those jobs -- ranging from farm work to jobs in wealthy  
suburbs -- to foreigners would alleviate their desire to immigrate 
illegally, McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a wide-ranging speech before 200 people in New London's  
town hall, McCain also said the United States should be ready to 
use force to defend Taiwan's independence from China. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to directly threaten China,'' said McCain, who is  
touring the state by bus. But, ``I don't think the U.S. should sit 
by and watch that kind of aggression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he remained optimistic that the next generation of  
Chinese leaders will embrace democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the speech, McCain focused on issues that have won him the  
most support so far -- China policy, the military, and campaign 
finance. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also touched on other issues, such as how to provide  
prescription drugs to elderly patients who cannot afford them. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the government should encourage the use of medical  
savings accounts, provide tax breaks for the self-employed and work 
to lower exorbitant inflation in medical costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of those in attendance said McCain earned their respect  
with his willingness to contradict the GOP on several issues, such 
as his proposal to rid political campaigns of unregulated 
donations. He said special interests control both parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``No longer are you represented in Washington unless you can  
give huge amounts of soft money,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain was to continue the New Hampshire bus tour Friday in  
Concord. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
