<DOCNO> APW19990902.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 03:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Willie Stargell Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Hall of Famer Willie Stargell is undergoing  
treatment for an undisclosed serious health problem with one of his 
organs. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh Pirates officials have refused comment about  
Stargell, one their greatest players ever and an assistant to 
general manager Cam Bonifay. 
</P>
<P>
	But former teammates and friends have become increasingly  
concerned about the 58-year-old Stargell, who has had health 
problems for about 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell was admitted to a Pittsburgh hospital under an assumed  
name for tests about three weeks ago, according to three sources 
close to the Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	During his hospital stay, the former Pirates star underwent  
blood tests and dialysis, a source said, speaking on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources did not disclose Stargell's specific ailment. But a  
former teammate, who did not want to be identified, said Stargell 
has undergone kidney dialysis for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell was moved recently from the Pittsburgh hospital to  
another medical care facility to undergo additional treatment and 
care, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately known if Stargell was still in the  
Pittsburgh area or had been moved to a facility near his home in 
Wilmington, N.C., where he lives with his wife, Margaret. 
</P>
<P>
	Pirates managing general partner Kevin McClatchy, who hired  
Stargell in 1997, has ordered team officials not to comment about 
Stargell. 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell has not been seen in the owner's box at Three Rivers  
Stadium, where he often watched games, for about a month. But such 
absences were not uncommon as Stargell often left town to watch 
minor league games, attend baseball card shows to sign autographs 
or to return to his home. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the sources said Stargell first began having health  
problems after his weight increased significantly following his 
retirement in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after rejoining former Pirates manager Chuck Tanner's  
coaching staff in Atlanta in 1986, he sought medical treatment for 
a heart condition -- apparently, an irregular heartbeat -- and was 
ordered to lose weight, one of the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell later dropped a considerable amount of weight, and  
looked to be at nearly his playing weight when he returned to the 
Pirates in February 1997 at McClatchy's request. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stargell put on weight after rejoining the Pirates, and team  
officials have known for months he had health problems. Unable to 
stand for long stretches, he usually sat on the dugout bench to 
watch batting practice, often shooing away anyone who blocked his 
view. 
</P>
<P>
	While in the dugout, Stargell sought out former teammates and  
friends for conversation and willingly gave interviews, even though 
his speech had slowed noticeably in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates have tried to deflect questions about Stargell's  
health, but team officials have received calls recently from former 
teammates and friends inquiring about his condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is one of the greatest team leaders ever in sports,''  
Tanner said recently when interviewed about the 1979 World Series 
champion Pirates. ``He lifted that team up and carried it to the 
World Series. Any time you needed a big hit that season, Willie 
gave it to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell hit 32 homers in 1979, several years after it was  
generally believed his career was winding down. He also hit 48 
homers for the 1971 World Series champion Pirates -- the most by any 
Pirates player in the last 49 years -- but was overshadowed in the 
World Series by Hall of Fame teammate Roberto Clemente. 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell played for the Pirates from 1962-82, batting .282 with  
475 homers -- he had seven more in the postseason -- and 1,540 RBIs. 
He is the Pirates' career leader in home runs, RBIs and extra-base 
hits (953). 
</P>
<P>
	Known as ``Pops'' while leading the 1979 ``We Are Family''  
Pirates, he shared the National League MVP award that year with 
Keith Hernandez of St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stargell also was the MVP of the NL playoffs and World Series  
and is the only player to win all three awards in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988, Stargell became the 200th member of the Hall of Fame  
and the 17th elected in his first year of induction. He later 
became the Braves' special assistant to the director of player 
personnel, a title he held until returning to Pittsburgh. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
