<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> When Hot Toys Get Cold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Every few years, there seems to be a must-have toy across the  
nation. But what happens to these toys once the next big thing 
catches on? 
</P>
<P>
	Some popular toys and where they are now.  

</P>
<P>
                          *Holiday Barbie    	
</P>
<P>
	Launched by Mattel in 1988, Holiday Barbie was among the  
nation's best-selling dolls in 1995 and '96. But sales soon fell, 
and the doll was discontinued this year. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Cabbage Patch Kids    	
</P>
<P>
	Sales of the pudgy dolls went as high as $4 billion for Coleco  
in the 1980s. The dolls, now made by Mattel, remain somewhat 
popular, and some original handmade versions command thousands of 
dollars from collectors. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Teddy Ruxpin    	
</P>
<P>
	Worlds of Wonder began selling the talking bears in 1985, and  
more than 7 million were sold within a few years. But many were 
returned because of malfunctions, and Worlds of Wonder filed for 
bankruptcy. Teddy Ruxpin was brought back in 1998 by Yes! 
Entertainment, which this year filed for bankruptcy court 
protection. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Hula Hoop    	
</P>
<P>
	Wham-O introduced the Hula Hoop in 1958, and 25 million were  
sold in just a few months. After two years, the number surpassed 
100 million. Sales slowed by the early '60s, but the plastic, 
circular rings are still found in most large toy stores. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
