<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Wants To Apologize to Author </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRYEBURG, Maine (AP) -- The driver whose van injured Stephen King  
as he was walking alongside a road said he would like to apologize 
to the author face-to-face. 
</P>
<P>
	The horror writer is recuperating after six operations to repair  
broken bones and a collapsed lung from the June 19 accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got distracted,'' Bryan Smith said in Wednesday's Bangor  
Daily News. ``It was one time, and one time only. I'm very, very 
sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he suffers from depression over the accident. He said  
he went off the road while trying to control his dog. A grand jury 
convenes Sept. 30 to decide whether charges should be filed against 
Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	King said he has no intention of suing Smith but wants his  
driver's license revoked. Smith's driving record includes four 
speeding violations, operating under the influence and driving to 
endanger. But he insisted he's not dangerous, as King has claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe 15 years ago he could say that. Fifteen? Twenty? Yes. I  
was dangerous,'' Smith said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
