<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 737 Dogged by Safety Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At any moment, there are roughly 800 Boeing  
737s flying somewhere in the world, making it the most common 
airliner in the sky. But there are lingering safety questions, and 
the crash of a 737 Tuesday in Argentina has put the airplane back 
in the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report released in July, the National Transportation Safety  
Board said there continue to be problems with the 737's rudder 
system, despite design changes prompted by fatal accidents and 
near-misses. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the safety board said the Federal Aviation  
Administration was concerned about the 737's rudder when it first 
certified the plane in the mid-1960s and again in 1997, shortly 
before it certified the latest series of the airplane, the 
so-called Next Generation 737. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, Boeing was able to overcome those concerns by  
arguing that the rudder -- a panel on the tail that controls the 
plane in the case of a crosswind or a lost engine -- was safe and 
reliable. The board, the lead investigator in transportation 
accidents, challenges that contention. 
</P>
<P>
	``The safety board is concerned that the new features (of the  
redesigned rudder system) do not address all of these 
malfunctions,'' the five members wrote in the report, their final 
word on the 1994 crash of a USAir 737 outside Pittsburgh. All 132 
aboard were killed when the plane suddenly spiraled into a ravine 
shortly before landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the LAPA airlines 737 that crashed Tuesday in  
Buenos Aires, Argentina, had lifted just a few feet off the runway 
when it skimmed across a road and crashed beside a golf course. 
Authorities said at least 64 people were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	A sudden loss of thrust would tend to point to an engine problem  
-- not one with the rudder -- but it will be months before 
investigators determine a cause. The NTSB, the FAA and Boeing have 
sent investigators to the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	The same parties are continuing to examine the April crash of a  
Turkish Airlines 737 in southeastern Turkey. That plane crashed 
eight minutes after takeoff after becoming engulfed in flames 
during a thunderstorm. The plane carried no passengers, but all six 
crew members were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing continues to insist that the 737 is a safe airplane.  
There are 3,100 in use worldwide and the airplane has made nearly 
80 million departures since being introduced. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the safest airplanes flying,'' Allen Berry, a  
Boeing engineer, told the St. Petersburg Times, which reported 
recently about the NTSB report. ``We feel strongly we have made 
improvements to make it even safer.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
