<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Seeks Tougher Self </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There was a moment in her U.S. Open victory over  
Silvia Farina when Monica Seles was on cruise control. Then she 
suddenly shifted into park. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading 6-2, 5-1 in Thursday's second-round match, Seles seemed  
to stop. Against Farina, that could be dangerous because the last 
time they met, in the Fed Cup in July, the Italian won 6-4, 4-6, 
6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	``Definitely, I didn't want to have a repeat,'' she said. ``My  
mind left me at 5-1. I thought, `This is going to be it, I'm 
serving with the wind. This is going to be too easy.''' 
</P>
<P>
	And suddenly, it wasn't so easy.  
</P>
<P>
	Quickly, Farina won two games before Seles pulled herself back  
and finished off the match, 6-2, 6-3. Afterward, she was a bit 
upset with the slip in concentration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just happy that I toughened it out there in that 5-3  
game,'' Seles said. ``It was very good this happened in an early 
round while I can still pull out a match. As the rounds go along, 
these things can't happen. So it's good it happened today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeded No. 4, Seles sees herself as something of an outsider at  
the Open, where the spotlight is on No. 1 Martina Hingis, defending 
champion Lindsay Davenport and the Williams sisters, Venus and 
Serena. 
</P>
<P>
	Seles has nine Grand Slam championships in her resume, but she  
has won just one of them since the stabbing incident in 1993 that 
took her off the tour for 27 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think definitely there's a lot of focus on Martina, Lindsay,  
Venus and Serena,'' she said. ``They totally deserve it. They 
played better tennis this summer than I have. 
</P>
<P>
	``So definitely, they're more favorites than I am. It doesn't  
matter. I don't care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Seles had her way, she'd never play any matches. Instead,  
she'd be out there hitting every day, practicing her tennis, but 
not looking to tear somebody's head off on the other side of the 
net. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly love to hit,'' she said. ``I just loved to practice  
and drill and that stuff. I really never enjoyed playing matches, 
even as a youngster. I just hate the whole thought that one 
(player) is better than the other. It drives me nuts. I just never 
liked it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That could be a dangerous mindset for a world class athlete, but  
Seles has managed to overcome those feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's survival out there,'' she said. ``If I don't, then the  
other person will. So you go into that automatic mode that you have 
no choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seles finally seems at ease with herself, at peace after the  
death of her father a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly miss him at the tennis court and at my practices,''  
she said. ``It's really hard. It's been hard to find direction, 
where my tennis game should be leading, where my dad would lead 
me'' 
</P>
<P>
	She is on her own, and there are times when she thinks it would  
help to develop a little bit of a mean streak, at least on the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been working on that,'' she said. ``But it's a hard one.  
I just want to be able to say `No' to more people and `I don't like 
this.' It's just part of growing up, I think, and not be such a 
pleaser.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
