<DOCNO> APW19990902.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds vs. Braves: No Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Call it a hex. Call it a tradition. No matter  
how hard they try -- and maybe they're trying too hard -- the 
Cincinnati Reds just can't beat the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last three years, they've played the Braves 29 times and  
can count their victories on one hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time a club beats you up like they have, it seems like  
they have your number,'' Reds third baseman Aaron Boone said. 
</P>
<P>
	They have all the numbers: an 8-1 record against the Reds this  
season, including a pair of three-game sweeps in Atlanta; a 29-5 
mark over the last three years; eight consecutive series wins since 
September 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta's 8-7 victory Wednesday night completed their season  
series and left the Reds with an all-too-familiar feeling. The 
contending Reds are one of the major leagues' biggest surprises, 
but there are no surprises when they face the NL's top team. 
</P>
<P>
	They just don't measure up.  
</P>
<P>
	``From where we were at the beginning of the year to the club  
that we've become, we felt like we were ready to climb into that 
elite group of teams,'' Boone said. ``But to do that, you've got to 
be competitive against those teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's something of a mystery why they're not. The Reds have gone  
8-1 against NL West leader Arizona, 8-3 against NL Central leader 
Houston and 5-4 against the New York Mets, the other team currently 
in contention for a wild-card berth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves are an entirely different story. The Reds' only  
victory over them came Monday, when the Braves didn't get into town 
until 3:30 a.m. and got drubbed 11-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta went on to score 16 runs in the next two games.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to see them get out of town,'' manager Jack McKeon  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reliever Mike Remlinger, who went to the Braves along with  
second baseman Bret Boone in the Denny Neagle trade last November, 
thinks the one-sided rivalry weighs on the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got that in the back of your head, even if you don't  
want it there,'' Remlinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe the Reds just try too hard.  
</P>
<P>
	``From being on the other side of it, I know when I pitched  
against the Braves I always tried to be on top of my game,'' 
Remlinger said. ``I think everybody feels that way. Whether they 
try to do more than they should or they're tight, I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds are inclined to think it's just one of those mysteries  
of baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think of the other clubs that have given us a tough time --  
San Diego last year,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``They did it to 
us. We've done it two years in a row to Arizona.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Padres won 11 of 12 from the Reds. Over the past  
two seasons, the Reds have won 13 of 18 from the Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds-Braves matter goes back much farther and runs much  
deeper. It's been so lopsided that the Reds felt some relief after 
turning a 7-1 deficit into a one-run loss Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes it competitive and it makes it fun,'' shortstop Barry  
Larkin said. ``Of course you want to win. It's a good situation 
that we came back. It's a confidence builder. It's all about 
respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves respect the Reds even as they beat them.  
</P>
<P>
	``We know they're for real,'' Bret Boone said. ``You don't play  
as good as they have to this point and be a fluke. We know we have 
to play our best against them. It just seems like when we've played 
them, we've played them very well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 19:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mine Workers Union Fund Facing Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- A fund that pays health insurance to  
70,000 retired coal miners and their families is $13 million in 
debt and could start cutting benefits early next year, the 
president of the United Mine Workers said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Without some new source of funds, the multi-employer trust fund  
will face a shortage of $250 million within five years, said Cecil 
Roberts, the union's leader. 
</P>
<P>
	The trust fund, known as the UMW Combined Benefit Fund, ``can  
operate on a cash basis through the end of this year and into early 
next year,'' Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless a solution is found soon, there will be increasing  
pressure by some trustees to cut benefits as the CBF deficit 
continues to grow,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Combined Benefit Fund was established seven years ago by  
federal legislation. It is financed by premiums paid by some 300 
employers, current and former coal operators, and it pays out an 
estimated $1 million a day. 
</P>
<P>
	But the companies required to pay into the fund have brought  
more than 60 lawsuits, challenging everything from the law's 
constitutionality to the amount they were ordered to pay, which was 
established by the Social Security Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund has won most of the legal disputes, according to  
Michael Holland, co-chairman of the CBF's board of trustees. But at 
least three rulings have reduced assets by as much as $113 million, 
and if they remain in place they could cost as much as $400 million 
over the life of the fund, Holland said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund's beneficiaries are an expensive group: 65 percent of  
them are women, generally miners' widows, and their average age is 
about 78. As a result, the cost of their health care is going up 
faster than that of the nation as a whole, Holland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts said the union is again working with Congress to develop  
a solution. 
</P>
<P>
	The union will hold meetings in Alabama, Indiana, West Virginia,  
Pennsylvania and Utah later this month to explain the situation to 
beneficiaries, and to enlist them in a campaign to persuade 
Congress to enact legislation to remedy the problem. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
