<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biggest Insurer Covers New Pap Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc., the nation's largest health insurer,  
reversed itself Thursday and agreed to cover a new type of Pap 
smear test, which federal officials in 1996 said was more effective 
in detecting early signs of cervical cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, a top Aetna official said the ThinPrep PapTest would  
add $1 billion to health care costs nationwide without any proof 
that it is better than the conventional Pap smear test at saving 
lives. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Aetna said new, as yet unpublished studies show  
ThinPrep increases the detection of abnormal or precancerous cells. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that it is best to have the treating physician make  
the decision'' about which type of Pap test to use, said Dr. Arnold 
Cohen, an obstetrician-gynecologist in charge of Aetna's women's 
health programs. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ThinPrep, Aetna said it will cover a similar  
test, PREP, made by AutoCyte, and an automated Pap test in which a 
computer, rather than a laboratory technician, scans Pap smear 
slides. 
</P>
<P>
	The coverage begins immediately.  
</P>
<P>
	The company's Aetna U.S. Healthcare unit, based in Blue Bell,  
Pa., provides health insurance to 21 million Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance coverage is crucial because ThinPrep typically costs  
$25 to $30 per test compared to $7 to $10 for the conventional Pap 
test. Aetna said its costs would increase as a result of the new 
coverage, but said it was too early to estimate the amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna joins most of the major health insurers to cover ThinPrep,  
which was approved in 1996 but has struggled until recently to 
build demand. The only major insurer not to cover the test is 
Kaiser Permanente, the nation's second-largest health maintenance 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	A Kaiser official said last month that the company is looking  
into covering the newer test. 
</P>
<P>
	About 13 percent of the 50 million Pap smears performed in the  
United States are now done with ThinPrep, which is made by Cytyc 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	ThinPrep makes it easier for lab technicians to interpret Pap  
smears, and as a result find more abnormal or precancerous cells. 
</P>
<P>
	ThinPrep treats the cells with a liquid to remove blood and  
mucus that can hide cancerous changes. In November 1996, the 
federal government agreed that the Thin Prep system is more than 65 
percent more effective in diagnosing precancerous cells, which can 
lead to cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Named for Dr. George Papanicolaou, the pathologist who developed  
it in 1948, the Pap smear involves a doctor scraping cells from the 
cervix, at the neck of the uterus. 
</P>
<P>
	The cells are smeared onto a glass slide and sent to a lab,  
where a technician reads the slide under a microscope. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pap smear is far from infallible. It misses problems  
about 20 percent of the time, according to the National Institutes 
of Health, usually because of poor cervical samples or difficulty 
reading the slides at the lab. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a big deal,'' said Tom Gunderson, an analyst at Piper  
Jaffray, said of Aetna's decision. ``It is not only nice for Aetna 
and its customers, but is a tremendous boon for Cytyc's 
psychology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Cytyc rose $2, or nearly 6 percent, to close at  
$36.56 1/4 Thursday on the Nasdaq Stock Market. ``This is just perfect 
for us,'' said Jeff Kelly, Cytyc's chief financial officer. ``It 
will lead many more women to get the test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many doctors and health insurers initially were hesitant to  
replace the conventional diagnostic test that led to a big drop in 
cervical cancer deaths with a pricier version. Critics claimed that 
the new test was no better than the conventional one at identifying 
cancer, and argued ThinPrep would result in too many false 
warnings, thus unnecessarily alarming patients. 
</P>
<P>
	ThinPrep's increasing market share comes as Cytyc, based in  
Boxborough, Mass., has convinced more big health insurers -- 
including several Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans -- that the new 
test is worth the extra expense. Other major insurers that cover 
ThinPrep include United HealthCare, Cigna and Foundation Health. 
Another major insurer, Humana, provides partial coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance coverage has led more doctors to order the test, and  
more women to request it. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna's Cohen said the new studies show ThinPrep helps detect  
more serious abnormal cells, which have a strong likelihood of 
becoming cancerous. He said older studies involved too few women, 
and showed the test only detected the type of abnormal cells that 
most likely would not become cancerous. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said the most important way to prevent cervical cancer is  
to get a regular Pap test, not which type of test to use. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit Strike Not Affecting Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Striking teachers stayed out of classrooms for a  
fourth day Thursday as school officials refused to back down on a 
plan to grant merit bonuses to every employee of an improved 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	The bonus plan is one sticking point with teachers, who say the  
plan fails to reward excellent teachers who happen to work in 
schools that perform poorly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have issues that haven't been resolved,'' said Jim  
Amar, a state mediator appointed Aug. 24 to sit in on the 
negotiations between the board and the Detroit Federation of 
Teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	There was at least one concession.  
</P>
<P>
	David Adamany, the chief executive of the 172,000-student  
district, agreed Wednesday to withdraw a proposal to extend the 
school day by 2 hours, to 8 1/2 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, teachers would not oppose having aides and other  
non-teaching personnel work longer days so the district could offer 
after-school programs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Adamany remained committed to his proposal to reward schools  
meeting test score and attendance targets by granting ``merit 
bonuses'' to every employee in that school -- including custodians 
and secretaries. 
</P>
<P>
	As bargaining resumed Thursday afternoon, the union in turn was  
digging in against the bonus plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Danic, an English teacher at Osborn High School, said the  
plan would reward teachers at what he called ``showcase schools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The inequity of the worst teacher in a good school receiving a  
bonus, but not a good teacher in a bad school, is totally unfair,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The district and the union representing 9,200 teachers also were  
sparring over issues including salary, class size and sick days. 
</P>
<P>
	The board and union President John Elliott early Monday morning  
agreed to extend the teachers' contract 10 days beyond its Monday 
expiration date. But several thousand union members bolted from 
Elliott that day during a raucous meeting at which they rejected 
the extension and voted to strike instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike has put at least a temporary halt to reform efforts  
led by Adamany since he took the job in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. John Engler, who signed legislation shifting control of the  
district from the elected board to an appointed board that hired 
Adamany, said the change was necessary to shore up lagging test 
scores, chronically low attendance and graduation rates in the 
nation's 10th-largest city. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Fryman Back With Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Travis Fryman feels like it's February and he's  
down in Florida at spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Fryman, sidelined since July with a torn ligament in his right  
knee, was recalled from a rehabilitation assignment on Thursday by 
the Cleveland Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like starting over to some extent,'' said Fryman, who  
played third base in the ninth inning of Thursday night's 6-5 
victory over the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Fryman tore the posterior collateral ligament in his knee after  
colliding with Kansas City first baseman Jeremy Giambi in a July 3 
game. He went on the DL the next day for just the second time in 
his career. Earlier this year, he was sidelined with back spasms 
and made his first trip to the DL in nine seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Fryman, now wearing a large brace on his knee, began a 20-day  
rehab stint for Double-A Akron and Triple-A Buffalo on Aug. 24. He 
batted a combined .217 (5-for-23) with two homers and six RBIs in 
seven games. He played some third base but used primarily as a 
designated hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	With the postseason nearing, Fryman wanted to get in at least 30  
games with the Indians so he could get himself ready for October. 
He said he hasn't had to slide yet and is still not running as well 
as he would like. 
</P>
<P>
	Fryman, who was not in the Indians' starting lineup Thursday  
night but could see some action, said his knee is pain free but 
that he hasn't been able to test it like he wants. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can work in the weight room, but the athleticism it takes  
to play you can't really duplicate,'' he said. ``You can take 
fungoes all day long, but reacting to balls off the bat and things 
like that you can only replicate in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fryman said the brace, which goes from his lower thigh to his  
calf, doesn't restrict what he can do defensively. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be limited in some extent,'' he said. ``Not the  
brace as much as the injury. It's not an injury you bounce right 
back from a few weeks later and you're 100 percent. It takes a 
period of time to get where you were, but at this time it's doing 
pretty well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Fryman, the Indians transferred catcher Sandy  
Alomar from the 15- to 60-day disabled list. Alomar, sidelined 
since May 17 following knee surgery, will begin a 20-day rehab 
stint Friday with Akron. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, too, is hoping to be ready for the postseason.  
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove, who could use Fryman at DH to get him some at-bats,  
has had to juggle his lineup and starting rotation all season 
because of injuries. He's happy that Fryman, one of the Indians 
leaders, is available to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to have one of your guys back, especially one you  
can depend on,'' he said. ``Hopefully, we can get him sharp enough 
where he can contribute during the postseason.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
