<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Near End of Their Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A summer vacation that put President  
Clinton's lame-duck status on uncomfortable display neared a close 
Thursday with a pair of fund-raisers for the family's newly minted 
politician -- the president's wife. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons also agreed to purchase a $1.7 million house in a  
New York City suburb, giving Hillary Rodham Clinton the New York 
residence she needs if she runs for the U.S. Senate next year. 
</P>
<P>
	While the president golfed, lounged and gave a handful of  
political speeches, much of the 16-day trip to Massachusetts and 
New York focused on Mrs. Clinton's presumed candidacy. She expected 
to raise about $800,000 for her exploratory campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The president expects to move into the five-bedroom, three-story  
home in Chappaqua, Westchester County, when his term ends in 
January 2001. To qualify as a candidate, Mrs. Clinton must 
establish residency by Election Day in November 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he has 17 months left in his term, Clinton is clearly  
thinking about his future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can work for cheap,'' he told a New Yorker this week. ``I've  
got a good pension.'' At another point he noted, ``I'm looking for 
a new role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons spent more than half their vacation in New York,  
forsaking a second week on the Massachusetts resort island of 
Martha's Vineyard where they have been summer regulars during 
Clinton's more than six years in office. They are to head to Camp 
David, the presidential retreat in Maryland, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton seemed both delighted and unsettled by the enthusiastic  
reception Mrs. Clinton drew during their first joint trip to New 
York state since she formed the exploratory committee. It marked 
the first time that Clinton campaigned on her behalf and helped 
raise money for the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are asking me how I'm reacting to this whole deal,'' he  
said Thursday night at a fund-raiser for the first lady. ``I love 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he plainly laments that his own time is waning and that he  
cannot run for president again. ``I hate it, actually,'' he told 
supporters last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In upstate New York this week, the president watched as crowds  
chanted and cheered for Mrs. Clinton, and the route of his 
motorcade near the Syracuse-area golf course where he played 
Thursday was lined with signs that read: ``Go Hillary!'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in a week, Clinton played the round with a  
group of eight instead of the traditional foursome. His party of 
upstate New York Democrats and business leaders included the 
majority leader of the New York Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton drove his own cart -- the only driving his cosseted life  
of limousines and helicopters allows him -- and went wide at the 
first turn off a paved cart path. 
</P>
<P>
	A gallery of club members at the Lafayette Golf and Country Club  
chuckled when Clinton headed the wrong way a few minutes later and 
had to pull a U-turn around a dead pine tree. Many of the carts in 
an unofficial motorcade behind him followed suit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
