<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Machinists Approve Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Members of Boeing's biggest union were on the job  
Thursday after signing off on their new three-year contract with a 
resounding 86 percent yes vote, the biggest margin of approval in 
their history with the aerospace giant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to send a message to corporate America that labor is  
back,'' said an exultant Bill Johnson, president of the 
International Aerospace Machinists' Seattle-based District Lodge 
751. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's an inspiration. We've seen major setbacks in the  
labor movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contract was approved 26,842-4,328 late Wednesday, with a 71  
percent turnout from the 44,000 Machinists members in Washington, 
Oregon and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact got a boost from Boeing Chairman and CEO Phil Condit,  
who stepped in personally to end a prickly bargaining stalemate 
last weekend and lobbied hard this week -- in newspaper, radio and 
TV ads -- to get it accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Machinists interviewed outside polling places called the pact  
``a miracle'' and a morale-booster. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably the best Boeing's ever offered. They know a  
strike would hurt their future efforts to sell planes,'' said 
Ulysses Phillips, a punch-press operator in Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the climate in the business world right now, the  
competition with Airbus (Industrie), the workers at Boeing got some 
recognition for their hard efforts,'' said Jeffrey Tazioli, who 
assembles wings at the suburban Auburn plant. ``Our efforts have 
been rewarded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Up until last Friday, negotiations were deadlocked and workers  
were preparing for a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were tired. Their morale was bad,'' said Kevin Mims,  
quality insurance inspector in Renton. When they saw Boeing's final 
contract offer Saturday, he said, ``Everyone was like, 'Yee-haw!''' 
</P>
<P>
	The old contract expired at 12:01 a.m. Thursday. The Machinists  
have struck over two of the last three contracts, most recently for 
69 days in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract offered two annual wage increases of 4 percent and  
a third-year 3 percent raise, as well as a 10 percent signing bonus 
worth $4,400 to the average machinist. It also holds steady worker 
contributions to health insurance premiums. 
</P>
<P>
	The only opposition to the agreement focused on retirement  
benefits and job security. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing offered a 25 percent increase in pensions, to $50 a month  
per year of service -- well below the 300 percent increase sought by 
the union. The contract offer also guaranteed ``no layoffs as the 
direct result of subcontracting or offloading.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
