<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rates Rise on 30-Year Mortgages / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages edged up to 7.83 percent this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The average was up from 7.80 percent last week, according to a  
weekly survey released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgages rates have been on an upward climb. So far this year,  
average rates on a 30-year mortgage have hit a low of 6.74 percent 
set at the end of January and the new high of 8.15 percent set two 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 7.45 percent this week, also up from the average of 7.43 
percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 6.18 percent this week, down from 6.22 
percent the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association said that mortgage  
loan applications for the week ending Aug. 27 increase 4.5 percent 
from the previous week but were down 25.7 percent compared to the 
same week last year. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
