<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush: Don't Fund Bad Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate George W.  
Bush said Thursday that federal funds should be confiscated from 
the worst-performing schools and made available to parents for 
private education, tutoring or ``whatever offers hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``More and more, we are divided into two nations, separate and  
unequal,'' the Texas governor said in prepared remarks to a 
Hispanic business group. ``One that reads and one that can't. One 
that dreams and one that doesn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his most detailed education policy speech to date, Bush said  
he would withhold federal money earmarked for poor schoolchildren 
from schools that fail year after year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Bush's plan, every school getting Title I money would be  
required to test its impoverished students on basic academics each 
year. A warning would be issued to schools that fail to make 
progress toward state standards. After three years of no progress, 
the Title I money would be matched with other federal education 
money and given to the state, which would set up an education 
account -- about $1,500 a year -- for each affected student. 
</P>
<P>
	The parents could choose how to spend the money. They could keep  
the money and their child in the original school or opt for an 
alternative, including private school and tutoring -- ``for whatever 
offers hope,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government currently spends $7.7 billion on Title I to help  
educate poor children. 
</P>
<P>
	A Bush aide said the plan would require states to create  
mechanisms for ensuring parents spent the money on education. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my administration, federal money will no longer flow to  
failure,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP presidential front-runner said he would halt federal  
spending on ``sloppy and trendy'' programs. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised to require every federal program affecting teacher  
training, curriculum research and school safety to prove results. 
Those that didn't would be stripped of their funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also proposed shifting the $4.4 billion Head Start program  
from the Department of Health and Human Services to the Education 
Department, a step he said would return the program's focus to 
preparing disadvantaged preschoolers for the classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Invoking the buzzwords often heard in school-reform efforts in  
California, Texas and many other states, Bush said schools must 
establish a few clear goals that help measure students' basic 
skills. Testing helps ensure they achieve them, he said. And 
someone must take responsibility when they fail, he said, singling 
out principals. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he said, local control of schools is essential  
to meeting the goals. 
</P>
<P>
	His proposal allowing federal money to flow to private  
institutions drew immediate fire from opponents, who say such 
arrangements siphon taxpayer money away from public schools that 
need it. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Secretary Richard Riley said he saw similarities  
between Bush's proposal and those of his brother Jeb, who as 
Florida's governor pushed through the nation's first statewide 
voucher plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how you dress it up, how long you delay it, or what  
you call it, a voucher is a voucher,'' Riley said. ``Gov. George W. 
Bush would have us start down the road of accountability, then take 
a dangerous detour into vouchers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We would be against a plan like this,'' said Reginald Felton,  
director of federal relations for the National School Boards 
Association. ``The objective is to raise the academic achievement 
of all students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But at a Title I elementary school Bush visited Thursday, the  
idea of vouchers won cautious support from two teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is a good idea, because sometimes private schools  
have a lot more to offer -- more personal, smaller classes,'' said 
teacher Joann Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	She and fellow teacher Janet Leinin didn't believe that such  
programs would rob Bennett-Kew Elementary School of students and 
the public money that follows them, because, they said, it is 
academically one of the strongest in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush delivered his remarks in a state where voters have soundly  
rejected proposals to allow public money for private schools, an 
arrangement often referred to as school vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, Bush has backed a proposed pilot program for  
taxpayer-funded vouchers for private school tuition. State 
lawmakers have declined to pass the proposal ever since Bush became 
governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month a federal judge halted a voucher program in Ohio,  
saying it appeared to have the ``primary effect of advancing 
religion'' because it allowed public money to be used for religious 
and other private schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge later said the program can remain in place for  
students who participated in the program last year, but said that 
would last only one semester or until a final judgment is reached 
in a lawsuit claiming the program violates the constitutional 
separation of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush offered a forceful defense of such programs.  
</P>
<P>
	``All monopolies are slow to reform when consumers have no power  
to express their frustration,'' he said. ``In education, parents 
who have options have influence.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.N. Demands Security in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- U.N. officials in East Timor pleaded with  
Indonesian security forces today to better protect them, one day 
after fighting between pro- and anti-independence supporters killed 
at least three people near the world body's compound. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, Indonesia said it might allow a U.N. peacekeeping  
force into East Timor, apparently backing away from its earlier 
stance that it alone would provide security to the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``The possibility is not closed for the government to allow the  
United Nations to deploy a U.N. peacekeeping force in East Timor, 
but this matter has not been discussed by the government,'' State 
Secretary Muladi told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the situation in East Timor worsens, I think the  
possibility for that would be worth considering,'' said Muladi, 
President B.J. Habibie's top aide. Muladi, like many Indonesians, 
uses one name. 
</P>
<P>
	In Canberra, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said  
planning already was under way ``for a United Nations security 
presence to be brought in place in East Timor,'' but only with 
Indonesia's consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of East Timorese were leaving the city of Dili today  
to avoid being targeted by more violence, residents said. Rumors 
were sweeping through Dili that there would soon be a wave of 
assaults by pro-Indonesian militiamen against people who voted for 
independence. The militiamen are believed to be backed by the 
Indonesian military. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no possibility of protecting either ourselves -- our  
international staff, our local staff -- or anybody else, other than 
the pressure we can put upon the Indonesian authorities to fulfill 
their responsibilities,'' said Ian Martin, head of the U.N. 
mission. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S., Australian, Portuguese and U.N. officials in New York also  
strongly criticized Indonesia's slow response to the violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with homemade guns, rifles and machetes, hundreds of  
militiamen clashed Wednesday with rock-throwing independence 
supporters outside U.N. headquarters in the provincial capital. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three people were killed near the U.N. buildings,  
including one who was hacked to death by militiamen armed with 
machetes, U.N. officials and witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian soldiers and police stood by without intervening as  
hundreds of people and dozens of journalists fled the scene. It 
took more than an hour for riot police to arrive and disperse the 
militants. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence came as ballots from Monday's historic referendum  
were being counted in Dili, East Timor's capital. The 
U.N.-sponsored vote asked the mostly Roman Catholic East Timorese 
whether they wanted to become independent or remain part of mostly 
Muslim Indonesia as an autonomous region. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, has been a province of  
Indonesia since being invaded in 1975. After decades of human 
rights abuses and international condemnation, Indonesia reversed 
policy in January and announced East Timor would be given the right 
of self-determination. 
</P>
<P>
	The outcome of the referendum won't be known until next week,  
but the high turnout left many people assuming the pro-independence 
supporters could win by a landslide. 
</P>
<P>
	Muladi also said today that more than 200,000 East Timorese,  
nearly one-quarter of the population, may flee from the province if 
voters there have chosen independence. Muladi did not provide the 
basis for his estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the refugees could be Indonesian loyalists fearing  
reprisals from independence supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Clashes between anti-independence militiamen and supporters of  
independence have raised fears that East Timor could slide back 
into lawlessness. 
</P>
<P>
	Many stores in Dili remained closed today, and there were few  
cars and pedestrians on the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of East Timorese were leaving the city in fear, going  
back to their home villages or to the safety of mountains outside 
the capital, residents in Dili said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin urged the Indonesian government to take responsibility  
for protecting U.N. officials and residents in the tense capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin said Wednesday's attack outside the U.N. compound was not  
directed at its buildings or staff members, but at residents who 
want to see the territory become independent from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is clear that we would not be in a position to have  
prevented the worst violence if the mob had indeed attempted to 
attack the compound itself,'' Martin told a news conference in 
Dili. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin said Indonesia's military commander, Gen. Wiranto, had  
ordered additional security for U.N. staff and premises in East 
Timor. That includes the Dili Museum building, where ballots from 
the referendum are being counted. It has not been attacked. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's government sent 360 additional police to Dili today.  
Martin also said security forces had set up a road block to the 
west of Dili to prevent anti-independence militiamen from coming 
into the town from areas that they control. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a special C-130 flight, the military evacuated journalists  
who had been threatened or attacked. 
</P>
<P>
	In another development, an independent election commission began  
hearing complaints by the anti-independence movement that local 
U.N. officials had cheated during the referendum by encouraging, 
and even forcing, illiterate villages to vote for independence. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
