<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mississippi School Furor Is Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROBINSONVILLE, Miss. (AP) -- A fracas over where to build the new  
Robinsonville Elementary School has grown so complex, so divisive, 
that some in this low-lying Delta community are calling it simply 
``The Big Mess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And no wonder. The U.S. Justice Department, the Congressional  
Black Caucus, the state attorney general, a powerful Mississippi 
developer, a New York City law firm and sundry civil rights groups 
are all weighing in on what, on the surface, looks like a local 
flap. 
</P>
<P>
	Below the surface, issues of race and power are merging with  
Tunica County's grim legacy of separate and unequal education to 
cast national attention on the proposed new school, a $5 million 
showcase hugging a planned upscale development. 
</P>
<P>
	The struggle also underscores a challenge faced far and wide --  
making sure that when new wealth comes to poor areas, the schools 
and other attendant social services are not limited to mere 
enclaves. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is pitiful this mess has gotten to this point,'' said a  
downcast Floy Siggers, a mother of 11 and PTA president. ``But rich 
people are always trying to pull something over on the poor 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For generations, expansive cotton fields provided the lifeblood  
for this predominately black county of about 8,600 residents near 
the Mississippi River in the state's northwest corner. But now, 
casinos are king. 
</P>
<P>
	Built along the river, 13 new gambling parlors are bringing  
visitors and wealth to Tunica County, until recently the second 
poorest in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight centers on a plan, championed by local and state  
education officials, to build a tony new public elementary school 
on land sold to the school district by a developer who is building 
an expensive housing project next to it. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hundred homes are planned. The single family dwellings  
would sell for more than $100,000 and bring a contemporary look to 
a town where double-wide trailer homes and ramshackle dwellings 
dominate. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics, including the local NAACP and Rep. Bennie Thompson,  
D-Miss., say the homes will be outside the price range of almost 
all blacks and will be bought mainly by white casino executives 
moving to the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The result, they say, will be a new, virtually all-white public  
school in an affluent pocket -- and an affront to longtime residents 
left with substandard schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want a new school. But locate it where our black children  
can benefit too,'' said Melvin Young of Concerned Citizens for a 
Better Tunica County. 
</P>
<P>
	The state officials involved, who are mostly white, and the  
civic officials pushing the project, who are mostly black, say the 
school will relieve overcrowding generally, just one way they see 
the gambling industry's tide lifting all boats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because it's Mississippi, everyone is looking for injustice to  
black people,'' said James Dunn, a black member of the county board 
of supervisors. ``But Tunica County is growing and changing. 
Everyone here knows Robinsonville isn't going to become all-white 
any time soon, if ever. We need a new school for our children 
today. '' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said he might believe officials were taking black  
people's best interests at heart if not for the history of 
education in Tunica County. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1954 Brown vs. Board of Education decision ruling school  
segregation unconstitutional meant little in Tunica County early 
on. White parents first sidestepped the law by holding whites-only 
classes in churches. Later, they created a system of private 
academies. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, a federal judge signed a desegregation order that is in  
effect today. Its effectiveness in bringing black and white 
children together was negligible. 
</P>
<P>
	Just 39 white children, but 2,000 black children, attend the  
county's four public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the county's private school, the Tunica Institute for  
Learning, is almost all-white. 
</P>
<P>
	``White parents there have never sent their kids to the public  
school system,'' said Thompson, who got 25 black members of 
Congress to sign a letter to Attorney General Janet Reno denouncing 
the current site. ``And now they expect us to believe they've had a 
change of heart. Well, I don't believe it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department also had doubts.  
</P>
<P>
	Reasoning that building the school in the subdivision would  
violate the spirit of the 1970 integration order for Tunica County, 
the department ruled last September against the school's planned 
location. The department has jurisdiction over major education 
decisions in the county under the decree. 
</P>
<P>
	Local school officials called in Mississippi Attorney General  
Michael Moore, who promptly set up meetings with Justice officials 
extolling the virtues of the current site. In a June letter to 
Reno, Moore said he was advising the district to build even though 
it hadn't received federal approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a strategic move that worked because we got a meeting  
(with the Justice Department),'' Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the department is reconsidering its position and a final  
decision is expected soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore disputes predictions that the school will become an  
all-white island in a sea of poorer black pupils. 
</P>
<P>
	Only nine of the homes have been built so far, and Moore says if  
the school were to open tomorrow more than 250 black students 
living nearby would attend. The school is planned to hold about 500 
pupils. 
</P>
<P>
	PTA president Siggers says one solution would be to move the  
school just a few miles south -- essentially meeting the existing 
black school population half way. 
</P>
<P>
	Local officials don't want to pay for land or services in a  
different location. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi activists opposed to the school are being advised by  
The Advancement Project, a public policy advocacy group with 
offices in Washington and Los Angeles. That group brought in a New 
York law firm that is donating its services. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides in the Big Mess agree on one thing: If no compromise  
is reached, a lawsuit from the loser is a certainty. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
