<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts on Bush-Education Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Facts and figures about the Title I program, which Republican  
presidential candidate George W. Bush proposed revising Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	WHAT: Title I, the main education program for poor and other  
educationally disadvantaged children is the cornerstone of the 1965 
Elementary and Secondary Education Act governing federal 
kindergarten-through-12th grade programs. 
</P>
<P>
	WHO BENEFITS: The program -- the largest K-12 program, with  
funding of $8.36 billion in fiscal 1999 -- serves 11 million of the 
nation's 58 million schoolchildren. All states receive the funding. 
Local districts tend to concentrate most of their Title I dollars 
in schools they deem have the most need. 
</P>
<P>
	PURPOSE: Title I is aimed at narrowing the gap in academic  
achievement between low-income students and their peers by 
providing supplemental funding to poor school districts. More than 
$120 billion has been funneled into Title I since its inception, 
making it one of the largest single federal investments in 
education. 
</P>
<P>
	DISTRIBUTION: The Education Department distributes Title I  
grants to states to give to individual schools based on a formula 
that takes into account how many of a school's students are living 
in poverty and what a given state spends on education per child. 
</P>
<P>
	HISTORY: Created in 1965 during the War on Poverty, Title I  
serves poor and disadvantaged children in nearly every school 
district in the country. In 1994, the law was changed to allow 
schools with 50 percent poor students to use the money on all 
students, rather than providing extra help to a limited number of 
students. Title I was formerly known as ``Chapter 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PRIVATE SCHOOLS: Private schools or a consortium of private  
schools are not eligible to receive Title I funds. Only a public 
school district can receive funds. 
</P>
<P>
	FUTURE: This fall, Congress will debate the reauthorization of  
ESEA and Title I. Republican leaders have criticized the program 
after reports that poor children lag behind other children in 
achievement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
