<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Albright Mediates Mideast Deadlock  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Egypt (AP) -- As prospects waned today for a West  
Bank agreement between Israel and the Palestinians, U.S. Secretary 
of State Madeleine Albright stepped in to mediate. Until now, 
Albright had held back, believing the most successful agreements 
are the product of direct negotiations between the parties with 
minimal intervention. Albright telephoned Israeli Prime Minister 
Ehud Barak and met with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. The 
sticking point was a dispute over how many Palestinian prisoners 
Israel would release as a goodwill gesture. Albright has given no 
indication of how she might come down on the prisoners or other 
issues. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Seeks Post-Quake Housing  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's government split today over how  
to house more than half a million quake survivors, who are crowded 
into borrowed rooms, damaged buildings, tent cities and even docked 
ferries as winter approaches. Public Works Minister Koray Aydin 
insisted that the government could make good on its pledge to have 
50,000 prefabricated houses ready within two months. But critics 
argue that temporary houses would waste money that should be saved 
for rebuilding. They say it would be better to move quake victims 
into existing shelters for the winter -- hotels, public housing and 
elsewhere -- and provide rent assistance. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Source Confirms Waco Assault  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Audio from an infrared videotape picked up an  
agent's voice seeking and receiving permission from a commander to 
fire incendiary tear-gas grenades at a concrete bunker adjacent to 
the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, an FBI source 
confirmed today. The source added that nothing on the videotape 
conflicts with the FBI's position that the tear gas did not ignite 
the blaze. Previously undisclosed evidence in the FBI's 1993 
assault on the compound has been impounded by federal marshals as 
Justice Department officials begin seeking an outsider to conduct a 
new investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Lashes N.C. Coast  
</P>
<P>
	WAVES, N.C. (AP) -- Tropical Storm Dennis meandered toward the  
North Carolina coast today, half the storm it was when it first 
spun into the Outer Banks. The fragile barrier islands were lashed 
by wind and 14-foot waves as crews struggled to deliver supplies to 
the stranded. President Clinton declared 50-mile-long Hatteras 
Island a disaster area and National Guard convoys ferried meals to 
the island. Yesterday, a land convoy delivering food discovered the 
island was effectively broken in two, as the storm had washed out 
highway N.C. 12. By today, winds had filled the gap with sand, 
enough of a fix to allow National Guard vehicles to cross. 

</P>
<P>
	Army Demotes Ret. Maj. Gen. Hale  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army took the highly unusual action today  
of demoting a retired general who admitted during his court-martial 
last spring that he had adulterous affairs with the wives of four 
subordinates. Army Secretary Louis Caldera reduced the rank of 
David Hale from a two-star major general to a one-star brigadier 
general. Hale's current retirement pay of $6,250 a month will be 
reduced by about $750 a month. That cut is retroactive to his 
retirement date of March 1, 1998. Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine, 
who urged Caldera to reduce Hale's rank, said she was pleased the 
Army secretary ``closed the Hale case on a high note of justice.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Sears Stock Plummets  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s stock plummeted 12  
percent today after the nation's second-largest retailer warned 
Wall Street that its third-quarter earnings would fall below 
expectations and announced a management shakeup. Sears, still mired 
in a slump despite a series of changes aimed at reviving its 
business, disclosed the news as it reported disappointing sales for 
the month of August. Shares in Sears were down 4 1/8 at 33 1/16 in 
late afternoon trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Lower; Dow Down 116.20  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today as concerns about  
inflation and interest rates were compounded by a dismal earnings 
outlook from Sears, Roebuck and Co. Just before the close, the Dow 
Jones industrial average was down 116.20 at 10,821.68 after having 
risen 108 points yesterday. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 
2,142-784. The Nasdaq was down 9.10 at 2,741.70. 

</P>
<P>
	Seles, Williams Sisters Advance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seventh-seeded Serena Williams joined her sister  
in the third round at the U.S. Open today after downing Jelena 
Kostanic of Croatia 6-4, 6-2. Yesterday, third-seeded Venus 
Williams scored a 6-4, 6-3 victory over Anne-Gaelle Sidot. Monica 
Seles also moved into the third round today, while Sandrine Testud 
became only the second seeded woman to be ousted from the 
tournament. No. 6 Amanda Coetzer of South Africa was eliminated on 
opening day by Irina Spirlea of Romania. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  



  	   	
</P>
