<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Bush: Don't Fund Bad Schools  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wading into the school voucher debate,  
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush said today in Los 
Angeles, ``Federal money will no longer flow to failure.'' He said 
his administration would require states to test disadvantaged 
students, strip federal funds from the worst-scoring schools and 
allow private schools to get the public money. Though aides said 
Bush intentionally avoided the politically charged term ``school 
vouchers'' in an address that laid out his first education 
proposals for the 2000 campaign, his plan would pump federal money 
into private schools -- a concept Democrats say would hurt the 
public school system. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.-China Trade Talks Planned  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and Chinese officials will hold trade  
talks next week for the first time since the accidental NATO 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. The move clears the way 
for a meeting between President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin. Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher said today 
the technical-level meeting will be a ``stocktaking'' of where the 
two countries stand on negotiations to bring China into the World 
Trade Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	2 U.N. Workers Killed in East Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia said Thursday it might allow a  
U.N. peacekeeping force into East Timor, apparently backing away 
from its earlier stance that it would provide security to the 
territory. The decision comes the same day two local U.N. staffers 
were killed in Maliana, 80 miles west of the territory's capital of 
Dili, which has been the scene of recent violence by 
anti-independence militias. The violence bring to four the number 
of local U.N. workers slain since Monday's independence referendum. 
Ballots are still being counted. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Mediates Mideast Deadlock  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Egypt (AP) -- As prospects waned Thursday for a West  
Bank agreement between Israel and the Palestinians, U.S. Secretary 
of State Madeleine Albright stepped in to mediate. Until now, 
Albright had held back, believing the most successful agreements 
are the product of direct negotiations between the parties with 
minimal intervention. Albright telephoned Israeli Prime Minister 
Ehud Barak and met with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. The 
sticking point was a dispute over how many Palestinian prisoners 
Israel would release as a goodwill gesture. Albright has given no 
indication of how she might come down on the prisoners or other 
issues. 

</P>
<P>
	Measles May Be Wiped Out in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Only 100 cases of measles were reported in the  
United States last year, the government said today. The number is 
the lowest on record and suggests the nation has all but stamped 
out the disease, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention 
said. All but 29 of those cases involved people who were infected 
in other countries. Measles still kills roughly 1 million people 
worldwide each year. About half of those deaths occur in central 
Africa. 

</P>
<P>
	Sears Stock Tumbles  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s stock plummeted 12  
percent today after the nation's second-largest retailer warned 
Wall Street that its third-quarter earnings would fall below 
expectations and announced a management shakeup. Sears, still mired 
in a slump despite a series of changes aimed at reviving its 
business, disclosed the news as it reported disappointing sales for 
the month of August. Shares in Sears closed down 3 11/16 at 33 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Drops 94.67  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed their end-of-summer slump today  
as concerns about inflation and interest rates were compounded by a 
dismal earnings outlook from Sears, Roebuck and Co. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed down 94.67 at 10,843.21, having worked 
its way back from a loss of 205 points earlier in the session. On 
the NYSE decliners led advancers 2,084-840. The Nasdaq was down 
16.56 at 2,734.24. 

</P>
<P>
	Williams Sisters, Seles Advance at Open  
