<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pork King Murphy To Sell Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- The nation's two largest hog growers  
announced a $290 million merger Thursday, a shakeout from last 
year's rock-bottom producer pork prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Smithfield Foods Inc., of Smithfield, Va., the world's largest  
hog producer and processor, agreed to buy No. 2 producer Murphy 
Family Farms of Rose Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase involves about 10 million shares of Smithfield  
Foods plus the assumption of about $170 million in Murphy Farms 
debt and other liabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy Family Farms, which specializes in raising hogs under  
contracts with independent farmers, struggled in the past year as 
pork prices hit the lowest prices in decades, said Kelly Zering, a 
North Carolina State University professor of agricultural resource 
economics. 
</P>
<P>
	Founder and chief executive officer Wendell H. Murphy signed a  
letter of intent Wednesday to sell his family-owned company to 
Smithfield, effective Jan. 1. Forbes magazine ranked it No. 355 on 
its 1998 list of privately held companies, with an estimated $650 
million in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Smithfield Foods, with $3.77 billion in sales for the year ended  
in April, will control 60 percent of the merged business operations 
from research and raising hogs to processing and distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Murphy Farms for some time has been analyzing the need for an  
alliance with a food processor to ensure stability for the Murphy 
family, the growers and the employees,'' said Lois Britt, a vice 
president and spokeswoman for Murphy Family Farms. 
</P>
<P>
	No layoffs are anticipated, and Wendell Murphy's future role in  
the merged companies has not yet been determined, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pork prices led the government to send hog producers at  
least $175 million in aid last year. Producer prices have since 
rebounded, with hog farmers getting 46 cents a pound again. 
</P>
<P>
	Smithfield Foods, which sends about 5.5 million hogs to market  
annually, raises hogs in North Carolina, South Carolina, Colorado, 
Virginia and Utah. A subsidiary, Carroll's Foods Inc., also 
produces hogs in Brazil and Mexico. Its products also are sold in 
Japan and Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined pork giant would control about 15 percent of the  
hogs on U.S. farms, giving Smithfield Foods less impact on pork 
prices than Tyson Foods Inc. in chicken or IBP Inc. in beef, said 
Grimes and analyst George Shipp. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
