<HEADLINE> Student Said ``Bullied'' Into Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREEBURG, Ill. (AP) -- A 14-year-old who was just four days into  
his freshman year in high school committed suicide after being 
tormented by bullies, his father said. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Rudy killed himself with a shotgun last week in the  
basement of his parents' home. His father, Earl Rudy, said his son 
had been tormented for ``four days straight'' by other students 
before the suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always a happy son, always friendly to people,'' Rudy  
said. ``He tried to be friendly to kids that didn't have any 
friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	High school administrators were interviewing Andrew's classmates  
Wednesday to determine who may have been involved in the 
harassment. Police said they've found evidence of verbal 
harassment, but no criminal acts. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we find that there was any criminal act committed, than we  
are certainly going to go for charges,'' said Chief of Police Steve 
Flater. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew's father said his son's tormentors had forced him into a  
locker and demanded he utter demeaning remarks. But school 
officials said no one witnessed such an incident. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials said they are focusing on a small number of  
students. 
</P>
<P>
	``I lost such a good son,'' said Rudy. ``I don't want anyone  
else to go through what we're going through.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
