<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wake Forest Track Coach Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- John Goodridge, men's track and cross  
country coach at Wake Forest for 15 years, resigned Thursday in 
protest of the firing of his wife, women's coach Francie Goodridge. 
</P>
<P>
	John Goodridge announced his resignation after his wife,  
Francie, a two-time Olympian, was fired over the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodridge alleged in a letter to reporters that his wife was  
fired in retaliation for complaining that Wake Forest wasn't doing 
enough to resolve Title IX issues, such as medical and safety 
concerns, scholarships and staffing. Title IX guarantees equality 
in men's and women's athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodridge said athletic director Ron Wellman also retaliated  
against the men's team by not giving it the full complement of NCAA 
allowable scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
	Wake Forest officials didn't immediately return calls seeking  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Francie has remained silent over her firing for fear of  
further harsher retaliation by Wellman against me and my program 
... and I simply can no longer dedicate my love for my sport and my 
efforts to this program,'' Goodridge said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodridge said Wellman fired Francie Goodridge over student  
complaints, but that action ``was a completely transparent, 
attempted cover-up for a planned agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodridge wasn't clear in his statement whether he and his wife  
would file a lawsuit, but said, ``That real agenda will be revealed 
in the legal process to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The women's cross country team ranked as high as sixth  
nationally under Francie Goodridge, who competed in the 1968 and 
1972 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The men's cross country team won four Atlantic Coast Conference  
championships, and John Goodridge was named ACC coach of the year 
six times. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
