<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 00:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher Strike Continues in Detroit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- With three children left idle as a teachers  
strike grinds into its third day, 27-year-old Angela Banks worries 
about what will happen next week. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, Ms. Banks has been tutoring her children on her own.  
But what if teachers don't return to work before she must go back 
to her own job at the county court? 
</P>
<P>
	``I had it together until they went on strike,'' she said  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Banks' dilemma was replicated across the city as affected  
parents looked into charter, private and parochial schools for ways 
to get their kids out of the house and into the classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Tinene Myers, whose 7-year-old daughter is handicapped and  
entering the second grade, said: ``I had planned on going back to 
school so this is putting a hold on my plans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teachers union, which represents about 9,200 classroom  
teachers, voted Monday to reject a 10-day contract extension 
recommended by a reform school board appointed last spring by Mayor 
Dennis Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	The teachers went on strike Tuesday on what should have been the  
first day of classes in the 172,000-student district. Talks ended 
late Wednesday without a breakthrough. Classes were not expected to 
be held today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say that anybody is wildly optimistic, but the number  
of issues is relatively small,'' David Adamany, the district's 
interim schools chief, said Wednesday. ``I think we're all hopeful 
we can close the gap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The main sticking points include the administration's merit pay  
proposal, a crackdown on teacher absenteeism, class size and the 
salary schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody wants change in the Detroit schools more than the  
teachers,'' Mark O'Keefe, a third-grade teacher, said. ``The time 
is right for reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Belle Isle Zoo -- offering free admission to all school  
kids during the strike -- security guard Alice Louis said she 
supports the teachers who have coped with overcrowding and 
shortages of supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The teachers have been there and done that. They deal with  
kids. They have to be the childrens' mother and father -- like 
second parents,'' said Ms. Louis, who has two kids in Detroit 
schools. ``The only thing they're asking for is a contract, and 
they deserve it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodericus Rayford, 33, also supports the educators. But while  
nine of his nieces, nephews, children and neighbors crowded his 
front porch, he also said he hoped they get back to work soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Otherwise, I'll get some signs for the kids, and we'll all go  
picket out there with them saying, `We want to go back!''' Rayford 
said with a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-year-old Quaashie Haten, who spent the day at a public  
playground and zoo with his brothers and mother, also wants to go 
back. ``I wanted to go to school,'' the second-grader confessed. 
</P>
<P>
	For parents looking for activities for their children, People's  
Community Services reopened three summer programs which had closed 
a week ago, associate director Lynne Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Adams-Butzel Recreation Center, supervisor Alton Darden  
said summer employees had to be called back to help open the center 
four hours earlier than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	And about 130 local students were signed up Wednesday to start  
school in neighboring Highland Park, which has opened its doors to 
students outside its boundaries. 
</P>
<P>
	While parents scampered to find something for their kids to do,  
there was growing evidence that patience with the strike -- the 
fourth by Detroit teachers since 1982 -- was wearing thin. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need their money like I need my money because they have  
kids to feed, too,'' said waitress Carolyn Norman, 38, whose 
daughter's senior year at Martin Luther King Jr. High School has 
been delayed. ``I'll give them until Labor Day. Then I'm going to 
have problems.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
