<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phiilippine Phone Changes Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The Philippines is considering  
setting up zones for companies specializing in electronic commerce 
which would let them use competitive international telephone rates, 
the government's top economic planner said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The only option currently available to many businesses is the  
international services of Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co., 
the country's dominant telephone company. Critics say these 
services are expensive and sometimes not up to par. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary for Socio-Economic Planning Felipe Medalla said the  
zones would be like the free ports that have already boosted 
foreign investment in areas like the former U.S. naval base at 
Subic Bay. Only this time, businesses will get access to cheaper 
international telephone rates rather than access to tax-free 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to create virtual free ports, and what's free is the  
freedom of choice,'' Medalla said. ``We are looking at it now, but 
what we have to do is make sure that companies aren't selling these 
services (to other telephone users) at standard rates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A growing number of electronic commerce and Internet-related  
companies are starting up in the Philippines, encouraged by the 
country's English-proficient workforce and the country's proximity 
to the biggest regional market, China. 
</P>
<P>
	Major international companies like America Online and Anderson  
Consulting have also been shifting their back office operations to 
the Philippines, and Medalla sees this as a potential driver of the 
Philippine economy in the years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Many businesses, though, have to rely on Internet servers based  
in other countries. The Philippines has been trying to modernize 
its telecommunications industry for some time, but has been 
handicapped by a constitutional curb on foreign ownership of 40 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	President Joseph Estrada is advocating constitutional revisions  
to allow greater foreign investment, but the process could take 
over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Former President Corazon Aquino and senior Catholic Church  
leaders oppose the charter change, fearing it could open the way to 
the kind of political abuses practiced by the late dictator 
Ferdinand Marcos. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
