<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures opened slightly lower today on  
the Chicago Board of Trade after two days of solid advances. Grain 
futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices later turned higher, buoyed by U.S. Department of  
Agriculture figures showing export sales higher than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the week ending Aug. 26 were 531,400 tons, the report  
said -- on the high side of what analysts had anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Any gains were expected to be limited by nervousness ahead of  
crop production forecasts expected later in the day and Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn prices also were buoyed by solid weekly export sales  
figures, turning higher after opening lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat opened slightly lower as investors responded to  
lower-than-expected weekly net export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, wheat for December delivery fell 2 3/4 cents to  
$2.64 cents a bushel; December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.20 1/2 cents a 
bushel; December oats fell 1/2 cent to $1.16 a bushel; November 
soybeans fell 2 cents to $4.86 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .15 cents to 66.22 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .02 cent to 79 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell .17 cent to 46.70 cents a pound; February pork 
bellies fell 2.30 cents to 57.30 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
