<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Mayor Loses Bid To Open Evidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- A week after federal investigators raided  
Mayor Milton Milan's office and home searching for ties to 
organized crime, a judge on Thursday refused the mayor's request to 
make public any evidence against him. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Magistrate Robert Kugler ruled against Milan and two  
newspapers -- The Philadelphia Inquirer and The Courier-Post of 
Cherry Hill -- who had sought release of documents related to the 
raid. 
</P>
<P>
	Milan, 36, is a former Marine and the first Latino mayor of  
Camden, the poorest city in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators last week executed search warrants at City Hall  
and Milan's home, carting away boxes of documents and materials. 
They have refused to say what they were seeking, or if Milan is a 
target. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have the FBI searching your bedroom at 7 in the  
morning, you're a target,'' said Edwin J. Jacobs, Milan's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents were seeking evidence of extortion, fraud, mail and tax  
fraud, conspiracy and interstate transportation in aid of 
racketeering, Jacobs said. 
</P>
<P>
	The warrants sought documents relating to jailed  
Philadelphia-South Jersey mob boss Ralph Natale, who was arrested 
in June on drug conspiracy charges. They also sought documents 
about 25 businesses and individuals, contractors, city employees 
and convicted drug dealers who pleaded guilty in a major cocaine 
ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs said there is no connection between Milan and Natale.  
Milan has declared his innocence, and has also rejected calls from 
critics for him to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no consideration whatsoever (of resigning). The  
people elected me to do a job and I am going to do that job ... 
till death do we part,'' Milan told the Inquirer and the 
Courier-Post. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Inquirer reported that Daniel Daidone, a former  
Natale associate and driver, was the alleged bridge between Milan 
and Natale. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the city had filed for bankruptcy, but averted the  
crisis when Milan agreed to give the state greater oversight of its 
finances. 
</P>
<P>
	Milan's attorney and the newspapers sought the affidavit  
outlining the probable cause for the search warrants and the 
inventory of what investigators seized. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfair to float all the rumors and not let the public  
know the facts,'' Jacobs said. ``We want the entire story known 
now, not six months from now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Renee M. Bumb told the judge that  
unsealing the documents would compromise the investigation. The 
government is also trying to protect the names of witnesses 
cooperating with their investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Kugler said releasing the documents would disclose the scope and  
the focus of the case. The documents will be made public, if and 
when an indictment is returned, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Milan sued the Inquirer after it ran an article weeks  
before the mayoral election identifying him as a suspect in a 
9-year-old murder case. He later dropped the suit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
