<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> August Retail Sales Mostly Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Retailers enjoyed another strong month in  
August, as Americans shrugged off rising interest rates and 
turbulence on Wall Street and kept buying at the nation's stores 
and malls. 
</P>
<P>
	But a few hints of weakness amid the sales reports issued  
Thursday raised some concerns over the outlook for consumer 
spending in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have a picture of a healthy consumer spending pattern  
out there, but the picture is getting more murky,'' said Steve 
Paspal, senior retail analyst at Sovereign Asset Management, a 
subsidiary of John Hancock Funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``In recent months, many retailers reported sales that topped  
expectations,'' he said. ``Now we are seeing more just meet 
expectations. That shows a slight slowdown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a strong year for retailers, which have benefited  
greatly this year from the resilient U.S. economy with low 
unemployment and tame inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Many merchants, however, have worried in recent months that  
borrowing and spending would slow after the Federal Reserve raised 
interest rates twice this summer in a preemptive strike against 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the Fed's two rate hikes have unsettled investors and  
weighed down the stock market -- including retail shares -- consumers 
so far have been unfazed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rate hikes were greeted with a big yawn by the consumer  
and their spending continues,'' said Kurt Barnard, a retail 
consultant and president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report in Upper 
Montclair, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	But Michael Niemira, a retail analyst at Bank of  
Tokyo-Mitsubishi, pointed out that August sales rose 6.6 percent 
overall -- which is still considered healthy -- but the gains were 
lower than the 7.3 percent seen during the January to July period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may just be seeing a slight, temporary pause, or it could  
be signaling something else,'' Niemira said. ``There seems to be a 
little weakness in the numbers and we will have to wait to see if 
that continues into September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for August, Wal-Mart was one of the top performers. The  
world's largest retailer was very aggressive with its prices on 
back-to-school merchandise -- which ended up hurting its 
competitors, namely Kmart. 
</P>
<P>
	Also reporting strong sales were the Limited and Gap, which  
lured shoppers with their trendy fashions, like capri pants and 
stretchy shirts with three-quarter sleeves. 
</P>
<P>
	Moderately priced department store chains such as J.C. Penney  
and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. did not fare as well, continuing to lose 
sales to the discounters and department store chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears and Penney both warned Thursday that its third-quarter  
earnings would be lower than Wall Street analysts' estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart's sales from stores open at least a year rose 8.7  
percent compared with August 1998, while total sales rose 26.9 
percent from year-ago levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales from stores open at least a year, known as same-store  
sales, are considered the most accurate measure of a retailer's 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Selected figures on August's sales at leading retail chains:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sears, same-store sales rose 0.1 percent, total sales down 3.3  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kmart, same-store sales up 3.4 percent, total sales up 5.6  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--J.C. Penney, same-store department store sales down 3.2  
percent; same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores up 8.8 percent; 
total sales up 5.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dayton Hudson, same-store sales up 4.9 percent, total sales up  
9.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federated, same-store sales up 2.9 percent, total sales up 14  
percent. Federated's total sales include revenues from the Internet 
and catalog seller Fingerhut, which was acquired in March. 
</P>
<P>
	--May Department Stores, same-store sales up 3.6 percent, total  
sales up 8.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Limited, same-store sales up 12 percent, total sales up 10  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gap, same-store sales up 8 percent, total sales up 29 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	--Ann Taylor same-store sales up 9 percent, total sales up 21  
percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
