<HEADLINE> Amtrak Attack Suspect Is Arraigned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A man pleaded innocent today to charges that he  
stabbed three people on an Amtrak train. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron Hall, 41, of Ontario, Calif., was arraigned in Common  
Pleas Court on one count of attempted murder and three of felonious 
assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, who was arraigned in a video link from the county jail,  
asked that an attorney be appointed for him. Judge Chris Boyko set 
bond at $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall is accused of stabbing two Amtrak conductors and a  
passenger on Aug. 26 about 15 miles west of Cleveland. In an 
earlier court appearance, he had claimed he acted in self-defense 
after he was threatened with a gun. The claim was similar to one he 
made the day before the train attack when he was removed from a bus 
for being unruly. 
  	   	
