<HEADLINE> College Football Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Jarious Jackson is supposed to be a  
running quarterback. Still, he passes well enough to make Michigan 
nervous. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime you have a mobile quarterback like that, it puts more  
pressure all over the defense,'' Michigan strong safety Tommy 
Hendricks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Jackson ran for 62 yards and tossed two touchdown  
passes as Notre Dame beat Michigan 36-20. As a result, the No. 7 
Wolverines will pay special attention to Jackson when the No. 16 
Irish come calling on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the opener for the Wolverines. Notre Dame has  
played once, a 48-13 victory last week over Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson played a big role in that win. He scored on a 38-yard  
run on a broken play and gained 85 yards while guiding the Irish to 
452 yards of total offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kansas made me run,'' Jackson said. ``But I liked that.''  
</P>
<P>
	On the down side, he completed only 9 of 17 passes for 85 yards,  
and threw three interceptions. If he makes that many mistakes 
against Michigan, it could be a long afternoon for the Irish. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing we told Jarious was to `let it rip,''' coach Bob  
Davie said. ``We've got 11 games left and we're not going to start 
concerning ourselves with interceptions right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's silly to get in that kind of game and get everybody tight  
about it. Hey, Jarious Jackson is the least of our problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan coach Lloyd Carr has refused to name his quarterback,  
although it probably will be Tom Brady. 
</P>
<P>
	Brady, a fifth-year senior, started all 13 games last season  
while leading the Wolverines to a 10-3 record, a share of the Big 
Ten championship and a Citrus Bowl victory over Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if the choice is Brady, there is a good chance  
sophomore Drew Henson will get plenty of time. Henson, who played 
in the New York Yankees' farm system during the summer, is 
considered more mobile. 
</P>
<P>
	Brady is a drop-back passer who completed 23 of 36 passes for  
267 yards in his first start last year at Notre Dame. But it was 
Henson who threw the only Michigan touchdown pass in that game. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games involving Top Ten teams Saturday, it's Akron at  
No. 2 Penn State, Wyoming at No. 3 Tennessee, Western Michigan at 
No. 4 Florida, No. 5 Nebraska at Iowa, Florida A&AMP;M at Miami, Murray 
State at No. 9 Wisconsin and No. 10 Georgia Tech at Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee opens defense of its national championship against a  
Wyoming team coming off a solid 8-3 season. Leading the No. 3 
Volunteers will be quarterback Tee Martin and running back Jamal 
Lewis, who had a big freshman season in 1997 but missed most of 
1998 with a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 5 Nebraska is looking to rebound from an injury-plagued 9-4  
season, an off year for the Cornhuskers. The Hawkeyes have a new 
coach in Kirk Ferentz. He succeeds Hayden Fry, who retired after 20 
years at Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be lot of attention on South Carolina's game at North  
Carolina State, with Lou Holtz making his debut as coach of the 
visiting Gamecocks. Holtz, who won more than 100 games before 
leaving Notre Dame after the 1996 season, went 33-12-3 as coach of 
North Carolina State in 1972-75. The Wolfback is coming off an 
upset of Texas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
