<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fires Can Rejuvenate Wilderness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT BALDY VILLAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Flames race up a  
chaparral-covered hillside, leaving behind smoldering, blackened 
bushes and scorched earth eerily absent of animals. 
</P>
<P>
	But this is far from a disaster for the Angeles National Forest.  
</P>
<P>
	After all, dead brush was burned away, and seeds will now have a  
chance to grow in soil enriched by ash. Animals will return to find 
more grazing area, and birds can more easily see their rodent prey. 
</P>
<P>
	From an environmental point of view, wildfires are not  
necessarily a bad thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires such as a still-smoldering 600-acre blaze below towering  
Mount Baldy have always been an important renewing force in the 
West. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wildlife actually benefits from this in the long term,'' said  
Karen Fortus, a resource officer for the U.S. Forest Service. ``It 
opens up areas that animals haven't been able to get to because the 
vegetation was just so thick they couldn't even get through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, policies of fighting every fire have led to thicker  
brush that burns hotter and spreads flames faster. These intense 
fires can create a waterproof crust that causes winter runoff 
problems and keeps nutrients from seeping into the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Agencies like the Forest Service and the National Park Service  
are increasingly using wildfires as a tool to manage resources. 
Some naturally sparked fires in remote areas are allowed to burn. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have that luxury here,'' Fortus said of the Mount  
Baldy fire that burned within miles of housing developments. ``With 
all the improvements and structures we have, it would be very 
politically risky, and personal property is more important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The blaze was ignited in roadside brush by an Aug. 25 car crash.  
The fire spread to within a mile of new developments springing up 
near the 10,080-foot mountain about 50 miles east of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters contained the fire within four days with no  
injuries or property damage. Hot spots were being doused by 
helicopter a week later, when Fortus and wildlife biologist Patti 
Krueger hiked through a canyon that used to be covered in 
chest-high scrub that had not burned since 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Now only the black skeletons of manzanita and chamise chaparral  
dot a landscape painted in gray. 
</P>
<P>
	It looks like everything died, but Krueger and Fortus see life.  
</P>
<P>
	Within months, seeds -- some dropped years ago -- will germinate  
because of the fire's heat. Other plants will simply grow new 
sprouts in soil enriched by nitrates and other nutrients in the 
ash. 
</P>
<P>
	The new growth will attract animals that before could not find  
food in the canyon dense with dead chaparral. Along the edge of the 
fire line, deer and other animals will be hidden from predators by 
unburned growth as they eat the sprouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a day or two after a fire, deer can be seen licking the  
ashes for nutrients. Some roll in the warm ashes, perhaps to kill 
ticks in their hides. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, the next three years are going to be an abundant time  
for wildlife in the area,'' Krueger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Very few animals are found dead as a result of a fire, said  
Richard Minnich, a University of California at Riverside earth 
sciences professor who also toured the fire area. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people think wildlife is devastated by fire,'' he  
said. ``Birds can fly away. Animals can outrun it or burrow into 
the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Angeles National Forest and across the West, rangers  
routinely set fires to clear brush and rejuvenate the soil Such 
``prescription'' burns are often unpopular with nearby residents 
and tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	``California is going to burn, and there's going to be a lot of  
smoke,'' said Barbara Bonefeld, a fire use specialist for the U.S. 
Forest Service. ``It's a question of: Do you want smoke under 
conditions where you can manage it or when you can't?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 20:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underwood Separates Left Shoulder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Unpredictable rookie defensive end  
Dimitrius Underwood dislocated his left shoulder during the Miami 
Dolphins' exhibition game against the Green Bay Packers Thursday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, who disappeared from the Minnesota Vikings' camp last  
month and was picked up by the Dolphins after the Vikings dropped 
him, wasn't expected to play against the Packers. But after 
defensive end Rich Owens went down with bruised ribs, coach Jimmy 
Johnson used Underwood sparingly during the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood apparently suffered the injury late in the third  
quarter after landing hard on the shoulder. He left the field under 
his own power, and moments later the team announced Underwood had 
separated the shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the team changed the diagnosis to a dislocated shoulder.  
</P>
<P>
	Underwood practiced with the Dolphins for the first time on  
Tuesday. He arrived in Florida a day late after missing two flights 
from Michigan, but the Dolphins elected to bring him to Green Bay 
for their final preseason game. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood sacrificed a $1.75 million signing bonus by leaving  
the Vikings, and he's getting a base salary of $395,000 in the 
first season of a five-year contract with Miami. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
