<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Pan Am Coach Misused Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBURG, Texas (AP) -- Pan American basketball coach Delray  
Brooks was fired because the school thinks he deposited a $25,000 
check from a road game into his personal bank account and withdrew 
money from the account, The (McAllen) Monitor reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brooks, in a letter to athletic director Bill Weidner,  
denies the accusation and insists he did nothing wrong, the 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the memo obtained by the newspaper, Brooks said he had not  
met with school officials concerning his dismissal last week. But 
Weidner said he twice met with Brooks to discuss two memos -- a 
notice of intent to dismiss Brooks and a termination letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks did not return a phone call to The Associated Press on  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks is a former assistant coach at Kentucky who helped the  
Wildcats to three Final Four appearances, including the 1996 
national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan Am hired him in 1997 after the school lost its NCAA  
certification in 1996. The certification was fully restored in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks, whose salary was nearly $63,000 last season, went 8-46  
in his first two seasons and was dismissed Aug. 23. The university 
said Brooks was fired because of a police investigation concerning 
the men's basketball team. 
</P>
<P>
	Campus police said they were investigating possible misuse of  
funds. No charges have been filed. 
</P>
<P>
	The school also chose not to renew the contracts of two  
assistant coaches, George Morgan and Patrick Harrington. 
</P>
<P>
	According to an Aug. 20 memo -- the notice of intent to fire  
Brooks -- Weidner accused the coach of depositing a check for 
$25,000 from a game at Southwest Missouri State into his personal 
account. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks then made ``a number of non-university business  
withdrawals against that checking account, including substantial 
cash withdrawals,'' the memo reads. 
</P>
<P>
	In his Aug. 21 response, Brooks denied knowing how the check was  
deposited but promised to find out. 
</P>
<P>
	``In life all you have is your integrity,'' he wrote.  
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 23, Weidner notified Brooks of his termination, taking  
effect the next day. Brooks appealed his firing on Friday with a 
letter to Weidner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not once, has anyone from the university, including my direct  
supervisor, questioned me concerning the investigation of 
allegations,'' he wrote. ``No communication whatsoever. ... I will 
prove my innocence as well as restore my name and my reputation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
