<DOCNO> APW19990902.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 06:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Lifts Some Economy Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's strict controls on  
sending money out of the country have boosted the economy, the 
prime minister said Thursday, a day after lifting a steep tax on 
the repatriation of foreign capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``The unorthodox, bold and strong measures which we took 366  
days ago have borne fruit,'' said Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad 
in a speech to business leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea, Malaysia rebuffed  
bailouts from the International Monetary Fund during the Asian 
currency and stock market collapse in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he locked in portfolio investments for one year, halted  
offshore trading of the ringgit and pegged it at 3.8 to the dollar. 
He subsequently hiked government spending to revive mothballed 
public works projects and sinking companies. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, a part of the controls was lifted, and investors  
became eligible to repatriate their principal without paying taxes. 
But penalties remained on repatriating profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahathir said the capital controls have triggered a stock market  
recovery, rising exports and external reserves, and higher job 
demand. Two weeks ago, the central bank announced the recession was 
over and the economy was set to grow by least by 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts were divided over Mahathir's analysis that currency  
controls alone bailed out Malaysia. 
</P>
<P>
	Amar Bhattacharya, a senior World Bank economist, praised  
Malaysia's recovery but doubted whether Mahathir's prescription 
could become a model path out of recession. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very difficult to isolate capital controls as the only  
(recovery) policy,'' he said. ``It doesn't mean that one policy is 
the answer for the future.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
