<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Opposes Education Vouchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley  
said Thursday that taxpayer-funded vouchers won't solve the problem 
of poor quality schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think school vouchers are the answer to the problems  
of public education,'' he said during a campaign swing through 
Cleveland, where a state-funded voucher program is the subject of a 
court debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said such programs have problems, ``not the least of  
which are issues of church and state,'' that must be resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have to do more with the public school system  
itself,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New Jersey, said he voted  
twice for federally funded experimental voucher programs. Neither 
bill became law. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil liberties and public education groups have challenged a  
state-funded program that gave poor Cleveland students tuition 
vouchers of up to $2,500 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the voucher schools have religious affiliations and  
opponents argue that the program violates the constitutional 
separation of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge halted the program last month, saying it  
appeared to have the ``primary effect of advancing religion.'' But 
he later said the program can remain in place only for students who 
participated last year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Republican presidential candidate and Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush proposed stripping poor-performing schools of 
federal education funds and letting parents spend the money on 
alternative education for their children, including private schools 
and tutoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he would not support Bush's program, but would be  
in favor of giving governors more latitude to spend federal 
education funds in exchange for greater accountability. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
