<HEADLINE> Smith Keeps Up Presidential Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire is  
continuing his independent run for president, dispelling 
speculation last month he might drop his long-shot campaign because 
of his wife's health. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is: I'm still in the race. I'm planning to  
continue as an independent candidate. I'm very excited about it,'' 
Smith told The Associated Press on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	When Smith announced last month he would not be a candidate for  
the U.S. Taxpayers Party, he also hinted the future of his campaign 
was in question because of health concerns about his wife, Mary Jo. 
She was in the hospital for tests after suffering chest and arm 
pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the tests were negative, his wife is fine and he is  
continuing his campaign to try to unify conservatives and other 
voters disenchanted with the political process and two-party 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 13, Smith pulled out of the Republican Party in a  
dramatic speech on the Senate floor because he felt it was not 
living up to its platform on such issues as abortion and gun 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	His first priority is rounding up possibly a quarter of a  
million signatures around the country so his name will appear on 
ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not easy, but we've got thousands of volunteers,'' he  
said. ``I don't know how far it will go, but I will take it as far 
as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's lead over former  
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley is narrowing in New Hampshire, 
according to a poll released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, conducted by Franklin Pierce College in Rindge and  
WNDS-TV in Derry, found that Gore's support has remained steady 
since a similar poll in April, while Bradley's numbers have 
climbed. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 232 Democratic and Democratic-leaning independents, 44  
percent chose Gore to 37 percent for Bradley. Nineteen percent were 
undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 6 percentage  
points. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Gore led Bradley nearly 2-to-1, 40 percent to 21  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The new poll also found Bradley would perform better than Gore  
against Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The 549 voters questioned favored Bush over Gore 48 percent to  
39 percent. But they placed Bradley in a statistical dead heat with 
Bush, trailing 44 percent to 41 percent. The margin of error for 
that part of the poll was plus or minus 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll found that independent voters seem more inclined to  
vote in the Democratic primary than they were in April. In April, 
25 percent of the independents questioned planned to vote in the 
Democratic primary. In Thursday's poll, 36 percent said they would. 
</P>
<P>
	If independents do swing to the Democratic primary, it could be  
a bonus for Bradley. The poll found independents favor Bradley over 
Gore 42 percent to 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush widened his lead among Republicans and Republican-leaning  
independents. He led the field with 48 percent, while John McCain, 
Elizabeth Dole and Steve Forbes lagged with 10 percent each. The 
margin of error for that part of the poll, which had 269 voters, 
was plus or minus 6 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Bush had 35 percent, Dole 15 percent, McCain 9 percent  
and Forbes 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of randomly selected registered voters was conducted  
from Sunday through Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Breaking with almost all of his Ohio  
colleagues, Sen. Mike DeWine on Thursday announced he's backing 
fellow Republican Sen. John McCain of Arizona for the party's 
presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine said he'll make his endorsement official at a Friday  
appearance with McCain in Concord, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	The first-term senator said he believes McCain's experiences,  
particularly his foreign policy knowledge and military background, 
make him most suited to be the GOP nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am endorsing him because I have known him for 17 years and I  
think he would be a great president,'' DeWine said. ``This is the 
man who in my opinion should be commander-in-chief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bob Taft and almost every other Republican official in  
Ohio, and the businesses that finance campaigns in Ohio, are 
backing Texas Gov. George Bush, who grossed $1 million from a 
single Cincinnati fund-raising trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Before DeWine made his choice known, the only prominent  
defection from the solid Bush front was state Treasurer Kenneth 
Blackwell, who is prominent in the campaign of publisher Steve 
Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Still up for grabs: the endorsements of two holdout congressmen,  
Paul Gillmor and Steve Chabot, plus that of the state's junior 
senator, George Voinovich. A spokesman said no Voinovich 
endorsement has been planned. 
  	   	
</P>
