<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets closed lower Thursday on  
various local news, with the large Tokyo market dipping slightly on 
the yen's recent strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 171.23  
points, or 0.96 percent, to 17,631.25. On Wednesday, the average 
had surged 2.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen makes Japanese goods more expensive and less  
competitive overseas, and Japanese exporters lose revenues in terms 
of the Japanese currency. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts said hopes of an economic recovery in Japan  
continued to lift market sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the yen's strength, the market remains comparatively  
strong,'' said Kazunori Jinnai of Daiwa Securities SB Capital 
Markets in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In the currency market, the yen fell back just slightly. The  
U.S. dollar bought 109.42 yen at late afternoon, up 0.20 yen from 
its level of 109.22 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its 
late New York level of 109.05 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong prices fell on losses by market heavyweight HSBC  
Holdings and other financial sector stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark Hang Seng Index fell 176.63 points, or 1.3  
percent, to 13,367.56. On Wednesday, the index had risen 0.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1.8 percent loss by HSBC Holdings -- the market's largest  
capitalized share -- dragged down financial sector blue chips, but 
some analysts said the selloff was too sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market's downward adjustment is unreasonable, particularly  
as it seems to completely ignore a recent slew of good news,'' said 
Sean Li of Amsteel Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the government announced that the Hong Kong economy  
had risen 0.5 percent in the second quarter after 15 months of 
contraction. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares tumbled 1.8 percent on the further weakening of  
the Thai currency, the baht. The SET index lost 7.86 points to end 
at 426.70. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares dropped on concerns over the Bank Bali troubles  
and the East Timor elections. The JSX Composite index were down 
0.66 points, or 0.1 percent, at 571.11 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares tumbled on heavy selling by foreign funds.  
The Composite Index fell 17.39 points, or 2.3 percent, to 735.52 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rose despite losses in BW Resources Corp. and  
Belle Corp. The PSE index was up 6.19 points, or 0.30 percent, at 
2,158.95. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares closed lower as investors cashed in on recent  
gains. The Weighted Price Index was down 47.18 points, or 0.60 
percent, at 8,226.15. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares fell on worries over higher U.S. interest  
rates. The STI dropped 4.13 points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,118.21. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares ended lower, led by losses in industrial sector  
shares. The All Ordinaries Index was down 3.7 points, or 0.10 
percent, at 2,993.7. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares fell on foreign selling triggered by worries over  
Hyundai Group. The Kospi was down 2.55 points, or 0.72 percent, at 
898.97. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on gains by Air New Zealand Ltd. and  
Auckland International Airport Ltd. The NZSE-40 Capital Index was 
up 4.41 points, or 0.20 percent, at 2,154.49. 



</P>
</TEXT>
