<HEADLINE> Conviction in Foster Parents Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONROE, Ga. (AP) -- A 22-year-old man was convicted Thursday of  
killing four members of a family who once took him in while he was 
trying to kick drugs and drinking. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Scott Heidler faces execution for the rampage.  
</P>
<P>
	Jurors cried as they watched a video of the blood-soaked home in  
the town of Santa Claus where Kim Daniels, 33; her husband, Danny, 
47; and their two children, Jessica, 16, and Bryant, 8, died from 
shotgun blasts as they slept Dec. 4, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just went from room to room, shooting,'' Heidler mumbled in  
an interview with police videotaped the day after the killings. ``I 
went berserk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the shooting, Heidler kidnapped the couple's three girls,  
ages 8, 9, and 10, and sexually assaulted one of them. Two boys, 
Corey, 4, and Gabriel, 10 months, were left at the house unharmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the seven children were in foster care. The couple had  
been foster parents and once cared for Heidler's younger sister. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidler had also lived for a time in the home, and the couple  
had brought him with them to church. 
</P>
<P>
	Nic D'Alesandro, a forensic psychologist, testified that Heidler  
had been an alcoholic since 11, began using drugs in his teens, and 
burned himself with cigarettes because it felt good. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury is to decide whether Heidler will get the electric  
chair. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
