<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Eludes Israelis, Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Egypt (AP) -- American and Palestinians converged on  
the Mediterranean resort of Alexandria today to try to salvage a 
Middle East peace agreement, but with Israeli official absent, a 
deal seemed unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	In a display of brinksmanship earlier today in Jerusalem,  
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators who had hammered out agreement 
on series of difficult points refused to budge on one -- the release 
of a few dozen Palestinian prisoners -- that is holding up a revised 
West Bank land-for-security deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Egyptians had hoped to host a signing ceremony between  
Israelis and Palestinians in Alexandria in the presence of U.S. 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who arrived here this 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said Albright was prepared to intervene to  
resolve the deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she feels this is a good deal for both sides and it  
would be a shame if it were lost,'' said a senior Clinton 
administration official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian negotiators Saeb Erekat and Mohammed Dahlan headed  
to Alexandria this afternoon, summoned by Palestinian leader Yasser 
Arafat, who arrived earlier for talks with Egyptian President Hosni 
Mubarak. 
</P>
<P>
	The office of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, said the  
premier had no immediate plans to travel to Alexandria. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. administration had billed Albright's Mideast tour not  
as a mediating visit, but as a stocktaking trip, perhaps even an 
opportunity to move on from the Israeli-Palestinian track to try to 
revive long-stalled Israeli talks with Syria. 
</P>
<P>
	State-run Damascus radio urged Albright to be forceful.  
</P>
<P>
	``The announced goal of Albright's tour is to push the peace  
process forward. This necessitates an active American role,'' said 
the broadcast. Albright is expected in Damascus on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	At first glance, the gaps between the Israelis and the  
Palestinians appeared easily solved, considering that both sides 
have already spent weeks in grueling negotiations to revise the Wye 
River interim agreement that was signed in October at the White 
House. They have compromised on difficult issues, such as a new 
timetable for Israeli troop pullbacks in the West Bank and a new 
deadline for a permanent peace accord -- September 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding Palestinian prisoners, Israel has offered to free 356  
held for anti-Israeli activities, while the Palestinians sought the 
release of 400. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel has said principles were at stake and that it would not  
release Palestinians who killed Israelis. Israeli Justice Minister 
Yossi Beilin said Israel would not budge on the criteria it has set 
for the release of prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Beilin, a veteran of negotiations with the Palestinians, said  
Israel was serious about making peace with the Palestinians and was 
not worried about delays. ``If it takes a couple more days (to 
negotiate), it's not the end of the world,'' Beilin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the emerging deal, Israel would withdraw from another 11  
percent of the West Bank in three stages, starting at the beginning 
of September and ending Jan. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations on a permanent peace agreement would begin  
immediately after the first pullback. Within five months of the 
start of negotiations, Israelis and Palestinians would complete a 
framework agreement on the so-called final status issues, such as 
the fate of Palestinian refugees, Palestinian statehood and the 
future of Jewish settlements. A final agreement would be completed 
within a year of the start of the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak has said that if the Palestinians don't accept the revised  
accord, he will implement the Wye agreement to the letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Palestinians initially demanded an exact  
implementation of Wye, they would apparently prefer the 
renegotiated version, because they would get more land sooner and 
would win the release of more security prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised agreement also gives the Palestinians the go-ahead  
to build a port in Gaza City and sets dates for the opening of land 
routes connecting the West Bank and Gaza. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel, in turn, benefits because the agreement defuses the  
potential threat of a unilateral Palestinian declaration of 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Each side blamed the other for the last-minute snag. Barak  
spokesman David Ziso said Israel was still waiting for answers from 
the Palestinians. Palestinian negotiator Erekat said it was up to 
Israel to pick up the phone. 
</P>
<P>
	Tempers were frayed in the last round of talks Wednesday.  
Shouting could occasionally be heard throughout the corridors 
outside the conference room. Repeated calls were made to Egyptian 
leaders. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
