<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Florida Court Upholds Term Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida voters knew what they were  
doing when they changed the constitution to limit state politicians 
to eight years in office, the state Supreme Court said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court's decision to uphold the term limits amendment  
means more than a third of the Legislature's 160 members will be 
barred from seeking re-election in November 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Term limits also apply to the state's six elected Cabinet  
officers. The governor was already limited to two successive 
four-year terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Five people challenged the amendment, approved by 77 percent of  
voters in 1992, saying voters were really seeking to oust career 
politicians in Congress -- not state officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the attention at that time was focused on Washington,  
they argued, and voters were persuaded to approve the amendment 
because of disgust with federal lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	After the U.S. Supreme Court threw out federal term limits, the  
five voters challenged the remaining term limits on state 
politicians. They argued that voters never meant to deprive 
themselves of the right to vote repeatedly for their state 
representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida court, in an unsigned, unanimous opinion, wrote that  
the challengers ``failed to establish that the voters' purpose ... 
was only to limit terms of federal officeholders and the voters 
would not have approved the term limits amendment if only state 
officeholders had been included.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challengers also claimed the amendment was unfair to rural  
voters who don't have as much representation in the Legislature as 
urban residents who have large delegations. The court also rejected 
that claim. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
