<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 08:26:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bird's Future With Pacers Unclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Larry Bird never promised the Indiana Pacers  
he would coach more than three years. 
</P>
<P>
	And that means the Hall of Famer's plans are unclear after next  
season. Bird could stay with the team beyond that, although it 
might put Donnie Walsh out of a job. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the end of his contract,'' Walsh, the team's president,  
said Wednesday. ``He hasn't come in and definitely told me that, 
but I've always known it was a three-year deal, and at the end of 
it he was going to make up his mind whether he wanted to coach or 
not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh's comments came a day after it was disclosed the  
42-year-old coach has had periodic bouts of irregular heartbeat. 
Bird is watching his diet and taking medication to treat atrial 
fibrillation, which is not life threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird was not available for comment Wednesday, and it was not  
clear if the possibility of his leaving coaching was tied to his 
heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	When he came to the Pacers in 1997, he acquired a minority  
ownership of the team and said he didn't expect to coach long. 
Walsh said he would step aside if Bird wants his job in the front 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd talk to the owners about that, I'd talk to Larry about  
that,'' Walsh said. ``If the best thing would be for me to leave 
the team, I'd leave the team. But we haven't really gotten into 
that yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird first experienced heart trouble late in his career with the  
Boston Celtics, and Walsh said he knew about the condition when he 
hired Bird in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``In effect, it was a matter of finding the level of the  
medicine in order to have his heart beat regularly. Once they found 
that, it seemed to me it was OK and he didn't have any more 
problems,'' Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Globe reported Wednesday that Bird indicated to Walsh  
the 1999-00 season would be his last as coach. Walsh told The 
Associated Press he never talked to Bird specifically about that, 
although he has been aware of that possibility all along. 
</P>
<P>
	``In dealing with Larry for the last two years, from the very  
beginning, he only committed to coach for three years,'' Walsh 
said. ``But he's going to coach this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've also spoken to him about continuing on as general  
manager, president, whatever you want to call it. So we'll continue 
to talk about that. But we really haven't sat down and had a 
definite discussion about this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird, who had never coached basketball at any level, was the NBA  
coach of the year in his first season with Indiana in 1998, when 
the Pacers were a franchise-record 58-24 and reached the Eastern 
Conference finals. Last season, shortened to 50 games by the league 
lockout, the Pacers were 33-17, won the Central Division 
championship and again reached the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird's heart ailment was disclosed in an excerpt in this week's  
Sports Illustrated from his upcoming book, ``Bird Watching: On 
Playing and Coaching the Game I Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew there was something wrong with my heart,'' Bird  
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would feel sudden exhaustion and his heart would  
start ``jumping around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bird was put on medication and told to exercise, eat healthy and  
drink alcohol only in moderation. But his condition worsened in the 
spring of 1997, right before he became the Pacers' coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got a little scared because it didn't seem like it was going  
away,'' Bird wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	His condition is not as serious as ventricular fibrillation,  
which doctors believed caused the death of former Celtics teammate 
Reggie Lewis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
