<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 53 Deaths in Heart Drug Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A study of an experimental drug to treat  
congestive heart failure was halted earlier this year after 53 
patients taking the medication died in the first six months, drug 
maker Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	There were nearly twice as many deaths among patients taking the  
drug than among patients taking a placebo, Lilly said. 
</P>
<P>
	A different formulation of the Lilly drug is sold under the name  
Cynt, and used in Europe and Asia to treat high blood pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	Indianapolis-based Lilly was studying the drug, a form of  
moxonidine, with Solvay SA, a Belgium firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The clinical trial, in which the drug was to be tested on at  
least 4,000 patients, began in August 1998 and was supposed to last 
two years. The trial tested a sustained-release formulation of the 
drug, meaning it was designed to be absorbed into the body slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	But the trial was halted in February after 82 deaths-- of which  
53 had taken the drug and 29 took a placebo-- occurred among the 
first 2,000 patients who were enrolled. The study was being 
conducted at medical facilities around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly had said last March that the study was being halted, but  
did not provide details at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly spokesman Ed West said the deaths were unfortunate but not  
unusual considering the severity of the patients' illnesses. It's 
unclear whether the drug hastened the patients' deaths, West added. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is no longer studying the drug for congestive heart  
failure. 
</P>
<P>
	West said Lilly has not sought to get U.S. approval for Cynt  
because it does not have any advantages over existing high blood 
pressure pills on the market. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
