<HEADLINE> Four Suspended and Fined by AL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cleveland designated hitter David Justice,  
Anaheim pitcher Troy Percival, Toronto reliever Paul Spoljaric and 
Minnesota infielder Cristian Guzman were all suspended for three 
games and fined $500 Thursday by the American League. 
</P>
<P>
	Percival and Guzman appealed the penalties, which were to begin  
Friday. Justice will decide Friday whether he will appeal. 
Spoljaric began serving his penalty Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Percival hit Justice with a pitch Tuesday night after the  
Indians rallied from an eight-run deficit in the eighth inning. 
Justice charged the mound and flung his helmet and hit the Anaheim 
reliever. Spoljaric was ejected Tuesday night for throwing at 
Guzman, who also charged. 
</P>
<P>
	For the players appealing, no penalty can start until after AL  
president Gene Budig holds a hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice, who had never been thrown out of a game in his career  
before Tuesday night's brawl, said he was afraid Budig would give 
him a stiffer penalty because of the helmet throwing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it might be more,'' Justice said Thursday night  
before the Indians played the Angels. ``When I heard three, I 
thought, that's not too bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove was also expecting Justice to be  
handed a longer suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised it was only three days, but I've very  
thankful,'' Hargrove said. ``I think it was the right decision.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
