<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fleet, BankBoston Plan Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Department of Justice has approved a plan by  
Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. to sell off more 
than 300 bank branches to resolve antitrust concerns about their 
upcoming merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleet has been working to complete a takeover of BankBoston, and  
the approval of the Justice Department gets the plan over an 
important regulatory hurdle. 
</P>
<P>
	The two banks have agreed to sell $13.2 billion in deposits in  
306 branch offices in Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island 
and Connecticut. The Justice Department said the sale was the 
largest divestiture in bank merger history. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said the branches will be sold to one large buyer,  
with the exception of 28 branches and $810 million in deposits that 
will go to small Massachusetts banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the agency did not identify the large buyer,  
Massachusetts Attorney General Tom Reilly said Sovereign Bancorp 
Inc. of Wyomissing, Pa., was working toward finalizing a deal with 
Fleet and BankBoston. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleet spokesman James Mahoney said that Thursday's decision set  
the stage for what he said would be a consumer-friendly 
divestiture. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think the plan assures ongoing competition and choices for  
consumers in the New England market,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Mahoney nor representatives from BankBoston or Sovereign  
commented on reports that the Pennsylvania bank planned to move 
into New England. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing is official until it comes out on Sovereign Bancorp  
letterhead,'' said Missy Orlando, a Sovereign spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Sovereign Bancorp Inc. has $24.6 billion in assets and more than  
310 community banking and loan offices in eastern Pennsylvania, New 
Jersey and Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleet, the nation's ninth-largest bank, has $69.7 billion in  
deposits and $104.4 billion in assets. BankBoston, the country's 
15th-biggest bank, has $48.5 billion in deposits and $73.5 billion 
in deposits. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, which would create the nation's eighth-largest bank,  
still needs the approval of the Federal Reserve Board. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0262 </DOCNO>
