<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Defenseman Ludwig Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Dallas Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig  
has retired after 17 years in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great ride, and I'm ready to step into another part  
of life,'' Ludwig said. 
</P>
<P>
	He told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram he will be a scout in the  
Stars' organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars had told him that he would not be offered a new  
contract for next season. He had talks with the Chicago Blackhawks 
and Detroit Red Wings about a contract to play another year, but he 
said he decided against joining another team because he felt he 
would be ``betraying'' the Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	So, he took the front-office job with the Stars.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think what it came down to was I really wanted to be a part  
of this organization and continue to build what they're building 
here,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 38-year-old Ludwig played on two Stanley Cup champion teams,  
the 1986 Montreal Canadiens and last year's Stars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 14:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals Sign Leeuwenburg, Groce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Center Jay Leeuwenburg signed a one-year  
contract with the Cincinnati Bengals on Thursday, two days after he 
was released by the Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals also brought back fullback Clif Groce, whom they  
waived on Monday, by agreeing to a three-year contract. Fullback 
Nicky Sualua, who's been hampered by a strained knee ligament, 
agreed to an injury settlement and was waived. 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenburg, 30, was the Colts' most experienced offensive  
lineman. He started 37 consecutive games for the Colts and made 
every offensive snap last year for a line that allowed only 22 
sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenburg lost his job during training camp to second-year pro  
Larry Moore, prompting the Colts to release him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals have been trying to solidify their chronically weak  
offensive line and add to its depth. They added free agent guards 
Brian DeMarco and Matt O'Dwyer in the offseason and moved Rich 
Braham to center. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
