<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Machinists Approve Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Machinists went to work today with a  
freshly approved contract that union members say signals a new era 
of mutual respect between company management and hourly workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact won 86 percent approval Wednesday night, the highest  
ever for a Boeing contract, union negotiator Dick Schneider told a 
cheering crowd after the votes were tallied. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been invited on a great journey by (Boeing chairman)  
Phil Condit,'' Schneider said. ``That invitation was to take this 
company into the next century in partnership. ... We have 
accepted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 26,842 to 4,328, with a 71 percent turnout from the  
44,000 members of the International Association of Machinists and 
Aerospace Workers in Washington, Oregon and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit, who stepped in personally to end a prickly bargaining  
stalemate last weekend, lobbied hard for acceptance, telling union 
members the contract ``offers unprecedented job security, the best 
wages and retirement plan in the industry, and world-class 
benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Machinists interviewed outside polling places called the pact  
``a miracle'' and a morale-booster. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the climate in the business world right now, the  
competition with Airbus, the workers at Boeing got some recognition 
for their hard efforts,'' said Jeffrey Tazioli, who assembles wings 
for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The old contract was to expire at 12:01 a.m. today. The  
Machinists went on strike over two of the last three contracts, 
most recently for 69 days in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing, the nation's No. 1 exporter, plans to deliver a record  
620 commercial planes this year. Meanwhile, a fierce rivalry with 
the European consortium Airbus Industrie has prompted a push to 
streamline operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure to keep producing helped bring negotiators  
together. The company dropped its demands for a seven-day work week 
and more worker contributions to health-insurance premiums. It 
offered two annual wage increases of 4 percent and a third-year 3 
percent raise, as well as a 10 percent signing bonus worth $4,400 
to the average machinist. 
</P>
<P>
	``This contract was probably the best we've ever gotten,'' said  
Victor Hebert, a 737 quality inspector in Renton. 
</P>
<P>
	The only opposition to the agreement focused on retirement  
benefits and job security. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing offered a 25 percent increase in pensions, to $50 a month  
per year of service -- well below the 300 percent increase sought by 
the union. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract offer also guaranteed ``no layoffs as the direct  
result of subcontracting or offloading,'' but exempted ``commercial 
airplane strategic work placement requirements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders at the company and the union said the exemption covers  
work allocated to foreign workers as a condition of winning 
aircraft orders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
