<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects Held in Georgia Slaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After being stripped, beaten with rocks and  
sticks and thrown down a ravine, 17-year-old Krystal Archer begged 
her three attackers to leave her alone. As she clung desperately to 
a tree, they set her hair on fire, pushed her down the ravine again 
and left her to die. 
</P>
<P>
	Battered and unable to walk, Miss Archer survived in the ravine  
for four days. But her attackers -- including her boyfriend -- 
returned again and again, each time hitting her with sticks and 
rocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, they returned to ``finish her off,'' police said,  
stabbing her several times and slitting her throat. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects were identified as Timothy Curtis Cole, 21, and  
Michael Christopher Teal, 19, both of Covington, and Danielle 
Hubbard, 18, of Athens. They were arrested Tuesday night and were 
being held in Madison, about 50 miles east of Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison County Sheriff Ken Pritchett said Thursday that one of  
the men, whom he would not identify, confessed to stabbing Miss 
Archer and slitting her throat. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were charged with felony murder and aggravated assault  
after Miss Archer's boyfriend, Cole, led authorities to the crime 
scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Pritchett, the sheriff's brother and deputy chief, said  
Teal and Miss Hubbard were dating and Cole and Miss Archer were 
dating. Miss Hubbard thought Miss Archer was ``eyeing her 
boyfriend,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence began when the two females began fighting in the  
woods. The fight escalated and the two men became involved. Over 
the next three or four hours, Miss Archer was stripped and forced 
to commit various acts, including sexual acts to her own body, 
Pritchett said. 
</P>
<P>
	She was hit with rocks and sticks. Three times, they threw her  
about 20 feet down into the ravine, which has about 2 feet of 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was completely unclothed holding a small tree, begging  
them to leave her alone,'' Pritchett said. ``That's when one of 
them walked up and lit her hair on fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the third time, Miss Archer fell unconscious. The next day  
the three returned and found Miss Archer alive but unconscious. 
</P>
<P>
	``They beat her again with sticks and rocks and piled brush on  
top of her so she wouldn't be found,'' Pritchett said. 
</P>
<P>
	When Miss Archer's attackers returned on the third day, they  
threw rocks into the ravine, trying to hit her in the head and 
``finish her off,'' Pritchett said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the fourth day they returned with a butcher's knife from Miss  
Hubbard's parents' house. Miss Archer was still alive -- and awake. 
She had dragged herself about 15 yards and propped herself up. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the men stabbed her five or six times in the chest and  
neck and then slit her throat, Pritchett said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
