<DOCNO> APW19990902.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Suspect Tried in Immigrant Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Prosecutors may not be able to use their star  
witness in the case against a self-proclaimed white supremacist who 
admitted that he killed a West African immigrant at a bus stop 
because he was black. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathan Thill, 21, is accused of shooting Oumar Dia to death and  
paralyzing Jeannie VanVelkinburgh as she came to Dia's aid. 
</P>
<P>
	The first trial in the case ended with the murder conviction of  
Thill's companion, Jeremiah Barnum. Ms. VanVelkinburgh's testimony 
helped convict him, even though she cried from her wheelchair, 
screamed at Barnum, belched loudly and sometimes refused to answer 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	But in July, a judge overturned the verdict, ruling that the  
trial judge failed to control Ms. Van Velkinburgh on the stand and 
jeopardized Barnum's right to a fair trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are appealing the decision, but with jury selection  
for Thill's trial scheduled to begin Friday, they would not comment 
on whether they plan to call Ms. VanVelkinburgh again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just trying to prosecute the case fairly,'' prosecutor  
Chuck Lepley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys did not return a telephone call seeking  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal analyst Andrew Cohen, a Denver attorney, noted prosecutors  
must decide whether Ms. VanVelkinburgh's testimony is crucial to 
their case. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is a witness who brings a lot to the prosecution ... but  
her credibility is in doubt and she might bring in a big risk,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thill could get the death penalty if convicted of ethnic  
intimidation, murder and attempted murder. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Senegal, the slightly statured Dia was a hotel  
bellhop who sent his earnings home to support his family and fellow 
villagers. 
</P>
<P>
	After leaving work on Nov. 19, 1997, Dia, was waiting at a  
downtown bus stop along with Ms. VanVelkinburgh when Thill and 
Barnum approached. 
</P>
<P>
	Thill knocked a baseball cap from Dia's head, called him a  
racial epithet and asked him whether he was prepared to die, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. VanVelkinburgh has testified that Barnum put Dia in a  
headlock and told him he did not belong in downtown's ``white 
territory.'' She said Thill pulled out a gun and shot Dia several 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	When she tried to intervene, Ms. VanVelkinburgh said Thill shot  
her in the spine, pointed the gun at her head and pulled the 
trigger twice. 
</P>
<P>
	The weapon was empty.  
</P>
<P>
	After his arrest, Thill told reporters, police and prosecutors  
that he shot Dia because he was black. Thill acknowledged in news 
interviews that he was a white supremacist and Dia, in his 
bellhop's apparel, was ``in the enemy's uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denver District Judge Federico Alvarez has said Thill's  
statements to police can't be used during the trial because he was 
not properly advised of his constitutional rights. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he said Thill's statements to the media may be used  
because Thill sought out reporters voluntarily. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 16:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trinidad Sees De La Hoya Knockout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAJARDO, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Felix Trinidad made a final promise  
to his countrymen before leaving Puerto Rico for the biggest fight 
of his career: An early knockout of Oscar De La Hoya. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in the best physical condition of my life, and I can't see  
how De La Hoya could end the fight on his feet,'' Trinidad said 
Thursday. ``I'm going to knock him out after the sixth round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad made the comments at a news conference at the El  
Conquistador Resort, his last appearance on the island before 
leaving Saturday to finish training in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The two undefeated champions will fight Sept. 18 in a  
welterweight unification bout at the Mandalay Bay Hotel in Las 
Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad, the IBF champion, is 35-0 with 30 knockouts. De La  
Hoya holds the WBC title and is 31-0 with 25 knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I put my hands on a boxer he falls, and De La Hoya will  
be no exception,'' Trinidad said. ``He won't be able to take the 
punishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Promoter Don King was in Puerto Rico to support Trinidad.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see anyone who could beat Tito (Trinidad). He's going  
to knock out De La Hoya in six rounds,'' King said. ``What I'm most 
interested in is that De La Hoya gets into the ring, doesn't get 
sick, or even a bruise, before the fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad is guaranteed $8.5 million for the fight, while De La  
Hoya will earn $15 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Darryl Hitless in First Game Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There were no majestic home runs from Darryl  
Strawberry in his comeback. Not even a base hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a couple of strikeouts and a walk for the New York Yankees  
slugger in his first game back from colon cancer and a drug 
suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always look for the situation to do something dramatic,''  
Strawberry said Thursday after the Yankees beat the Oakland 
Athletics 9-3. ``It just wasn't one of those days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's fourth comeback in five years with the Yankees  
began with warm applause from the 33,147 fans, who remember the 
dramatic homers and the role Strawberry played on two World Series 
champions. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's first major league at-bat since last Sept. 27, came  
leading off the second inning against Gil Heredia and offered no 
new memories. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry took a big cut at the first pitch, fouling it back  
onto the screen. After taking a called second strike and then a 
ball, Strawberry checked his swing on a fastball that nipped the 
outside corner. 
</P>
<P>
	John Shulock called him out and Strawberry walked back to the  
dugout after a brief discussion of the call. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take some at-bats for me to make the  
adjustments,'' Strawberry said. ``When you haven't played at this 
level for this long, it takes more than one day to get back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry walked on five pitches in the third inning and was  
erased on a double-play grounder by Jorge Posada. 
</P>
<P>
	With a man on second and one out in the fifth, Oakland manager  
brought in left-hander Ron Mahay. Strawberry looked overmatched 
this time, again striking out on four pitches. He waved at strike 
three. 
</P>
<P>
	Chili Davis pinch-hit for Strawberry in the sixth.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was really good to be back, with all the guys pulling for  
me,'' Strawberry said. ``It was a good day overall for the club. We 
won the game. That's the most important thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next month will be a test for Strawberry, as manager Joe  
Torre determines whether Strawberry can contribute in the 
postseason. He will get at-bats as a pinch-hitter and a few chances 
to start at DH or in left field as Torre rests his regulars down 
the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``He feels comfortable and it's just a matter of getting him  
at-bats,'' Torre said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990902.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 22:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
