<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Human Smuggling Can Be Dangerous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. (AP) -- Death is the ultimate price refugees  
pay when they entrust their lives to smugglers, say new public 
service announcements to be broadcast throughout southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Border Patrol agents on Wednesday announced the campaign, which  
is aimed at reducing the number of Cubans, Haitians and other 
refugees who risk their lives by paying smugglers to bring them to 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since 1993, there have been more than 140 confirmed deaths of  
Cuban and Haitian migrants during attempted ocean crossings'' said 
Michael Sheehy of the Border Patrol. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents hope the U.S.-based relatives of migrants will take heed  
when they see the ominous scenes of people struggling in rough surf 
or listen to a somber radio spot detailing the dangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Gov. Frank Brogan characterized the smugglers as criminals  
who care only about making money. 
</P>
<P>
	``They treat people as nothing more than human cargo,'' he said.  
``They do not care at all about the lives of the desperate people 
they put on rafts and into small boats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spots in English, Spanish and Creole were sent to 55  
television stations and 100 radio stations. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the Immigration and Naturalization Service formed an  
anti-smuggling task force to focus on the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard has added two additional cutters to patrol the  
waters off the Florida Keys. The agency has stopped 1,181 migrants 
at sea this year, compared with 1,047 all of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Border Patrol has apprehended about 2,628 people since its  
fiscal year began last Oct. 1, compared with 1,041 refugees 
apprehended during the first 11 months of the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight people were convicted of alien smuggling last year  
compared with 43 since Oct. 1, agents said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
