<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Sign Wing Tom Chorske </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Tom Chorske, who played 26 games for three NHL  
teams last season, was one of three forwards signed Thursday by the 
Pittsburgh Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins open training camp Saturday, a day after new owner  
Mario Lemieux's takeover of the team is expected to be approved in 
U.S. Bankruptcy Court. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz has set a 9 a.m. hearing  
Friday to finalize the paperwork of a transaction that took nearly 
10 months to complete. Lemieux's purchase was approved Wednesday by 
the NHL Board of Governors. 
</P>
<P>
	Chorske, 32, was an unrestricted free agent who had three  
assists last season while playing for the New York Islanders, 
Washington Capitals and Vancouver Canucks. He has 114 goals and 117 
assists in 563 career NHL games. 
</P>
<P>
	Also signed were Greg Crozier, 23, who played with Michigan of  
the Central Collegiate Hockey Association last season, and Dylan 
Gyori, 20, a forward with Tri-City of the Western Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	Crozier was the Penguins' third-round pick in the 1994 entry  
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins have invited 63 players to camp.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
