<HEADLINE> Johnson Will 'Let Loose' in 200M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Although Maurice Greene won the 200  
meters at the world championships, Michael Johnson is intent on 
proving he is still the fastest at that distance. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, the 400-meter world record finally his, promised  
Thursday to ``let loose'' in the 200 at tonight's Van Damme meet 
and establish himself again as the favorite to retain his Olympic 
title in Sydney next year. 
</P>
<P>
	After years of chasing the 400 world record, he finally  
succeeded in Seville, Spain, defending his world championship title 
and setting a world mark of 43.18 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	He planned to run his first post-Seville race in the 200 at the  
Van Damme. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually when I run a good 400, a good 200 will follow,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not predict, however, that he would challenge his world  
record of 19.32 seconds in the 200. Surpassing the season's best of 
19.84 by Nigerian Francis Obikwelu would suit him just fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``My coach and I decided we are not going to think about any  
particular time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene won the Seville 200 title in 19.90, only the fifth-best  
time of the year. With a personal best of 19.86, there are 10 
runners ahead of him on the all-time list. Johnson has five times 
among the top dozen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would bet on me,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Certainly, everyone is expecting Johnson to win at the Van  
Damme, the sixth of seven Golden League meets. Greene decided to 
sidestep the event in the King Baudouin stadium, known for its fast 
curves, and race in Britain instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The absence of Greene put some of the focus on the men's 800 and  
women's 3,000, where Dane Wilson Kipketer and Romania's Gabriela 
Szabo have their eyes on a $1 million Golden League bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The two champions have won all five Golden League meets so far,  
and if they continue their streak through the Van Damme and 
Tuesday's ISTAF Berlin meet, they will end up with $500,000 each as 
the overall jackpot would be sliced in half. 
</P>
<P>
	Steeplechase world record holder Bernard Barmasai also won his  
five races so far, but the IAAF kicked him out of the jackpot 
competition. He planned to run tonight, bent on winning his two 
remaining races to prove a point. Afterwards, he said he might sue 
the IAAF if the share of the jackpot is denied him. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF punished Barmasai for saying he colluded with a rival  
to determine the outcome of the Golden League race in Zurich. 
Barmasai denied he tried to fix the race. 
</P>
<P>
	American 100-meter world champion Marion Jones was the only  
other athlete with a perfect 5-for-5 performance, but the sprinter 
has not recovered from the back injury suffered during the 
semifinals of the women's 200 in Seville last week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
