<HEADLINE> Clinton Fund-Raiser Backs House Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Golf buddy and political financier Terry  
McAuliffe has raised money for Bill Clinton's White House campaigns 
and presidential library, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's 
Senate bid and the couple's legal defense fund. 
</P>
<P>
	And now he's helping them share once again in the great American  
dream -- owning their own home. 
</P>
<P>
	McAuliffe is putting up $1.35 million as collateral to guarantee  
the money the Clintons are borrowing to buy their first home of 
their own since at least the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and Mrs. Clinton signed a contract Thursday to buy  
a $1.7 million house in Westchester County, about an hour north of 
New York City, and will put up the $350,000 down payment out of 
their own money. 
</P>
<P>
	McAuliffe -- a former investment banker who made a fortune in  
home building, telecommunications and title insurance -- is an 
important member of Clinton's inner circle, politically and 
personally. 
</P>
<P>
	He was national finance chairman of the Clinton-Gore campaign in  
1996 and co-chaired Clinton's inauguration the next year. He heads 
the effort to raise $125 million for the Clinton presidential 
library to be built in Arkansas and advised Mrs. Clinton when she 
was first considering a run for the Senate from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1996 election, Clinton asked McAuliffe to chair the  
Democratic National Committee. McAuliffe turned him down, in part, 
it was said, because of the controversy over fund raising and the 
record amounts collected by, among others, McAuliffe. A 
well-publicized McAuliffe memo was blamed by many for the access 
that later-embarrassing political donors had to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	But he remained a close personal friend of Clinton and his wife  
and was often a member of the president's weekend golf foursomes. A 
native of Syracuse, the has been with the Clintons nearly all this 
week during their vacation in upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you this -- I have no closer friends than the  
president and first lady,'' McAuliffe said Thursday night at a 
fund-raiser one of his friends from kindergarten was hosting for 
Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	McAuliffe also has helped Vice President Al Gore raise money,  
and was the chief fund-raiser for House Minority Leader Dick 
Gephardt in his 1988 bid for the White House. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
