<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plantiffs Win 50 Percent of Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Individuals seeking damages in civil lawsuits  
had slightly better than a 50-50 chance of winning in cases 
resolved by a jury or a judge, according to government statistics 
released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs made up 52 percent of the winners in the 15,638 civil  
cases in 1996 that were decided by a jury or in bench trials. The 
cases, from the nation's 75 largest counties, were examined by the 
Justice Department's Bureau of Justice Statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs in contract disputes enjoyed the most success,  
winning 62 percent of their cases. People who sued in tort cases 
such automobile accidents, vandalism and for medical malpractice 
won their cases 48 percent of the time. Plaintiffs in trials based 
on property lawsuits won 32 percent of the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, plaintiffs won 49 percent of jury trials during 1996,  
slightly less than the 52 percent who won their cases in 1992. 
Plaintiffs won 62 percent of cases decided by a judge in 1996. Data 
for bench trials was not collected in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Most civil cases are resolved before they reach the trial level,  
but the data from trial cases provided details about money awarded 
as damages. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, plaintiffs from the 75 largest counties who won their  
cases were awarded about $3 billion in compensatory and punitive 
damages. Slightly more than $2 billion was awarded in tort cases 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of all plaintiffs who won their cases were awarded $33,000  
or more. About 16 percent won more than $250,000 in total damages 
and an estimated 6 percent were awarded $1 million or more. 
</P>
<P>
	In several types of cases, such as in medical malpractice and  
employment discrimination, jurors were more likely than judges to 
award damages of at least $1 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
