<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Record Number Held Back in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- More than 21,000 students in the nation's  
largest school system will be forced to repeat a grade because they 
failed tests at the end of summer school, didn't take the required 
tests or never attended the summer classes at all. 
</P>
<P>
	When summer school results were first announced on Aug. 20,  
School Chancellor Rudy Crew said most of the children who attended 
summer school had passed their tests and would move on to the next 
grade. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, officials revealed that 14,000 of the 35,000  
students who had been told to attend summer school skipped the 
tests or never showed up at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were trying to funnel the information as we got it,'' said  
Karen Crowe, a Crew spokeswoman. ``There was nothing sinister 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1.1 million-student school system doesn't have a  
computerized system for tracking summer school attendance, Crew 
aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew said Wednesday he will stand by his decision to fail the  
students -- more than 7,000 who failed the tests and the 14,000 who 
never attended summer school or dropped out before taking the 
tests. He has been a critic of social promotion, the practice of 
promoting students within their age group even if they are failing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The answer has to be very swift,'' Crew said. ``If you fail to  
go, if you take and ultimately do not pass the test, you will be 
held back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
